{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777759415807,"sessionID":"ses_2154958d3ffePO2jmYLnAOPepB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EjFLUTaA2CxnpfeiFMPPqR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\ntitle: \"Early JAL redirect in ID stage — save 1 bubble per unconditional jump\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  CoreMark is function-call heavy (matrix_test, core_state_transition,\n  core_list_find, crcu8, list_*, etc. all invoke subroutines). Every JAL\n  currently costs TWO pipeline bubbles because the jump is resolved in\n  EX (flushing IF and ID). But JAL is fully decodable at the ID stage:\n  the target is `pc + J-immediate`, with no register dependency and no\n  condition to evaluate. Resolving it one stage earlier shaves one\n  bubble per call — measurable on a call-heavy workload — without\n  touching the Fmax-critical ALU path, the multiplier, or the\n  forwarding network. Current Fmax (135.21 MHz) is already at target,\n  so an IPC-only improvement translates directly to fitness gain.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add an ID-stage JAL early-redirect path. Concretely:\n\n  1. In id_stage, compute `jal_target = pc + J-imm` combinationally\n     whenever the decoded instruction is a JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr &&\n     !is_illegal && valid && no flush). Drive a new `redirect_id` /\n     `redirect_id_target` pair up to if_stage and the hazard unit.\n  2. In if_stage, give EX redirect priority over ID redirect (EX's\n     resolved branch/JALR is the ground-truth mispredict path), and\n     give ID redirect priority over the default pc+4.\n  3. In hazard_unit, a new `redirect_id` signal triggers `flush_if`\n     (NOP into the IF/ID bundle) — flushing ONE stage instead of two\n     since the JAL itself is now in ID and will propagate normally to\n     EX/MEM/WB so the rd=PC+4 writeback still happens.\n  4. Add a `predicted` bit to id_ex_t and ex_mem_t. When ID issues\n     early redirect, the JAL propagates with `predicted=1`. In\n     ex_stage, the EX redirect fires only when either (a) the\n     instruction is NOT predicted, or (b) the predicted target\n     disagrees with the EX-resolved target (defensive — should never\n     trigger for JAL since both use pc+J-imm). This keeps JALR and\n     BRANCH flushes unchanged (their `predicted=0` stays).\n  5. JAL writeback (rd=PC+4), misaligned-jump trap detection, and\n     RVFI pc_wdata semantics remain exactly where they are today (in\n     EX stage); invariants 2/4/5 unaffected because the retirement\n     stream and trap discipline don't move.\n  6. On EX-stage misprediction (which shouldn't happen for JAL but\n     the defensive check covers it), fall back to full 2-stage flush\n     exactly like today — no regression path weakening.\n\n  Expected effect: every JAL saves exactly one cycle. CoreMark's\n  inner loops contain ~several JALs per iteration through function\n  calls; empirically 2–5% IPC improvement is realistic. The added\n  logic is tiny (one 32-bit adder + one mux in ID, one extra bit on\n  pipeline registers), well off the ALU/multiplier critical path, so\n  Fmax should hold at ~135 MHz. No decoder changes — the existing\n  JAL recognition feeds the new logic unchanged.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `predicted` bit to id_ex_t and ex_mem_t pipeline bundles so the EX stage can distinguish JALs already redirected by ID from fresh control flow.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute jal_target = pc + J-imm combinationally for JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr). Emit redirect_id + redirect_id_target to core.sv. Latch ctrl.predicted=1 into the ID/EX register when early redirect fires.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Accept a second redirect input (redirect_id, redirect_id_target). Priority: EX redirect > ID redirect > pc+4. Emit NOP on either redirect kind (existing flush path already does this via if_stage's flush input).\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Suppress redirect when the in-flight JAL arrives with predicted=1 AND its EX-computed target matches the predicted target. Leave JALR/BRANCH redirect paths unchanged. Propagate predicted into ex_mem_t (defensive; not consumed downstream but keeps the bundle consistent for waveform debug).\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add redirect_id input; on redirect_id without EX redirect, assert flush_if only (ID captures the JAL normally). Keep the full 2-stage flush behavior on EX redirect (branch mispredict / JALR).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire redirect_id / redirect_id_target between id_stage, if_stage, and hazard_unit. No RVFI port changes; channel-1 remains tied off; retirement semantics unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb test that fires a sequence of JALs and checks that the observed cycle count between retirements is reduced by one per JAL versus the baseline, confirming the early-redirect path is active.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777759415789,"end":1777759415805}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm formulating a clean hypothesis around JAL early-redirect behavior. The current 5-stage pipeline has JAL firing a redirect in the EX stage and flushing the IF and ID stages, but CoreMark's heavy reliance on function calls—particularly in `matrix_test`, `state_machine`, `core_list_find`, and the various `core_bench_*` functions, plus the JALR returns—suggests this could be a significant bottleneck worth investigating.\n\nThe key insight is that JAL targets are fully computable in the ID stage since they're just PC plus the immediate from the decoded instruction, whereas JALR can't be resolved early because it depends on rs1. So I'm planning to resolve JAL targets combinationally in ID, emit a redirect signal up to the IF stage, and flush only IF rather than both IF and ID. I'll add a \"predicted\" bit to track when a JAL has already been resolved early, so when it reaches EX it won't trigger a redundant redirect that would flush the correct path. BRANCH and JALR stay on the original EX-resolution path since they can't be predicted earlier.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deab79504001393dykxvRoZy0V","sessionID":"ses_2154958d3ffePO2jmYLnAOPepB","messageID":"msg_deab771ab001R7vVZuK99aQ1G2"}}
