{"type":"text","timestamp":1777759420939,"sessionID":"ses_2154958d3ffePO2jmYLnAOPepB","part":{"id":"prt_deab7f66a003e3gcVtohU0TXx0","messageID":"msg_deab7ee5c001gPglBk8QX7Bgvx","sessionID":"ses_2154958d3ffePO2jmYLnAOPepB","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Early JAL redirect in ID stage (micro_opt). Currently every JAL costs 2 pipeline bubbles because it's resolved in EX. Since JAL's target is `pc + J-imm` with no register dependency, it's fully resolvable in ID — cutting the cost to 1 bubble. CoreMark is call-heavy, so this should yield ~2–5% IPC improvement, translating directly to fitness since Fmax is already at target (135 MHz). The added logic (one adder + mux in ID, one pipeline-register bit) is well off the ALU/multiplier critical path.\n\nKey invariants preserved: JAL writeback of PC+4 still happens at WB; misalign-jump trap still fires in EX; RVFI retirement stream unchanged; BRANCH/JALR keep their 2-stage flush semantics; defensive same-cycle check in EX reverts to full flush if the predicted target ever disagreed.","time":{"start":1777759417962,"end":1777759420938}}}
