{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777761333163,"sessionID":"ses_2152b142effeJaBnw8lpnjlVpu","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01X99bcVRebJvqtJ1xHMtDWv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head; ls cores/bench/experiments/ 2>/dev/null","description":"List existing hypotheses directory"},"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n","metadata":{"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777761333159,"end":1777761333161}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the benchmark results for cores/bench/, I'm trying to optimize around the micro_opt hypothesis where we're currently at 341.04 compared to a baseline of 301.04, with Fmax sitting at 153.19 MHz. The iterative divider unit gave us a solid 13.29% boost, but the branch prediction additions created significant regressions in both area and frequency, so I need to find a different approach that doesn't sacrifice the critical path.\n\nThe real bottleneck seems to be in the ALU's combinational multiplier—it's doing three parallel 64-bit multiplications for different sign combinations and then selecting the result, which wastes DSP resources and likely dominates the EX stage timing. I could either pipeline the multiplier output to push it into a second cycle, removing it from the critical path entirely, or consolidate the three separate multipliers into a single signed operation with sign extension logic. The pipelined approach would help frequency but adds stall complexity, whereas consolidating would be cleaner but might not fully solve the path issue.\n\nActually, the better micro-optimization is to use a single 33-bit signed multiplier with sign-selection logic on each operand—for MULHU both operands are unsigned, for MULH both are signed, for MULHSU the first is signed and second unsigned, and for MUL the low bits are the same regardless of signedness. I'd pre-sign-extend the operands to 33 bits, do one 66-bit multiplication, then select either the low or high 32 bits of the result. This should cut the multiplier area roughly in half while potentially improving Fmax, and it's a well-documented RISC-V optimization.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dead52f5d0010nkBZPRuSQhgxR","sessionID":"ses_2152b142effeJaBnw8lpnjlVpu","messageID":"msg_dead4ec84001gvkrFI0YX6TGDC"}}
