{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777761399265,"sessionID":"ses_2152b142effeJaBnw8lpnjlVpu","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01CS2Fax9NJ4XDQpasKBwWGk","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\ntitle: \"Share a single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\n  parallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\n  `mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\n  $signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\n\n  On the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\n  small cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\n  product adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\n  roughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\n  outputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone —\n  so the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\n\n  This is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\n  EX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\n  extraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\n  this exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\n  multiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\n  in that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\n  on the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\n  cycle) matters — we want area reduction, not pipelining.\n\n  LUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\n  LUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\n  for Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\nhypothesis: |\n  Collapse the three parallel 64-bit multiplications into a single shared\n  33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign-extensions are selected per\n  op. RV32M semantics map cleanly onto one signed 33x33->66 multiplier:\n\n    op       sign_a   sign_b    result slice\n    MUL      (either — low half is invariant to signedness)  low[31:0]\n    MULHU    0        0         high[63:32]  (unsigned * unsigned)\n    MULH     a[31]    b[31]     high[63:32]  (signed   * signed)\n    MULHSU   a[31]    0         high[63:32]  (signed   * unsigned)\n\n  Implementation plan inside `rtl/alu.sv`:\n    1. Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with a single `logic signed [65:0]\n       mul_prod` computed from two 33-bit signed operands:\n         a_ext = {sign_a & a[31], a};   // 33-bit\n         b_ext = {sign_b & b[31], b};   // 33-bit\n         mul_prod = $signed(a_ext) * $signed(b_ext);\n       where sign_a, sign_b are decoded from `op` combinationally:\n         MUL    -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0  (unsigned*unsigned; low half matches)\n         MULH   -> sign_a=1, sign_b=1\n         MULHU  -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0\n         MULHSU -> sign_a=1, sign_b=0\n    2. Case statement now reads `mul_prod[31:0]` for MUL and\n       `mul_prod[63:32]` for the three high-half variants. Unused\n       top bits [65:64] of mul_prod are dead-code eliminated by\n       yosys; silence Verilator UNUSEDSIGNAL locally.\n    3. ALTOPS branch under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is untouched (the\n       XOR stand-ins already bypass real arithmetic). This keeps\n       per-iteration formal BMC tractable exactly as today.\n    4. `ex_stage.sv` and every other RTL file are unmodified. The\n       alu_result_final mux for div_unit is unaffected.\n\n  Expected outcome: ~2x fewer DSP blocks used for MUL*, a visibly\n  shorter output-select LUT chain in the EX cone, and therefore\n  measurably higher Fmax plus a smaller LUT4 count. Area reduction\n  also relieves routing pressure in the LUT-tight 5433/10000 region,\n  which has shown second-order Fmax benefits on this target.\n\n  IPC is unchanged (MUL/MULH* remain single-cycle combinational).\n  Risk surface is confined to a single file and a tight set of four\n  bit-exact operations that the cocotb test_alu.py + cosim diff\n  cover exhaustively (30+ vectors per op) — regression on arithmetic\n  correctness would fail loudly before FPGA eval.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777761399257,"end":1777761399264}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm noticing that the current ALU design runs three separate 64-bit multiplications in parallel, which is inefficient—it wastes both LUT and DSP resources, and the Gowin GW2AR-18 platform only has so many DSP blocks available before three multipliers become a bottleneck. I should explore whether I can share the multiplier hardware across these operations instead.\n\nThe key insight is to use a single 33x33 signed multiplier and handle the sign-extension rules for each instruction type: MUL and MULHU just need zero-padding at bit 32, MULH requires sign-extending both operands, and MULHSU sign-extends the first operand while zero-padding the second. Then I extract either the high or low 32 bits from the resulting 66-bit product depending on which instruction is executing. This approach should cut DSP usage dramatically while potentially improving timing since the output multiplexing becomes simpler.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dead5c28a0010yfxmrivMqKE8A","sessionID":"ses_2152b142effeJaBnw8lpnjlVpu","messageID":"msg_dead54d64001wQsOdxkq5AiDZW"}}
