{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762554602,"sessionID":"ses_215194e50ffeLk4kV2eZZ12KUo","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01M7aPSFB8BSFerQNWYpEdZo","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r3s0\ntitle: \"Regfile reset removal + write-first split to enable Gowin distributed-LUTRAM inference\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The register file today is 32x32 of explicit flops with a synchronous\n  reset that clears every entry, plus combinational reads with a\n  write-first bypass mux. On Gowin GW2AR-18, Yosys + Gowin synth can\n  infer a 2R1W memory of this shape as distributed LUTRAM (SPX9 / DPX9\n  cells) — but ONLY if the storage array has no reset-net. The current\n  `if (reset) for (int i; i<32; i++) regs[i] <= 0;` forces 32x32=1024\n  discrete flops plus two 32:1 combinational read muxes built from LUTs.\n\n  Core stats today are 5717 LUT4 / 2186 FF / 170.13 MHz. If ~1024 of\n  those FFs are regfile storage (~47% of the FF budget) and a comparable\n  chunk of LUTs implement the two read-port 32:1 muxes, converting to\n  distributed LUTRAM plausibly frees several hundred LUTs and ~1024 FFs.\n  Freed LUT/FF budget is headroom for future hypotheses (e.g. a small\n  BTB that previously failed on area), and more importantly the read\n  path collapses from a LUT-mux tree to a LUTRAM output that is well-\n  modelled by Gowin's timing library — potentially a small Fmax bump\n  through the ID-stage read cone.\n\n  This is pure micro_opt: no pipeline topology change, no IPC change,\n  no new module, no hazard discipline change. The semantics (2R1W +\n  x0=0 + write-first bypass on same-cycle R+W) are preserved bit-for-\n  bit; only the storage primitive changes, driven by synth-friendly\n  RTL shape.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure `rtl/reg_file.sv` along three lines, preserving every\n  externally-visible behavior:\n\n    1. Remove the synchronous reset from the storage array. The 32-entry\n       `regs[]` becomes an un-reset distributed-RAM-shaped memory.\n       Architectural correctness does not depend on x0-init content\n       (x0 is hardwired to 0 via the read-port mux) or on non-x0\n       reset content (the selftest/CoreMark crt0 writes every live\n       register before reading it; any uninitialized-read hazard is\n       already a program bug).\n    2. Keep the x0=0 combinational short-circuit on each read port\n       OUTSIDE the RAM block — it stays a 2-way mux on the read path\n       (addr==0 ? 0 : ram_read). This preserves the \"writes to x0 are\n       silently dropped, reads of x0 are always 0\" invariant without\n       the RAM needing a reset.\n    3. Keep the write-first same-cycle bypass as an EXPLICIT combinational\n       mux on the read port: `(w_en && w_addr==rs_addr) ? w_data :\n       ram_read`. Gowin's distributed RAM does not natively emit\n       write-first on the same-cycle-read path for 2R1W configurations,\n       so the bypass stays external. Yosys infers the underlying\n       single-write-two-read array as either SDPB or a pair of mirrored\n       SPX9 banks; both are fine for a 32x32 file.\n\n  Internally the storage becomes:\n      logic [31:0] regs [0:31];\n      always_ff @(posedge clock) if (w_en && w_addr != 0) regs[w_addr] <= w_data;\n  and the read path combinationally evaluates:\n      addr==0         ? 32'b0\n      : (w_en && w_addr==addr) ? w_data\n      :                  regs[addr]\n\n  The write-to-x0 guard is kept INSIDE the storage always_ff (not merely\n  on w_en externally) so the RAM never captures a bogus x0 write; Gowin\n  synth accepts this conditional write for LUTRAM inference because it\n  is still a \"write the RAM on a condition\" shape, not a reset.\n\n  Unit-test plan: `test/test_regfile.py` (cocotb) already covers the\n  write/read/x0/bypass contract; re-run to confirm bit-equivalence.\n  Cosim + CoreMark pick up any functional regression automatically\n  since every instruction reads/writes through this file.\n\n  Risk: if Gowin synth declines to infer distributed RAM (some corner\n  of the write-guard pattern or read-port count) the change is still\n  a no-op to correctness but may move Fmax 1-2 MHz either way. The\n  baseline behavior (all-flops, reset) is a fallback the tool will\n  select automatically. Upside case: 500-1000 LUT4 and ~1000 FF freed,\n  small Fmax bump, translating to a few % fitness improvement.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n    description: \"Remove the reset-clear loop on the regs[] array; keep the write-guard (w_en && w_addr!=0) inside the storage always_ff so x0 writes never touch the array. Keep the x0=0 short-circuit and the write-first bypass as explicit combinational muxes on the read ports so Gowin synth sees a clean 2R1W LUTRAM-shaped memory with no storage-level reset.\"\n  - file: test/test_regfile.py\n    description: \"Extend the existing regfile cocotb suite: (a) assert that after reset, a read of x0 returns 0 (unchanged); (b) assert that a read of a non-x0 register before any write returns SOME deterministic value from the test's perspective (we don't assert 0 post-reset since storage is no longer reset — instead assert that after a write-then-read round trip every non-x0 reg returns the written value); (c) re-run the existing write-first bypass test to confirm same-cycle R+W still returns new data. If test/test_regfile.py does not exist, create it with these three tests plus the 32-deep write/read sweep.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777762554591,"end":1777762554601}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" This is a fresh approach worth exploring — using register file RAM inference hasn't been attempted yet. Let me formulate the hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deae76baf0014liE0BWCNeogFw","sessionID":"ses_215194e50ffeLk4kV2eZZ12KUo","messageID":"msg_deae75c05001GkOWHe232O84uK"}}
