{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777759410861,"sessionID":"ses_21549585fffePPezGHdBpHeucc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012smVCRsZSHBtnAWxMPm4nG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\ntitle: \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative multi-cycle unit to shorten ALU critical path\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current ALU is fully combinational — every op, including 32-bit signed/unsigned\n  division and remainder, is computed in a single EX-stage cycle via SystemVerilog\n  `/` and `%`. On the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) there are no DSP blocks that\n  map division; synthesis emits a restoring-divider tree that is almost certainly\n  BOTH the timing-critical path AND a significant LUT4 consumer.\n\n  Current fitness is Fmax-dominated: 135.21 MHz on a 5-stage in-order pipeline is\n  low for a design this simple. Removing the combinational divider should let the\n  EX stage re-close timing around just the adder/shifter/logic/comparator and\n  DSP-backed multiplier, freeing considerable slack.\n\n  CoreMark performs very few DIV/REM ops (the hot loops are integer add/shift/\n  compare/MUL and memcpy-like stores). Paying 32 cycles for a rare DIV is a\n  great trade when every other instruction gets a shorter clock period.\nhypothesis: |\n  Pull ALU_DIV / ALU_DIVU / ALU_REM / ALU_REMU out of the combinational `alu`\n  module and into a new `div_unit.sv` iterative restoring divider:\n    - 32-cycle unsigned restoring-divide datapath (33-bit partial remainder,\n      1 subtract + 1 shift per cycle) with a tiny pre/post sign-fixup wrapper\n      for signed DIV/REM per RV32M semantics.\n    - 2-state FSM (IDLE, BUSY) with a `busy` output that drives a new\n      `div_stall` input on `hazard_unit`. While busy: stall_id + stall_ex_mem\n      hold the ID/EX and EX/MEM registers, flush_if emits bubbles so no new\n      work enters, hold_mem_wb keeps MEM/WB quiet so rvfi_order doesn't jump.\n    - On completion (cycle 32), the result is muxed into the EX-stage ALU\n      output path for one cycle, EX/MEM captures it normally, `busy` drops,\n      and the pipeline resumes.\n    - Preserve the existing RV32M edge-case semantics (DIV-by-0 → -1,\n      INT_MIN/-1 overflow → INT_MIN, REM-by-0 → dividend, etc.) in the\n      sign-fixup wrapper; same table as current `alu.sv`.\n    - Keep the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` ifdef path IDENTICAL (the cheap XOR\n      stand-ins stay in `alu.sv` and complete in one cycle; the iterative\n      unit is only instantiated in the non-ALTOPS build). This preserves\n      formal-gate runtime on every iteration.\n    - MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational in `alu.sv` — they map cleanly\n      to Gowin DSP blocks and aren't the Fmax bottleneck.\n\n  Expected effect:\n    + Fmax: shorter EX combinational cone, likely +15..25% (critical path\n      currently threads the ~32-level divider tree). This dominates fitness.\n    + LUT4: iterative divider uses ~200 LUTs vs. the ~1000+ LUT\n      combinational tree → -5..-10% area, freeing headroom.\n    - IPC: CoreMark 10-iter run executes a handful of DIV/REM at most\n      (mostly in printf, outside the timing markers). Even 100 DIVs × 32\n      cycles = 3200 cycles over ~4.5M total = <0.1% IPC loss.\n\n  Net: fitness = IPC × Fmax should rise meaningfully because the Fmax gain\n  vastly exceeds the IPC cost.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 12\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n    description: \"New iterative 32-cycle restoring divider. Inputs: start, op (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), a, b. Outputs: busy, done, result. 2-state FSM; pre-sign-fixup on a,b; post-sign-fixup on result; handle div-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32M semantics in 1 cycle fast-path.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational case (keep the ALTOPS branch unchanged). MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational. Add a defensive default so removed ops don't silently return 0 during EX — the div_unit drives the final result via ex_stage mux.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate div_unit. On ID/EX.ctrl.alu_op ∈ {DIV,DIVU,REM,REMU} fire start for one cycle, assert div_stall until busy drops, mux div_unit.result into the EX/MEM.alu_result write on the completion cycle. Preserve misalign_fault / redirect logic.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add div_stall input from ex_stage. Fold into stall_if / stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb the same way dmem_stall is handled (priority: redirect still wins for branch resolution, but a DIV in flight must complete before the redirect is honoured — use the existing stall_ex_mem pathway).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new div_stall signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit. No IO-contract changes: the top-level core port set (imem/dmem/RVFI_0/RVFI_1) is untouched.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Update tests: DIV/REM vectors now need to drive `start` and wait for `done` on the new div_unit, rather than reading the combinational alu output. Keep the same 30+ vectors per op covering signed/unsigned/by-zero/overflow edge cases to preserve invariant 5b.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a regression test: a sequence of DIV followed by dependent ADD must stall EX for ~32 cycles then retire in order with correct rd_wdata; RVFI order monotonic; no trap on legal DIV.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777759410852,"end":1777759410860}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm identifying the combinational 32-bit divider in the ALU as the likely critical path bottleneck—it's probably consuming the most LUTs on the Tang Nano 20K and limiting the maximum frequency since there's no dedicated DSP hardware for division.\n\nThe key insight is that extracting division and remainder into a separate multi-cycle unit that stalls the execute stage would let me shorten the ALU's combinational logic, increase clock frequency, and reduce overall LUT usage without significantly hurting performance since the benchmark doesn't rely heavily on division.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deab76c54001iaamWNgF0qCIyT","sessionID":"ses_21549585fffePPezGHdBpHeucc","messageID":"msg_deab7506d001mAK7F3ryMilRwE"}}
