{"type":"text","timestamp":1777761402518,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14fcffeYqX4a4nkZR1rkD","part":{"id":"prt_dead5a657002ixcG7Z5ZTCOOir","messageID":"msg_dead59d62001by0JFo975qsmhH","sessionID":"ses_2152b14fcffeYqX4a4nkZR1rkD","type":"text","text":"Good — no prior skid-buffer / fetch-FIFO attempts. Let me write the hypothesis.","time":{"start":1777761363543,"end":1777761402517}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777761402522,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14fcffeYqX4a4nkZR1rkD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01J93M3UkRY4LP28TBGLHcNk","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\ntitle: \"Decoupled instruction-fetch FIFO (2-entry) to absorb iStall and ID-side bubbles\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  Fitness is measured under the orchestrator's cosim mode with ~22% random\n  iStall + dStall (VexRiscv-parity methodology). In the current 5-stage\n  pipeline, fetch is directly coupled to ID consumption: when imem_ready=0\n  the PC register freezes AND the IF/ID combinational payload becomes a NOP,\n  so every iStall cycle is a straight-through pipeline bubble. Symmetrically,\n  any cycle where ID cannot consume (load-use stall, EX redirect target\n  unknown, dmem/div stall propagating upstream) is a cycle where a successful\n  imem fetch — if one were possible — is discarded. Under 22% random iStall\n  this pattern of \"fetch bubble = retire bubble\" costs roughly 22% of peak\n  IPC directly; even a small fetch decoupling buffer should recover a large\n  fraction of that.\n\n  Prior LESSONS.md entries on the PC path show that widening the fetch-PC\n  mux or adding predictor logic on the critical path has regressed twice\n  (hyp-001 early-redirect, hyp-003 BTB). That argues for a purely *queue-\n  side* decoupling change that leaves the IF→imem request path unchanged\n  and only adds state downstream of the imem response. There is ~4.5k LUT\n  slack and the core is not LUT-starved after DIV was extracted, so spending\n  ~100–150 LUTs on a small FIFO is affordable if it pays back in IPC.\n\n  This is a well-understood structural pattern (Rocket's fetch buffer,\n  VexRiscv's decoupled IBUS plugin, BOOM's fetch queue) and does not touch\n  decode, EX, or RVFI semantics at all — retirement still happens from\n  MEM/WB exactly as before, rvfi_order is still strictly monotonic.\nhypothesis: |\n  Insert a 2-entry instruction FIFO between the imem response and the\n  IF/ID combinational bundle, decoupling fetch from ID-side backpressure.\n\n  Mechanism:\n    - New module `fetch_buffer.sv`: 2-entry SRL/flop FIFO holding\n      {pc[31:0], instr[31:0], valid}. Head feeds IF/ID; tail captures\n      imem_data when a fetch completes and FIFO has room.\n    - `if_stage.sv` becomes a thin driver: PC advances (pc+4) whenever\n      the FIFO has space to accept a new response (i.e. a fetch request\n      may complete this cycle). The imem_addr output is still just the\n      current PC — request is in-flight when imem_ready=1 AND space\n      available; the response word is written into the FIFO tail at the\n      end of the same cycle (zero-wait semantics preserved).\n    - Hazard interface is unchanged externally: stall_if continues to\n      freeze the PC register on load-use / dmem stall / div stall, but\n      now it does NOT have to stall the FIFO drain — ID can keep pulling\n      buffered instructions while PC is held and imem is idle. The\n      `stall_if` wire is retargeted at the PC register only; a new\n      `ibuf_pop` (ID consumes head) governs FIFO advance.\n    - Redirect: on EX redirect, both the PC register and the FIFO are\n      flushed atomically; imem_addr becomes redirect_target next cycle.\n      This is identical in latency to the current redirect path — no\n      extra PC-mux tier is introduced.\n    - flush_if on IF/ID combinational output becomes: \"FIFO empty OR\n      redirect this cycle\" — emits NOP/invalid into ID. Load-use bubble\n      injection still lives in hazard_unit via flush_id; the fetch\n      buffer plays no role in ID/EX register control.\n\n  Why it should help (under 22% iStall methodology):\n    - When imem_ready=0 but FIFO has ≥1 buffered instruction, ID still\n      consumes a valid instruction that cycle — an iStall bubble\n      converts to zero bubbles.\n    - When ID stalls (load-use, dmem stall) and imem_ready=1, the FIFO\n      continues filling up to its 2-entry capacity; those buffered\n      instructions pre-pay for subsequent iStall cycles.\n    - Mathematical back-of-envelope: with 22% random iStall and ID\n      backpressure roughly uncorrelated, a 2-entry buffer's steady-state\n      occupancy recovers ~50–70% of the iStall bubbles; expected IPC\n      lift 4–8% on CoreMark.\n\n  Why it should not hurt Fmax:\n    - The imem request path is unchanged (PC → imem_addr). The imem\n      response no longer fans out to the IF/ID combinational payload\n      directly; instead it feeds FIFO tail flops and the FIFO head\n      feeds IF/ID. This is a *shortening* of the post-imem combinational\n      cone on cycles where the FIFO head is already valid (IF/ID\n      becomes flop-to-flop rather than mem-port-to-flop through the\n      flush mux).\n    - No new path traverses the EX-stage PC resolution. No new 32-bit\n      comparators added. FIFO pointer logic is 2-entry (single-bit\n      head/tail), negligible.\n\n  Area: ~96 bits of state (2 × (32 instr + 32 pc + 1 valid)) plus a\n  tiny control FSM. Budget ~120 LUT4 / 96 FF. Current 5433/10000 LUT\n  leaves plenty of room.\n\n  RVFI/invariant impact: none. Retirement still happens at MEM/WB.\n  rvfi_order still +1 per retirement. All channel-1 ports stay tied\n  off (single-issue). The 2-channel NRET=2 contract is untouched.\n  misaligned-branch and misaligned-mem traps still originate in EX/MEM.\n  The FIFO purely buffers imem responses on their way into ID.\n\n  Rollout guard: unit test `test/test_fetch_buffer.py` exercises\n  (a) zero-wait continuous fetch, (b) periodic iStall with ID\n  consuming, (c) ID stall with imem ready, (d) redirect flushing\n  both PC and buffer mid-flight, (e) back-to-back redirects.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/fetch_buffer.sv\n    description: \"New 2-entry instruction FIFO holding {pc, instr, valid}. Single-cycle push (on imem response capture when space available) and single-cycle pop (on ID consume). Flush input clears both entries atomically for EX redirect.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Retarget stall_if to gate only the PC register update; drive imem_addr from PC as before; instantiate fetch_buffer and route imem_data into its push port; drive IF/ID combinational bundle (pc, instr, valid) from the FIFO head instead of directly from imem_data. On redirect, assert fetch_buffer.flush and override PC → redirect_target in the same cycle (preserving existing priority).\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Split stall_if into two conceptually distinct signals: pc_hold (freezes PC reg on load-use / dmem stall / div stall — same condition as today's stall_if) and flush_if (IF/ID becomes NOP on redirect OR FIFO-head-not-valid). Add ibuf_pop output = !stall_id && !flush_if && fifo_head_valid to govern FIFO advance. Semantics for downstream stages are identical — only the fetch side decouples.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire the new hazard-unit signals (pc_hold, ibuf_pop) through to if_stage; no change to RVFI port set, no change to channel-1 tie-off, no change to imem/dmem port signatures.\"\n  - file: test/test_fetch_buffer.py\n    description: \"New cocotb suite: zero-wait streaming, periodic iStall with active ID, ID-stall with imem-ready, redirect-during-fill flushes both entries, back-to-back redirect, load-use + iStall coincidence. Uses channel-0 RVFI probes only (single-issue contract).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Extend existing pipeline suite with an iStall-burst scenario (e.g. 50 cycles with pseudo-random 22% iStall driving a known instruction stream) asserting rvfi_order strict-monotonicity, no X/Z on channel-1 ports, and bounded retirement latency (liveness sanity).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777761402515,"end":1777761402521}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I haven't tried a fetch FIFO or skid buffer approach yet, so let me work through what that hypothesis would look like.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dead5a6660017rbPN7yrhuHSzU","sessionID":"ses_2152b14fcffeYqX4a4nkZR1rkD","messageID":"msg_dead59d62001by0JFo975qsmhH"}}
