{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777762484332,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"id":"prt_deae6c06a001w0cdal7rkMoCpO","messageID":"msg_deae6b2bc001O1w6qOCuKzpGmD","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","snapshot":"adc3532f7c57aef53f7838c90c05183b498ed51c","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762519951,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01XsgPUNMNjdmaejAmrAm7CW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check existing hypotheses directory"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777762519938,"end":1777762519949}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the performance data from these architectural experiments, the DIV extraction and Fetch FIFO both showed strong gains around 13-15%, while the BTB proved too costly for the LUT-constrained design and the shared multiplier's overhead outweighed its DSP benefits. I'm weighing which optimizations to prioritize for the structural hypothesis.\n\nWith plenty of LUT headroom available now (5717 out of 10000), I'm considering several candidates: removing the write-first bypass from the register file to simplify the read path, pipelining the multiplier across 2-3 stages to potentially relieve the EX critical path, or splitting the EX stage deeper to reduce Fmax pressure—though each trade-off involves pipeline depth penalties or synthesis placement risks. The early branch redirect only yielded marginal gains since the PC path is already Fmax-critical, so I'm focusing on where structural changes could meaningfully improve the critical path without excessive area cost.\n\nLooking at the ALU, the three parallel 32×32 multiplies (signed, unsigned, and mixed) feeding into a case statement are likely contributing to the combinational delay. Extracting the multiplier into a pipelined unit similar to how DIV extraction gained +13% could work—I'd start the multiply in EX and complete it in MEM, then bypass the result back for dependent operations. This would require a 1-cycle stall when MUL results are needed immediately, but it pulls a heavy combinational block out of the critical path using Gowin's DSP registers.\n\nCoreMark doesn't stress MUL heavily (mostly in matrix and CRC routines), so the stall penalty should be minimal. The real question is whether the three multiplies in parallel are actually the bottleneck or if it's the branch resolve logic or regfile-to-ALU path instead. I should verify which path is truly critical before committing to the MUL extraction.\n\nBeyond that, I'm considering simpler wins like widening the fetch buffer to 4 entries for better iStall absorption, or adding a minimal store buffer to let the pipeline continue past stores when possible. A tiny branch predictor (4-entry, untagged) could help too, though the earlier BTB failure is a cautionary tale. Most of these are incremental gains with diminishing returns, so I need to pick the highest-impact option.\n\nThe pipelined multiplier still looks strongest—it mirrors the DIV win structurally and forces explicit DFF insertion regardless of what the synthesis tool does with DSP blocks. Merging MEM and WB into a 4-stage pipeline is tempting for reducing latencies and forward paths, but it breaks down when I think through the load-data timing: dmem_rdata arrives combinationally, so collapsing MEM into WB would either force multi-cycle loads or require MEM to stay as its own stage anyway. The tradeoffs don't pan out.\n\nI'm also tempted by moving the branch comparator into ID with a simple static predictor (backwards-taken, forwards-not-taken), which would resolve branches a cycle earlier and change the pipeline topology structurally. But lesson-001-r1s0 already showed that early JAL redirect in ID regressed by 1.67% due to the added combinational path and decode priority logic, so I should be cautious about similar ID-stage changes.\n\nCommitting to the 1-cycle pipelined multiplier with stall logic matching the DIV pattern—hypothesis ID r3s1.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deae74b4d0015e6cMngNeDib7W","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","messageID":"msg_deae6b2bc001O1w6qOCuKzpGmD"}}
