{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762525568,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01XJHHK9Y4A9fX85bn5C7pBp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -i 'mul\\|multiplier' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -20","description":"Search log for multiplier-related hypotheses"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Early JAL redirect in ID stage \\u2014 save 1 bubble per unconditional jump\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is function-call heavy (matrix_test, core_state_transition,\\ncore_list_find, crcu8, list_*, etc. all invoke subroutines). Every JAL\\ncurrently costs TWO pipeline bubbles because the jump is resolved in\\nEX (flushing IF and ID). But JAL is fully decodable at the ID stage:\\nthe target is `pc + J-immediate`, with no register dependency and no\\ncondition to evaluate. Resolving it one stage earlier shaves one\\nbubble per call \\u2014 measurable on a call-heavy workload \\u2014 without\\ntouching the Fmax-critical ALU path, the multiplier, or the\\nforwarding network. Current Fmax (135.21 MHz) is already at target,\\nso an IPC-only improvement translates directly to fitness gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is function-call heavy (matrix_test, core_state_transition,\\ncore_list_find, crcu8, list_*, etc. all invoke subroutines). Every JAL\\ncurrently costs TWO pipeline bubbles because the jump is resolved in\\nEX (flushing IF and ID). But JAL is fully decodable at the ID stage:\\nthe target is `pc + J-immediate`, with no register dependency and no\\ncondition to evaluate. Resolving it one stage earlier shaves one\\nbubble per call \\u2014 measurable on a call-heavy workload \\u2014 without\\ntouching the Fmax-critical ALU path, the multiplier, or the\\nforwarding network. Current Fmax (135.21 MHz) is already at target,\\nso an IPC-only improvement translates directly to fitness gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an ID-stage JAL early-redirect path. Concretely:\\n\\n1. In id_stage, compute `jal_target = pc + J-imm` combinationally\\n   whenever the decoded instruction is a JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr &&\\n   !is_illegal && valid && no flush). Drive a new `redirect_id` /\\n   `redirect_id_target` pair up to if_stage and the hazard unit.\\n2. In if_stage, give EX redirect priority over ID redirect (EX's\\n   resolved branch/JALR is the ground-truth mispredict path), and\\n   give ID redirect priority over the default pc+4.\\n3. In hazard_unit, a new `redirect_id` signal triggers `flush_if`\\n   (NOP into the IF/ID bundle) \\u2014 flushing ONE stage instead of two\\n   since the JAL itself is now in ID and will propagate normally to\\n   EX/MEM/WB so the rd=PC+4 writeback still happens.\\n4. Add a `predicted` bit to id_ex_t and ex_mem_t. When ID issues\\n   early redirect, the JAL propagates with `predicted=1`. In\\n   ex_stage, the EX redirect fires only when either (a) the\\n   instruction is NOT predicted, or (b) the predicted target\\n   disagrees with the EX-resolved target (defensive \\u2014 should never\\n   trigger for JAL since both use pc+J-imm). This keeps JALR and\\n   BRANCH flushes unchanged (their `predicted=0` stays).\\n5. JAL writeback (rd=PC+4), misaligned-jump trap detection, and\\n   RVFI pc_wdata semantics remain exactly where they are today (in\\n   EX stage); invariants 2/4/5 unaffected because the retirement\\n   stream and trap discipline don't move.\\n6. On EX-stage misprediction (which shouldn't happen for JAL but\\n   the defensive check covers it), fall back to full 2-stage flush\\n   exactly like today \\u2014 no regression path weakening.\\n\\nExpected effect: every JAL saves exactly one cycle. CoreMark's\\ninner loops contain ~several JALs per iteration through function\\ncalls; empirically 2\\u20135% IPC improvement is realistic. The added\\nlogic is tiny (one 32-bit adder + one mux in ID, one extra bit on\\npipeline registers), well off the ALU/multiplier critical path, so\\nFmax should hold at ~135 MHz. No decoder changes \\u2014 the existing\\nJAL recognition feeds the new logic unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `predicted` bit to id_ex_t and ex_mem_t pipeline bundles so the EX stage can distinguish JALs already redirected by ID from fresh control flow.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute jal_target = pc + J-imm combinationally for JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr). Emit redirect_id + redirect_id_target to core.sv. Latch ctrl.predicted=1 into the ID/EX register when early redirect fires.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept a second redirect input (redirect_id, redirect_id_target). Priority: EX redirect > ID redirect > pc+4. Emit NOP on either redirect kind (existing flush path already does this via if_stage's flush input).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect when the in-flight JAL arrives with predicted=1 AND its EX-computed target matches the predicted target. Leave JALR/BRANCH redirect paths unchanged. Propagate predicted into ex_mem_t (defensive; not consumed downstream but keeps the bundle consistent for waveform debug).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add redirect_id input; on redirect_id without EX redirect, assert flush_if only (ID captures the JAL normally). Keep the full 2-stage flush behavior on EX redirect (branch mispredict / JALR).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire redirect_id / redirect_id_target between id_stage, if_stage, and hazard_unit. No RVFI port changes; channel-1 remains tied off; retirement semantics unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that fires a sequence of JALs and checks that the observed cycle count between retirements is reduced by one per JAL versus the baseline, confirming the early-redirect path is active.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `predicted` bit to id_ex_t and ex_mem_t pipeline bundles so the EX stage can distinguish JALs already redirected by ID from fresh control flow.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute jal_target = pc + J-imm combinationally for JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr). Emit redirect_id + redirect_id_target to core.sv. Latch ctrl.predicted=1 into the ID/EX register when early redirect fires.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept a second redirect input (redirect_id, redirect_id_target). Priority: EX redirect > ID redirect > pc+4. Emit NOP on either redirect kind (existing flush path already does this via if_stage's flush input).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect when the in-flight JAL arrives with predicted=1 AND its EX-computed target matches the predicted target. Leave JALR/BRANCH redirect paths unchanged. Propagate predicted into ex_mem_t (defensive; not consumed downstream but keeps the bundle consistent for waveform debug).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add redirect_id input; on redirect_id without EX redirect, assert flush_if only (ID captures the JAL normally). Keep the full 2-stage flush behavior on EX redirect (branch mispredict / JALR).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire redirect_id / redirect_id_target between id_stage, if_stage, and hazard_unit. No RVFI port changes; channel-1 remains tied off; retirement semantics unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that fires a sequence of JALs and checks that the observed cycle count between retirements is reduced by one per JAL versus the baseline, confirming the early-redirect path is active.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 306.06, \"delta_pct\": 1.67, \"vs_baseline\": 1.67, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.96, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442217, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10260, \"ff\": 1860, \"seeds\": [127.8, 135.96, 154.77], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:20:36.648605Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r1s0 (regression, +1.67%): ID-stage JAL early-redirect adds a decode\\u2192J-imm-add\\u2192IF-PC-mux combinational path plus a new priority tier (EX>ID>pc+4) on the Fmax-critical fetch PC selection; the per-JAL bubble savings on CoreMark's call-heavy inner loops don't offset the Fmax/area cost, so \\\"IPC-only\\\" optimizations on the PC path are rarely free.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative multi-cycle unit to shorten ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU is fully combinational \\u2014 every op, including 32-bit signed/unsigned\\ndivision and remainder, is computed in a single EX-stage cycle via SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%`. On the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) there are no DSP blocks that\\nmap division; synthesis emits a restoring-divider tree that is almost certainly\\nBOTH the timing-critical path AND a significant LUT4 consumer.\\n\\nCurrent fitness is Fmax-dominated: 135.21 MHz on a 5-stage in-order pipeline is\\nlow for a design this simple. Removing the combinational divider should let the\\nEX stage re-close timing around just the adder/shifter/logic/comparator and\\nDSP-backed multiplier, freeing considerable slack.\\n\\nCoreMark performs very few DIV/REM ops (the hot loops are integer add/shift/\\ncompare/MUL and memcpy-like stores). Paying 32 cycles for a rare DIV is a\\ngreat trade when every other instruction gets a shorter clock period.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU is fully combinational \\u2014 every op, including 32-bit signed/unsigned\\ndivision and remainder, is computed in a single EX-stage cycle via SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%`. On the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) there are no DSP blocks that\\nmap division; synthesis emits a restoring-divider tree that is almost certainly\\nBOTH the timing-critical path AND a significant LUT4 consumer.\\n\\nCurrent fitness is Fmax-dominated: 135.21 MHz on a 5-stage in-order pipeline is\\nlow for a design this simple. Removing the combinational divider should let the\\nEX stage re-close timing around just the adder/shifter/logic/comparator and\\nDSP-backed multiplier, freeing considerable slack.\\n\\nCoreMark performs very few DIV/REM ops (the hot loops are integer add/shift/\\ncompare/MUL and memcpy-like stores). Paying 32 cycles for a rare DIV is a\\ngreat trade when every other instruction gets a shorter clock period.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Pull ALU_DIV / ALU_DIVU / ALU_REM / ALU_REMU out of the combinational `alu`\\nmodule and into a new `div_unit.sv` iterative restoring divider:\\n  - 32-cycle unsigned restoring-divide datapath (33-bit partial remainder,\\n    1 subtract + 1 shift per cycle) with a tiny pre/post sign-fixup wrapper\\n    for signed DIV/REM per RV32M semantics.\\n  - 2-state FSM (IDLE, BUSY) with a `busy` output that drives a new\\n    `div_stall` input on `hazard_unit`. While busy: stall_id + stall_ex_mem\\n    hold the ID/EX and EX/MEM registers, flush_if emits bubbles so no new\\n    work enters, hold_mem_wb keeps MEM/WB quiet so rvfi_order doesn't jump.\\n  - On completion (cycle 32), the result is muxed into the EX-stage ALU\\n    output path for one cycle, EX/MEM captures it normally, `busy` drops,\\n    and the pipeline resumes.\\n  - Preserve the existing RV32M edge-case semantics (DIV-by-0 \\u2192 -1,\\n    INT_MIN/-1 overflow \\u2192 INT_MIN, REM-by-0 \\u2192 dividend, etc.) in the\\n    sign-fixup wrapper; same table as current `alu.sv`.\\n  - Keep the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` ifdef path IDENTICAL (the cheap XOR\\n    stand-ins stay in `alu.sv` and complete in one cycle; the iterative\\n    unit is only instantiated in the non-ALTOPS build). This preserves\\n    formal-gate runtime on every iteration.\\n  - MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational in `alu.sv` \\u2014 they map cleanly\\n    to Gowin DSP blocks and aren't the Fmax bottleneck.\\n\\nExpected effect:\\n  + Fmax: shorter EX combinational cone, likely +15..25% (critical path\\n    currently threads the ~32-level divider tree). This dominates fitness.\\n  + LUT4: iterative divider uses ~200 LUTs vs. the ~1000+ LUT\\n    combinational tree \\u2192 -5..-10% area, freeing headroom.\\n  - IPC: CoreMark 10-iter run executes a handful of DIV/REM at most\\n    (mostly in printf, outside the timing markers). Even 100 DIVs \\u00d7 32\\n    cycles = 3200 cycles over ~4.5M total = <0.1% IPC loss.\\n\\nNet: fitness = IPC \\u00d7 Fmax should rise meaningfully because the Fmax gain\\nvastly exceeds the IPC cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative 32-cycle restoring divider. Inputs: start, op (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), a, b. Outputs: busy, done, result. 2-state FSM; pre-sign-fixup on a,b; post-sign-fixup on result; handle div-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32M semantics in 1 cycle fast-path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational case (keep the ALTOPS branch unchanged). MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational. Add a defensive default so removed ops don't silently return 0 during EX \\u2014 the div_unit drives the final result via ex_stage mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit. On ID/EX.ctrl.alu_op \\u2208 {DIV,DIVU,REM,REMU} fire start for one cycle, assert div_stall until busy drops, mux div_unit.result into the EX/MEM.alu_result write on the completion cycle. Preserve misalign_fault / redirect logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_stall input from ex_stage. Fold into stall_if / stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb the same way dmem_stall is handled (priority: redirect still wins for branch resolution, but a DIV in flight must complete before the redirect is honoured \\u2014 use the existing stall_ex_mem pathway).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new div_stall signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit. No IO-contract changes: the top-level core port set (imem/dmem/RVFI_0/RVFI_1) is untouched.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update tests: DIV/REM vectors now need to drive `start` and wait for `done` on the new div_unit, rather than reading the combinational alu output. Keep the same 30+ vectors per op covering signed/unsigned/by-zero/overflow edge cases to preserve invariant 5b.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a regression test: a sequence of DIV followed by dependent ADD must stall EX for ~32 cycles then retire in order with correct rd_wdata; RVFI order monotonic; no trap on legal DIV.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative 32-cycle restoring divider. Inputs: start, op (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), a, b. Outputs: busy, done, result. 2-state FSM; pre-sign-fixup on a,b; post-sign-fixup on result; handle div-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32M semantics in 1 cycle fast-path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational case (keep the ALTOPS branch unchanged). MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational. Add a defensive default so removed ops don't silently return 0 during EX \\u2014 the div_unit drives the final result via ex_stage mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit. On ID/EX.ctrl.alu_op \\u2208 {DIV,DIVU,REM,REMU} fire start for one cycle, assert div_stall until busy drops, mux div_unit.result into the EX/MEM.alu_result write on the completion cycle. Preserve misalign_fault / redirect logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_stall input from ex_stage. Fold into stall_if / stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb the same way dmem_stall is handled (priority: redirect still wins for branch resolution, but a DIV in flight must complete before the redirect is honoured \\u2014 use the existing stall_ex_mem pathway).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new div_stall signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit. No IO-contract changes: the top-level core port set (imem/dmem/RVFI_0/RVFI_1) is untouched.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update tests: DIV/REM vectors now need to drive `start` and wait for `done` on the new div_unit, rather than reading the combinational alu output. Keep the same 30+ vectors per op covering signed/unsigned/by-zero/overflow edge cases to preserve invariant 5b.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a regression test: a sequence of DIV followed by dependent ADD must stall EX for ~32 cycles then retire in order with correct rd_wdata; RVFI order monotonic; no trap on legal DIV.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 341.04, \"delta_pct\": 13.29, \"vs_baseline\": 13.29, \"fmax_mhz\": 153.19, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491817, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5433, \"ff\": 2053, \"seeds\": [152.21, 155.93, 153.19], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:23:20.177314Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r1s1 (improvement, +13.29%): Combinational `/` and `%` synthesize to a ~32-level restoring-divider tree that dominates both EX critical path and LUT4 area on DSP-less Gowin parts, and since CoreMark hits DIV/REM a handful of times (mostly outside timing markers), pulling them into an iterative 32-cycle `div_unit` with hazard-unit stall is a near-pure Fmax/area win \\u2014 always keep the ALTOPS branch identical in `alu.sv` so formal BMC stays tractable.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage BTB + bimodal predictor to eliminate taken-branch bubbles\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Today the 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves every control transfer in\\nEX. A taken branch or jump flushes two in-flight instructions (the one\\nin IF->ID this cycle, plus the one captured into ID/EX next cycle), so\\nevery taken CTI costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble. Untaken conditional\\nbranches cost 0 because the static predict-not-taken path matches the\\npc+4 default fetch.\\n\\nCoreMark is branch-dense: the inner loops of matrix_mul_matrix_bitextract,\\ncore_list_mergesort, crc16, and core_bench_state all spin on backward\\nbranches that are taken the overwhelming majority of the time, plus\\nevery function call/return is a JAL + JALR pair that unconditionally\\ncosts the 2-cycle bubble today. Back-of-the-envelope: if taken CTIs\\nare ~15% of retired instructions (typical for integer workloads) and\\nwe pay 2 bubble cycles each, that is ~30% CPI overhead attributable\\nto branches alone. Even a modest-accuracy predictor that covers the\\nhot loops and function returns should claw back a large chunk of that.\\n\\nThere is headroom in the LUT budget (9880/10000) but it is tight, and\\nFmax is already at 135 MHz. The predictor must be cheap and must not\\nsit on the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Today the 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves every control transfer in\\nEX. A taken branch or jump flushes two in-flight instructions (the one\\nin IF->ID this cycle, plus the one captured into ID/EX next cycle), so\\nevery taken CTI costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble. Untaken conditional\\nbranches cost 0 because the static predict-not-taken path matches the\\npc+4 default fetch.\\n\\nCoreMark is branch-dense: the inner loops of matrix_mul_matrix_bitextract,\\ncore_list_mergesort, crc16, and core_bench_state all spin on backward\\nbranches that are taken the overwhelming majority of the time, plus\\nevery function call/return is a JAL + JALR pair that unconditionally\\ncosts the 2-cycle bubble today. Back-of-the-envelope: if taken CTIs\\nare ~15% of retired instructions (typical for integer workloads) and\\nwe pay 2 bubble cycles each, that is ~30% CPI overhead attributable\\nto branches alone. Even a modest-accuracy predictor that covers the\\nhot loops and function returns should claw back a large chunk of that.\\n\\nThere is headroom in the LUT budget (9880/10000) but it is tight, and\\nFmax is already at 135 MHz. The predictor must be cheap and must not\\nsit on the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small branch target buffer with a bimodal direction predictor,\\nlooked up combinationally in IF alongside the imem fetch. Concretely:\\n\\n1. rtl/bpu.sv (new): 32-entry direct-mapped BTB indexed by PC[6:2].\\n   Each entry holds {valid, tag[24:0], target[31:0], ctr[1:0]}. Predict\\n   taken when the entry is valid, tag matches, and ctr[1]=1. JAL/JALR\\n   entries are forced to ctr=2'b11 on allocation (unconditional-taken).\\n   The predicted-PC path is: pc_next = hit_and_taken ? btb_target : pc+4.\\n   Lookup is a single LUT-RAM read plus a 25-bit comparator \\u2014 short\\n   enough to coexist with the existing imem-addr fanout inside one\\n   135 MHz cycle on GW2AR-18.\\n\\n2. rtl/if_stage.sv: consume the BPU's (predict_taken, predict_target,\\n   predict_valid) and forward them down the pipeline inside if_id_t /\\n   id_ex_t / ex_mem_t so EX can detect misprediction.\\n\\n3. rtl/core_pkg.sv: extend the pipeline bundles with three extra\\n   payload bits (predicted_taken, predicted_target[31:0]).\\n\\n4. rtl/ex_stage.sv: compute the \\\"actual\\\" resolution as today, then:\\n     - correct prediction (taken matches and target matches, or both\\n       not-taken) => suppress redirect entirely. Zero-bubble path.\\n     - misprediction => redirect to the architecturally-correct next\\n       PC (unchanged from today's redirect logic). Two-bubble flush,\\n       same as baseline.\\n   Also emit a BPU update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) so the\\n   BPU can train on every resolved CTI. Updates happen a few cycles\\n   after lookup; training-in-flight is fine because the prediction\\n   path is tolerant of stale counters \\u2014 at worst we eat the 2-cycle\\n   bubble we would have eaten anyway.\\n\\n5. rtl/core.sv: wire the BPU instance, the BPU-update bundle from EX,\\n   and the new prediction fields through the stage instantiations.\\n   The existing redirect + flush_if/flush_id plumbing is reused\\n   untouched for misprediction recovery.\\n\\nRVFI contract is unaffected: rvfi_pc_rdata / rvfi_pc_wdata still come\\nfrom the MEM/WB register and still reflect the architecturally-correct\\nPC chain (mispredicts are corrected before retirement, just like\\nload-use stalls are invisible to retirement). Channel 1 stays tied\\noff; this is still single-issue. Invariants 1..10 all hold.\\n\\nTests: extend test/test_pipeline.py with a tight-loop CoreMark-like\\nkernel (BNE backward 1000 times) and assert IPC > 0.9; add a\\nmisprediction-recovery cocotb test that flips a branch direction\\nmid-stream and checks architectural state is identical to the\\nbaseline single-step reference.\\n\\nExpected win: CoreMark/MHz moves from the current baseline (~2.2)\\ntoward 2.6-2.8 if the 32-entry BTB captures the hot loops. Fmax may\\ndrop 1-3% from the extra IF-stage mux; net fitness should still be\\nclearly positive. Worst case (Fmax loss dominates) we abort and keep\\nthe BPU as a #ifdef'd option.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bpu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters. Combinational lookup port (pc -> predict_taken, predict_target, predict_valid) and synchronous update port (pc, taken, target, is_cti, allocate). JAL/JALR allocations force counter to strongly-taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken:1 and predicted_target[31:0] fields so the prediction travels with the instruction and EX can detect misprediction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate-and-wire path to the BPU: drive pc into the lookup port, route predict_taken into the PC-next mux (pc_next = predict_taken ? predict_target : pc+4), and forward the prediction metadata into if_id_t. On redirect from EX, discard prediction (flush semantics unchanged).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bpu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters. Combinational lookup port (pc -> predict_taken, predict_target, predict_valid) and synchronous update port (pc, taken, target, is_cti, allocate). JAL/JALR allocations force counter to strongly-taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken:1 and predicted_target[31:0] fields so the prediction travels with the instruction and EX can detect misprediction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate-and-wire path to the BPU: drive pc into the lookup port, route predict_taken into the PC-next mux (pc_next = predict_taken ? predict_target : pc+4), and forward the prediction metadata into if_id_t. On redirect from EX, discard prediction (flush semantics unchanged).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 243.18, \"delta_pct\": -19.22, \"vs_baseline\": -19.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 101.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194085, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 14143, \"ff\": 3758, \"seeds\": [101.99, 103.98, 99.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:34:07.431021Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (regression, -19.22%): A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational IF-stage lookup plus a new EX-stage `correct_next_pc != predicted_next_pc` 32-bit comparator widens both the fetch-PC mux and the branch-resolution path simultaneously, and on a LUT-tight (9880/10000) Gowin part the BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles (+33 bits/stage) blow area and Fmax faster than the recovered taken-branch bubbles pay back \\u2014 predictor hypotheses on this target must budget Fmax/LUT cost before IPC gain, and the BTB-index/tag geometry should be sized to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint, not picked by convention.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Share a single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Collapse the three parallel 64-bit multiplications into a single shared\\n33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign-extensions are selected per\\nop. RV32M semantics map cleanly onto one signed 33x33->66 multiplier:\\n\\n  op       sign_a   sign_b    result slice\\n  MUL      (either \\u2014 low half is invariant to signedness)  low[31:0]\\n  MULHU    0        0         high[63:32]  (unsigned * unsigned)\\n  MULH     a[31]    b[31]     high[63:32]  (signed   * signed)\\n  MULHSU   a[31]    0         high[63:32]  (signed   * unsigned)\\n\\nImplementation plan inside `rtl/alu.sv`:\\n  1. Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with a single `logic signed [65:0]\\n     mul_prod` computed from two 33-bit signed operands:\\n       a_ext = {sign_a & a[31], a};   // 33-bit\\n       b_ext = {sign_b & b[31], b};   // 33-bit\\n       mul_prod = $signed(a_ext) * $signed(b_ext);\\n     where sign_a, sign_b are decoded from `op` combinationally:\\n       MUL    -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0  (unsigned*unsigned; low half matches)\\n       MULH   -> sign_a=1, sign_b=1\\n       MULHU  -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0\\n       MULHSU -> sign_a=1, sign_b=0\\n  2. Case statement now reads `mul_prod[31:0]` for MUL and\\n     `mul_prod[63:32]` for the three high-half variants. Unused\\n     top bits [65:64] of mul_prod are dead-code eliminated by\\n     yosys; silence Verilator UNUSEDSIGNAL locally.\\n  3. ALTOPS branch under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is untouched (the\\n     XOR stand-ins already bypass real arithmetic). This keeps\\n     per-iteration formal BMC tractable exactly as today.\\n  4. `ex_stage.sv` and every other RTL file are unmodified. The\\n     alu_result_final mux for div_unit is unaffected.\\n\\nExpected outcome: ~2x fewer DSP blocks used for MUL*, a visibly\\nshorter output-select LUT chain in the EX cone, and therefore\\nmeasurably higher Fmax plus a smaller LUT4 count. Area reduction\\nalso relieves routing pressure in the LUT-tight 5433/10000 region,\\nwhich has shown second-order Fmax benefits on this target.\\n\\nIPC is unchanged (MUL/MULH* remain single-cycle combinational).\\nRisk surface is confined to a single file and a tight set of four\\nbit-exact operations that the cocotb test_alu.py + cosim diff\\ncover exhaustively (30+ vectors per op) \\u2014 regression on arithmetic\\ncorrectness would fail loudly before FPGA eval.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 327.64, \"delta_pct\": -3.93, \"vs_baseline\": 8.84, \"fmax_mhz\": 147.17, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491817, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5429, \"ff\": 2051, \"seeds\": [169.29, 147.17, 145.03], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:43:33.490819Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (regression, -3.93%): Collapsing three parallel 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier moves the operand-signedness mux *before* the multiplier (an op\\u2192sign_a/sign_b case + AND-with-MSB + sign-extension) serializing onto the DSP input path, and widens operands from 32\\u219233 bits which on Gowin GW2AR-18's 18x18 signed DSP primitives bumps the 2x2 DSP tile to a 3x2/3x3 arrangement with deeper partial-product adder tree; synthesis was already sharing/DCEing unused halves of the three parallel products, so the \\\"3x DSP savings\\\" was largely illusory while the pre-mux on the critical EX cone cost real Fmax \\u2014 shared-operator consolidation only wins when the pre-selection mux is cheaper than the post-selection mux it replaces.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\n\"Wire redirect_id / redirect_id_target between id_stage, if_stage, and hazard_unit. No RVFI port changes; channel-1 remains tied off; retirement semantics unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that fires a sequence of JALs and checks that the observed cycle count between retirements is reduced by one per JAL versus the baseline, confirming the early-redirect path is active.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `predicted` bit to id_ex_t and ex_mem_t pipeline bundles so the EX stage can distinguish JALs already redirected by ID from fresh control flow.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute jal_target = pc + J-imm combinationally for JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr). Emit redirect_id + redirect_id_target to core.sv. Latch ctrl.predicted=1 into the ID/EX register when early redirect fires.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept a second redirect input (redirect_id, redirect_id_target). Priority: EX redirect > ID redirect > pc+4. Emit NOP on either redirect kind (existing flush path already does this via if_stage's flush input).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect when the in-flight JAL arrives with predicted=1 AND its EX-computed target matches the predicted target. Leave JALR/BRANCH redirect paths unchanged. Propagate predicted into ex_mem_t (defensive; not consumed downstream but keeps the bundle consistent for waveform debug).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add redirect_id input; on redirect_id without EX redirect, assert flush_if only (ID captures the JAL normally). Keep the full 2-stage flush behavior on EX redirect (branch mispredict / JALR).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire redirect_id / redirect_id_target between id_stage, if_stage, and hazard_unit. No RVFI port changes; channel-1 remains tied off; retirement semantics unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that fires a sequence of JALs and checks that the observed cycle count between retirements is reduced by one per JAL versus the baseline, confirming the early-redirect path is active.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 306.06, \"delta_pct\": 1.67, \"vs_baseline\": 1.67, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.96, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442217, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10260, \"ff\": 1860, \"seeds\": [127.8, 135.96, 154.77], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:20:36.648605Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r1s0 (regression, +1.67%): ID-stage JAL early-redirect adds a decode\\u2192J-imm-add\\u2192IF-PC-mux combinational path plus a new priority tier (EX>ID>pc+4) on the Fmax-critical fetch PC selection; the per-JAL bubble savings on CoreMark's call-heavy inner loops don't offset the Fmax/area cost, so \\\"IPC-only\\\" optimizations on the PC path are rarely free.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative multi-cycle unit to shorten ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU is fully combinational \\u2014 every op, including 32-bit signed/unsigned\\ndivision and remainder, is computed in a single EX-stage cycle via SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%`. On the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) there are no DSP blocks that\\nmap division; synthesis emits a restoring-divider tree that is almost certainly\\nBOTH the timing-critical path AND a significant LUT4 consumer.\\n\\nCurrent fitness is Fmax-dominated: 135.21 MHz on a 5-stage in-order pipeline is\\nlow for a design this simple. Removing the combinational divider should let the\\nEX stage re-close timing around just the adder/shifter/logic/comparator and\\nDSP-backed multiplier, freeing considerable slack.\\n\\nCoreMark performs very few DIV/REM ops (the hot loops are integer add/shift/\\ncompare/MUL and memcpy-like stores). Paying 32 cycles for a rare DIV is a\\ngreat trade when every other instruction gets a shorter clock period.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU is fully combinational \\u2014 every op, including 32-bit signed/unsigned\\ndivision and remainder, is computed in a single EX-stage cycle via SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%`. On the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) there are no DSP blocks that\\nmap division; synthesis emits a restoring-divider tree that is almost certainly\\nBOTH the timing-critical path AND a significant LUT4 consumer.\\n\\nCurrent fitness is Fmax-dominated: 135.21 MHz on a 5-stage in-order pipeline is\\nlow for a design this simple. Removing the combinational divider should let the\\nEX stage re-close timing around just the adder/shifter/logic/comparator and\\nDSP-backed multiplier, freeing considerable slack.\\n\\nCoreMark performs very few DIV/REM ops (the hot loops are integer add/shift/\\ncompare/MUL and memcpy-like stores). Paying 32 cycles for a rare DIV is a\\ngreat trade when every other instruction gets a shorter clock period.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Pull ALU_DIV / ALU_DIVU / ALU_REM / ALU_REMU out of the combinational `alu`\\nmodule and into a new `div_unit.sv` iterative restoring divider:\\n  - 32-cycle unsigned restoring-divide datapath (33-bit partial remainder,\\n    1 subtract + 1 shift per cycle) with a tiny pre/post sign-fixup wrapper\\n    for signed DIV/REM per RV32M semantics.\\n  - 2-state FSM (IDLE, BUSY) with a `busy` output that drives a new\\n    `div_stall` input on `hazard_unit`. While busy: stall_id + stall_ex_mem\\n    hold the ID/EX and EX/MEM registers, flush_if emits bubbles so no new\\n    work enters, hold_mem_wb keeps MEM/WB quiet so rvfi_order doesn't jump.\\n  - On completion (cycle 32), the result is muxed into the EX-stage ALU\\n    output path for one cycle, EX/MEM captures it normally, `busy` drops,\\n    and the pipeline resumes.\\n  - Preserve the existing RV32M edge-case semantics (DIV-by-0 \\u2192 -1,\\n    INT_MIN/-1 overflow \\u2192 INT_MIN, REM-by-0 \\u2192 dividend, etc.) in the\\n    sign-fixup wrapper; same table as current `alu.sv`.\\n  - Keep the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` ifdef path IDENTICAL (the cheap XOR\\n    stand-ins stay in `alu.sv` and complete in one cycle; the iterative\\n    unit is only instantiated in the non-ALTOPS build). This preserves\\n    formal-gate runtime on every iteration.\\n  - MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational in `alu.sv` \\u2014 they map cleanly\\n    to Gowin DSP blocks and aren't the Fmax bottleneck.\\n\\nExpected effect:\\n  + Fmax: shorter EX combinational cone, likely +15..25% (critical path\\n    currently threads the ~32-level divider tree). This dominates fitness.\\n  + LUT4: iterative divider uses ~200 LUTs vs. the ~1000+ LUT\\n    combinational tree \\u2192 -5..-10% area, freeing headroom.\\n  - IPC: CoreMark 10-iter run executes a handful of DIV/REM at most\\n    (mostly in printf, outside the timing markers). Even 100 DIVs \\u00d7 32\\n    cycles = 3200 cycles over ~4.5M total = <0.1% IPC loss.\\n\\nNet: fitness = IPC \\u00d7 Fmax should rise meaningfully because the Fmax gain\\nvastly exceeds the IPC cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative 32-cycle restoring divider. Inputs: start, op (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), a, b. Outputs: busy, done, result. 2-state FSM; pre-sign-fixup on a,b; post-sign-fixup on result; handle div-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32M semantics in 1 cycle fast-path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational case (keep the ALTOPS branch unchanged). MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational. Add a defensive default so removed ops don't silently return 0 during EX \\u2014 the div_unit drives the final result via ex_stage mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit. On ID/EX.ctrl.alu_op \\u2208 {DIV,DIVU,REM,REMU} fire start for one cycle, assert div_stall until busy drops, mux div_unit.result into the EX/MEM.alu_result write on the completion cycle. Preserve misalign_fault / redirect logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_stall input from ex_stage. Fold into stall_if / stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb the same way dmem_stall is handled (priority: redirect still wins for branch resolution, but a DIV in flight must complete before the redirect is honoured \\u2014 use the existing stall_ex_mem pathway).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new div_stall signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit. No IO-contract changes: the top-level core port set (imem/dmem/RVFI_0/RVFI_1) is untouched.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update tests: DIV/REM vectors now need to drive `start` and wait for `done` on the new div_unit, rather than reading the combinational alu output. Keep the same 30+ vectors per op covering signed/unsigned/by-zero/overflow edge cases to preserve invariant 5b.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a regression test: a sequence of DIV followed by dependent ADD must stall EX for ~32 cycles then retire in order with correct rd_wdata; RVFI order monotonic; no trap on legal DIV.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative 32-cycle restoring divider. Inputs: start, op (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), a, b. Outputs: busy, done, result. 2-state FSM; pre-sign-fixup on a,b; post-sign-fixup on result; handle div-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32M semantics in 1 cycle fast-path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational case (keep the ALTOPS branch unchanged). MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU stay combinational. Add a defensive default so removed ops don't silently return 0 during EX \\u2014 the div_unit drives the final result via ex_stage mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit. On ID/EX.ctrl.alu_op \\u2208 {DIV,DIVU,REM,REMU} fire start for one cycle, assert div_stall until busy drops, mux div_unit.result into the EX/MEM.alu_result write on the completion cycle. Preserve misalign_fault / redirect logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_stall input from ex_stage. Fold into stall_if / stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb the same way dmem_stall is handled (priority: redirect still wins for branch resolution, but a DIV in flight must complete before the redirect is honoured \\u2014 use the existing stall_ex_mem pathway).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new div_stall signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit. No IO-contract changes: the top-level core port set (imem/dmem/RVFI_0/RVFI_1) is untouched.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update tests: DIV/REM vectors now need to drive `start` and wait for `done` on the new div_unit, rather than reading the combinational alu output. Keep the same 30+ vectors per op covering signed/unsigned/by-zero/overflow edge cases to preserve invariant 5b.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a regression test: a sequence of DIV followed by dependent ADD must stall EX for ~32 cycles then retire in order with correct rd_wdata; RVFI order monotonic; no trap on legal DIV.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 341.04, \"delta_pct\": 13.29, \"vs_baseline\": 13.29, \"fmax_mhz\": 153.19, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491817, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5433, \"ff\": 2053, \"seeds\": [152.21, 155.93, 153.19], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:23:20.177314Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r1s1 (improvement, +13.29%): Combinational `/` and `%` synthesize to a ~32-level restoring-divider tree that dominates both EX critical path and LUT4 area on DSP-less Gowin parts, and since CoreMark hits DIV/REM a handful of times (mostly outside timing markers), pulling them into an iterative 32-cycle `div_unit` with hazard-unit stall is a near-pure Fmax/area win \\u2014 always keep the ALTOPS branch identical in `alu.sv` so formal BMC stays tractable.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage BTB + bimodal predictor to eliminate taken-branch bubbles\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Today the 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves every control transfer in\\nEX. A taken branch or jump flushes two in-flight instructions (the one\\nin IF->ID this cycle, plus the one captured into ID/EX next cycle), so\\nevery taken CTI costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble. Untaken conditional\\nbranches cost 0 because the static predict-not-taken path matches the\\npc+4 default fetch.\\n\\nCoreMark is branch-dense: the inner loops of matrix_mul_matrix_bitextract,\\ncore_list_mergesort, crc16, and core_bench_state all spin on backward\\nbranches that are taken the overwhelming majority of the time, plus\\nevery function call/return is a JAL + JALR pair that unconditionally\\ncosts the 2-cycle bubble today. Back-of-the-envelope: if taken CTIs\\nare ~15% of retired instructions (typical for integer workloads) and\\nwe pay 2 bubble cycles each, that is ~30% CPI overhead attributable\\nto branches alone. Even a modest-accuracy predictor that covers the\\nhot loops and function returns should claw back a large chunk of that.\\n\\nThere is headroom in the LUT budget (9880/10000) but it is tight, and\\nFmax is already at 135 MHz. The predictor must be cheap and must not\\nsit on the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Today the 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves every control transfer in\\nEX. A taken branch or jump flushes two in-flight instructions (the one\\nin IF->ID this cycle, plus the one captured into ID/EX next cycle), so\\nevery taken CTI costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble. Untaken conditional\\nbranches cost 0 because the static predict-not-taken path matches the\\npc+4 default fetch.\\n\\nCoreMark is branch-dense: the inner loops of matrix_mul_matrix_bitextract,\\ncore_list_mergesort, crc16, and core_bench_state all spin on backward\\nbranches that are taken the overwhelming majority of the time, plus\\nevery function call/return is a JAL + JALR pair that unconditionally\\ncosts the 2-cycle bubble today. Back-of-the-envelope: if taken CTIs\\nare ~15% of retired instructions (typical for integer workloads) and\\nwe pay 2 bubble cycles each, that is ~30% CPI overhead attributable\\nto branches alone. Even a modest-accuracy predictor that covers the\\nhot loops and function returns should claw back a large chunk of that.\\n\\nThere is headroom in the LUT budget (9880/10000) but it is tight, and\\nFmax is already at 135 MHz. The predictor must be cheap and must not\\nsit on the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small branch target buffer with a bimodal direction predictor,\\nlooked up combinationally in IF alongside the imem fetch. Concretely:\\n\\n1. rtl/bpu.sv (new): 32-entry direct-mapped BTB indexed by PC[6:2].\\n   Each entry holds {valid, tag[24:0], target[31:0], ctr[1:0]}. Predict\\n   taken when the entry is valid, tag matches, and ctr[1]=1. JAL/JALR\\n   entries are forced to ctr=2'b11 on allocation (unconditional-taken).\\n   The predicted-PC path is: pc_next = hit_and_taken ? btb_target : pc+4.\\n   Lookup is a single LUT-RAM read plus a 25-bit comparator \\u2014 short\\n   enough to coexist with the existing imem-addr fanout inside one\\n   135 MHz cycle on GW2AR-18.\\n\\n2. rtl/if_stage.sv: consume the BPU's (predict_taken, predict_target,\\n   predict_valid) and forward them down the pipeline inside if_id_t /\\n   id_ex_t / ex_mem_t so EX can detect misprediction.\\n\\n3. rtl/core_pkg.sv: extend the pipeline bundles with three extra\\n   payload bits (predicted_taken, predicted_target[31:0]).\\n\\n4. rtl/ex_stage.sv: compute the \\\"actual\\\" resolution as today, then:\\n     - correct prediction (taken matches and target matches, or both\\n       not-taken) => suppress redirect entirely. Zero-bubble path.\\n     - misprediction => redirect to the architecturally-correct next\\n       PC (unchanged from today's redirect logic). Two-bubble flush,\\n       same as baseline.\\n   Also emit a BPU update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) so the\\n   BPU can train on every resolved CTI. Updates happen a few cycles\\n   after lookup; training-in-flight is fine because the prediction\\n   path is tolerant of stale counters \\u2014 at worst we eat the 2-cycle\\n   bubble we would have eaten anyway.\\n\\n5. rtl/core.sv: wire the BPU instance, the BPU-update bundle from EX,\\n   and the new prediction fields through the stage instantiations.\\n   The existing redirect + flush_if/flush_id plumbing is reused\\n   untouched for misprediction recovery.\\n\\nRVFI contract is unaffected: rvfi_pc_rdata / rvfi_pc_wdata still come\\nfrom the MEM/WB register and still reflect the architecturally-correct\\nPC chain (mispredicts are corrected before retirement, just like\\nload-use stalls are invisible to retirement). Channel 1 stays tied\\noff; this is still single-issue. Invariants 1..10 all hold.\\n\\nTests: extend test/test_pipeline.py with a tight-loop CoreMark-like\\nkernel (BNE backward 1000 times) and assert IPC > 0.9; add a\\nmisprediction-recovery cocotb test that flips a branch direction\\nmid-stream and checks architectural state is identical to the\\nbaseline single-step reference.\\n\\nExpected win: CoreMark/MHz moves from the current baseline (~2.2)\\ntoward 2.6-2.8 if the 32-entry BTB captures the hot loops. Fmax may\\ndrop 1-3% from the extra IF-stage mux; net fitness should still be\\nclearly positive. Worst case (Fmax loss dominates) we abort and keep\\nthe BPU as a #ifdef'd option.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bpu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters. Combinational lookup port (pc -> predict_taken, predict_target, predict_valid) and synchronous update port (pc, taken, target, is_cti, allocate). JAL/JALR allocations force counter to strongly-taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken:1 and predicted_target[31:0] fields so the prediction travels with the instruction and EX can detect misprediction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate-and-wire path to the BPU: drive pc into the lookup port, route predict_taken into the PC-next mux (pc_next = predict_taken ? predict_target : pc+4), and forward the prediction metadata into if_id_t. On redirect from EX, discard prediction (flush semantics unchanged).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bpu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters. Combinational lookup port (pc -> predict_taken, predict_target, predict_valid) and synchronous update port (pc, taken, target, is_cti, allocate). JAL/JALR allocations force counter to strongly-taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken:1 and predicted_target[31:0] fields so the prediction travels with the instruction and EX can detect misprediction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate-and-wire path to the BPU: drive pc into the lookup port, route predict_taken into the PC-next mux (pc_next = predict_taken ? predict_target : pc+4), and forward the prediction metadata into if_id_t. On redirect from EX, discard prediction (flush semantics unchanged).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 243.18, \"delta_pct\": -19.22, \"vs_baseline\": -19.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 101.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194085, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 14143, \"ff\": 3758, \"seeds\": [101.99, 103.98, 99.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:34:07.431021Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (regression, -19.22%): A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational IF-stage lookup plus a new EX-stage `correct_next_pc != predicted_next_pc` 32-bit comparator widens both the fetch-PC mux and the branch-resolution path simultaneously, and on a LUT-tight (9880/10000) Gowin part the BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles (+33 bits/stage) blow area and Fmax faster than the recovered taken-branch bubbles pay back \\u2014 predictor hypotheses on this target must budget Fmax/LUT cost before IPC gain, and the BTB-index/tag geometry should be sized to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint, not picked by convention.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Share a single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Collapse the three parallel 64-bit multiplications into a single shared\\n33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign-extensions are selected per\\nop. RV32M semantics map cleanly onto one signed 33x33->66 multiplier:\\n\\n  op       sign_a   sign_b    result slice\\n  MUL      (either \\u2014 low half is invariant to signedness)  low[31:0]\\n  MULHU    0        0         high[63:32]  (unsigned * unsigned)\\n  MULH     a[31]    b[31]     high[63:32]  (signed   * signed)\\n  MULHSU   a[31]    0         high[63:32]  (signed   * unsigned)\\n\\nImplementation plan inside `rtl/alu.sv`:\\n  1. Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with a single `logic signed [65:0]\\n     mul_prod` computed from two 33-bit signed operands:\\n       a_ext = {sign_a & a[31], a};   // 33-bit\\n       b_ext = {sign_b & b[31], b};   // 33-bit\\n       mul_prod = $signed(a_ext) * $signed(b_ext);\\n     where sign_a, sign_b are decoded from `op` combinationally:\\n       MUL    -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0  (unsigned*unsigned; low half matches)\\n       MULH   -> sign_a=1, sign_b=1\\n       MULHU  -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0\\n       MULHSU -> sign_a=1, sign_b=0\\n  2. Case statement now reads `mul_prod[31:0]` for MUL and\\n     `mul_prod[63:32]` for the three high-half variants. Unused\\n     top bits [65:64] of mul_prod are dead-code eliminated by\\n     yosys; silence Verilator UNUSEDSIGNAL locally.\\n  3. ALTOPS branch under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is untouched (the\\n     XOR stand-ins already bypass real arithmetic). This keeps\\n     per-iteration formal BMC tractable exactly as today.\\n  4. `ex_stage.sv` and every other RTL file are unmodified. The\\n     alu_result_final mux for div_unit is unaffected.\\n\\nExpected outcome: ~2x fewer DSP blocks used for MUL*, a visibly\\nshorter output-select LUT chain in the EX cone, and therefore\\nmeasurably higher Fmax plus a smaller LUT4 count. Area reduction\\nalso relieves routing pressure in the LUT-tight 5433/10000 region,\\nwhich has shown second-order Fmax benefits on this target.\\n\\nIPC is unchanged (MUL/MULH* remain single-cycle combinational).\\nRisk surface is confined to a single file and a tight set of four\\nbit-exact operations that the cocotb test_alu.py + cosim diff\\ncover exhaustively (30+ vectors per op) \\u2014 regression on arithmetic\\ncorrectness would fail loudly before FPGA eval.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 327.64, \"delta_pct\": -3.93, \"vs_baseline\": 8.84, \"fmax_mhz\": 147.17, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491817, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5429, \"ff\": 2051, \"seeds\": [169.29, 147.17, 145.03], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:43:33.490819Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (regression, -3.93%): Collapsing three parallel 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier moves the operand-signedness mux *before* the multiplier (an op\\u2192sign_a/sign_b case + AND-with-MSB + sign-extension) serializing onto the DSP input path, and widens operands from 32\\u219233 bits which on Gowin GW2AR-18's 18x18 signed DSP primitives bumps the 2x2 DSP tile to a 3x2/3x3 arrangement with deeper partial-product adder tree; synthesis was already sharing/DCEing unused halves of the three parallel products, so the \\\"3x DSP savings\\\" was largely illusory while the pre-mux on the critical EX cone cost real Fmax \\u2014 shared-operator consolidation only wins when the pre-selection mux is cheaper than the post-selection mux it replaces.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Search log for multiplier-related hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"Search log for multiplier-related hypotheses","time":{"start":1777762525563,"end":1777762525566}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deae75ea0001mFOlEzrvY1HzPU","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","messageID":"msg_deae7595d0015xLJFf6J7XsmQS"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1777762525642,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"id":"prt_deae7617f0013Grwbh1xABBt4j","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"adc3532f7c57aef53f7838c90c05183b498ed51c","messageID":"msg_deae7595d0015xLJFf6J7XsmQS","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":71582,"input":1,"output":131,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":139,"read":71311}},"cost":0.03980425}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777762530569,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"id":"prt_deae77507001RcpBCn4edPu6lv","messageID":"msg_deae761fb001RmEHADvLR4RFjt","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","snapshot":"adc3532f7c57aef53f7838c90c05183b498ed51c","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762608101,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01LLM2yNGVydiX1ZeWicGAeY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r3s1\ntitle: \"Pipelined 1-cycle MUL unit — break EX critical path through the 32x32 multiplier(s)\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The DIV extraction hypothesis (+13.29%) and fetch FIFO (+14.90%) both\n  won by removing heavy combinational logic from the Fmax-critical EX\n  cone (and by decoupling stall windows). After those landed, Fmax is\n  170 MHz and LUT budget is comfortable (5717/10000), so the remaining\n  structural lever is the single largest combinational slab still\n  sitting in EX: the three parallel 32x32→64-bit multiplies in\n  `alu.sv` (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su), their 64-wide output mux, and\n  the alu_result_final mux that feeds the EX/MEM register capture all\n  in one combinational path.\n\n  The alu.sv comment claims \"MUL stays combinational because Gowin\n  DSP blocks absorb it without widening the cone.\" At 170 MHz the\n  period is ~5.88 ns — a Gowin GW2AR-18 32x32 signed multiply maps\n  to a 2x2 cluster of 18x18 DSPs with a fabric partial-product adder\n  tree and consumes ~3–4 ns before the ALU output mux and the EX/MEM\n  setup path. That's plausibly the remaining critical path, which\n  means even the 391.86 fitness number is MUL-limited. Removing the\n  combinational MUL from the EX cycle is the same class of structural\n  win that DIV extraction delivered.\n\n  The previous failed attempt at touching the multiplier (r2s0,\n  -3.93%) regressed because it added a *pre-multiplier* sign mux on\n  the DSP operand path and widened 32→33 bits — that's the opposite\n  geometry. Putting a pipeline register AFTER the DSP product cleanly\n  breaks the EX cone without perturbing the DSP input path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extract MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU from the combinational ALU into a new\n  `mul_unit.sv` with a 1-cycle fixed-latency pipeline register, using\n  the same dispatch/stall pattern that divunit extraction used. Design:\n\n  1. rtl/mul_unit.sv (new): inputs clock/reset/start/op/a/b, outputs\n     busy/done/result. Two-state FSM identical in spirit to div_unit\n     but trivially short:\n       - S_IDLE: on start, compute the three 33/32-bit products per\n         the current alu.sv case (or a single op-gated product if\n         the synthesizer prefers), register the selected 32-bit\n         slice (low half for MUL, high half for MULH/MULHU/MULHSU)\n         into result_q, go to S_COMPLETE next cycle.\n       - S_COMPLETE: drive done=1 and result=result_q for exactly\n         one cycle; go back to S_IDLE.\n     Total latency: 2 cycles start→done, versus 1 cycle today (MUL\n     was free combinational). The EX register actually captures on\n     the done cycle, so net wall-clock cost = +1 cycle per MUL.\n     Keep the internal product computation identical to alu.sv's\n     three-parallel structure (mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su) so synthesis\n     is free to share DSPs at will — we do NOT consolidate to a\n     single 33x33 multiplier (that was r2s0's mistake).\n\n  2. rtl/alu.sv: remove MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU from the non-ALTOPS\n     case arm (they become '0 placeholders, parallel to how\n     DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU are handled today). The ALTOPS branch is\n     UNCHANGED — the XOR stand-ins still resolve combinationally\n     so formal BMC stays tractable inside the 20-step budget.\n     Drop mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su declarations (they migrate to\n     mul_unit.sv).\n\n  3. rtl/ex_stage.sv: instantiate mul_unit next to div_unit under\n     the same `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` guard. Define\n     `is_mul_op = op ∈ {MUL,MULH,MULHU,MULHSU}` and fire mu_start\n     for one cycle when a MUL lands in EX and the unit is idle\n     (mirror the div_started_q pattern). Extend alu_result_final:\n       - is_div_op → du_result\n       - is_mul_op → mu_result\n       - else      → alu_result (the ALU's combinational cone for\n                     add/shift/logic/branch-compare, now free of\n                     the heaviest slab)\n     Add a new output `mul_stall_o` that is high from the cycle a\n     MUL enters EX through the cycle before mu_done, exactly like\n     div_stall_o. Under ALTOPS mul_stall_o is tied 0 and the ALU's\n     combinational XOR stand-ins handle MUL.\n\n  4. rtl/hazard_unit.sv: add a `mul_stall` input; OR it into the\n     existing dmem_stall/div_stall fan-out driving stall_id,\n     stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb. Fetch-side signals (ibuf_pop,\n     flush_id) are untouched because mul_stall implies no new work\n     into ID/EX and no redirect (MUL can't be a CTI).\n\n  5. rtl/core.sv: wire mul_stall from ex_stage to hazard_unit.\n     Top-level IO (imem/dmem/RVFI channels) is UNCHANGED. Channel 1\n     remains tied off. The 2-channel NRET=2 contract is preserved.\n\n  Why this should win:\n    + Removes three 32x32→64 combinational multiplies and their\n      64-wide output mux from the EX-stage cone. Gowin DSP output\n      flops now register cleanly, freeing the Fmax-critical path\n      to close around just add/shift/logic/compare. Expected Fmax\n      lift 8–15% (precedent: DIV extraction shortened a similar\n      restoring-tree and gained comparable fraction).\n    + Zero new pre-mux on DSP inputs — avoids the r2s0 failure mode.\n    + LUT4 cost for mul_unit is minimal (the products already exist;\n      we just add ~64 flops for result_q plus a tiny FSM).\n    + 1-cycle stall per MUL is the entire IPC cost. CoreMark's 10-\n      iteration run executes on the order of a few thousand MULs\n      (bit-extracts in the matrix kernel, crc updates), so ~2–5K\n      extra cycles against 4.5M total = <0.2% IPC loss.\n\n  Why it's safer than r2s0:\n    - We add the register AFTER the DSP, not muxes BEFORE it.\n    - Operand widths stay at 32 bits (no 33-bit DSP cluster bump).\n    - No change to the alu_a/alu_b operand path feeding the ALU.\n    - Mirrors the proven div_unit dispatch pattern exactly, so the\n      hazard-unit and ex_stage changes are small and precedented.\n\n  RVFI / invariants audit:\n    - Channel 0 retirement order is unaffected: a MUL retires at\n      MEM/WB one cycle later than today; rvfi_order still\n      monotonically +1 per retirement.\n    - Channel 1 stays tied off (`io_rvfi_valid_1 = 0`, rest '0).\n    - Trap discipline unchanged — MUL is never illegal, never\n      causes misalign, can't be a CTI.\n    - Memory-access bounds unchanged.\n    - ALTOPS formal path identical to today (mul_unit not\n      instantiated under ALTOPS).\n    - `make formal-deep` regression: the real-arithmetic branch\n      now sits in mul_unit.sv rather than alu.sv — same vectors,\n      same operators, same edge cases. test_alu.py must still\n      validate MUL* correctness (its ALU-level vectors are moved\n      onto the mul_unit instance or a pipeline-level test).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/mul_unit.sv\n    description: \"New 1-cycle pipelined multiplier. 2-state FSM (S_IDLE, S_COMPLETE). Inputs: clock, reset, start, op (MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU), a[31:0], b[31:0]. Outputs: busy, done (1-cycle pulse), result[31:0]. Internally computes mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su in parallel identically to today's alu.sv and selects the 32-bit slice per op into result_q on the start cycle; drives result_q out on the S_COMPLETE cycle. No RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch inside — this module is only instantiated when ALTOPS is undefined.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Remove MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU from the non-ALTOPS case (default to 32'b0, parallel to how DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU are already handled). Drop the mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su product computations from the non-ALTOPS path. ALTOPS branch is untouched — the XOR stand-ins remain combinational so formal BMC stays tractable. Update the module-level comment to reflect that MUL has joined DIV outside the combinational cone.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate mul_unit alongside div_unit under !RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS. Define is_mul_op from the ALU_MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU encodings. Generate mu_start with a one-shot mul_started_q (mirrors div_started_q). Extend alu_result_final: pick mu_result when is_mul_op, du_result when is_div_op, alu_result otherwise. Add mul_stall_o = is_mul_op && in.valid && !mu_done. Tie mul_stall_o = 0 under ALTOPS.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add mul_stall input. OR it into stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb exactly as div_stall is folded in today. flush_id stays gated on !mul_stall (mirrors the div_stall behaviour). No change to ibuf_pop logic — pop stays suppressed whenever stall_id is asserted.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire the new mul_stall signal from u_ex to u_hazard. No change to any io_* port or the RVFI 2-channel set. Channel 1 remains tied off.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU direct-ALU vectors: either keep them by wrapping in a mul_unit harness (start → wait for done → read result) or migrate them to a dedicated test_mul_unit.py with identical vector coverage. Preserve all 30+ per-op vectors from invariant 5b.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a regression test: MUL followed by an ADD that consumes the product. Verify the pipeline stalls exactly one extra cycle (relative to an ADD-ADD pair) and that the dependent ADD reads the correct post-MUL value via forwarding. Also verify rvfi_order monotonic +1 across the MUL retirement.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777762608091,"end":1777762608100}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The key takeaways are becoming clear: DIV extraction and the fetch FIFO both delivered substantial performance gains by simplifying the pipeline, while the BTB consumed too many resources and created timing issues, and the shared multiplier ended up being a step backward.\n\nI'm at 170 MHz with comfortable headroom on LUTs, so the real constraint is still that combinational path through the multiplier in EX. The DIV precedent suggests pipelining might unlock more Fmax, though the earlier multiplier experiment was risky. I need to think about what structural changes haven't been explored yet.\n\nPipelining the multiplier itself could work—register the DSP output and forward it back, accepting a stall when the result's needed immediately. That's different from the mux-heavy approach that failed before. Alternatively, I could split EX into two stages to break up the critical path, but that risks making branch mispredicts more expensive and complicates forwarding. There's also the store path to consider, which I haven't fully optimized yet.\n\nActually, a decoupled store buffer is worth exploring. Right now any STORE stalls the entire pipeline until dmem_ready, but if I capture stores into a 1-entry buffer and let the pipeline continue, I could absorb some of that dmem latency without needing to widen the memory bus or restructure the whole execute stage.\n\nThe tradeoff is load-after-store forwarding gets trickier, and I'd need to handle the case where a LOAD follows a STORE to the same address. But looking at the cycle count and dmem stall percentage, this could reclaim meaningful cycles when non-memory instructions follow a store.\n\nOn second thought, pipelined MUL feels like the safer bet—it mirrors the DIV optimization that already worked, and I can implement it cleanly by registering the multiplier output and letting MUL instructions take two cycles through EX, similar to how DIV works now.\n\nThe math checks out: CoreMark probably has around 1000 MUL instructions across 10 iterations, which is only 0.02% of the total 4.5M cycles, so even a 1-cycle stall per MUL is negligible if Fmax improves enough to offset it.\n\nThe original designer's comment about MUL staying combinational because DSP blocks handle it efficiently might be outdated—at 170 MHz with a ~5.88ns cycle time, a 32x32 DSP multiply through two tiles plus the add tree is already consuming 3-4ns, leaving almost no margin for post-mux and register setup, so it's likely the critical path.\n\nPipelining the MUL with a register after the DSP output is the right move: it's a clean structural change similar to the DIV optimization, low risk since it doesn't touch the PC or branch logic, and the hazard logic is straightforward.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deae7f0ca001V8ZQC81yfIopW0","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","messageID":"msg_deae761fb001RmEHADvLR4RFjt"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777762608118,"sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","part":{"id":"prt_deae7ec4d002w05j4tHG1yY5An","messageID":"msg_deae761fb001RmEHADvLR4RFjt","sessionID":"ses_215194dc6ffe7gz58Vlg837cxp","type":"text","text":"Good — I have full context now. Key takeaways from the history:\n\n1. **DIV extraction (+13.29%)** and **fetch FIFO (+14.90%)** were both structural wins by removing heavy combinational logic from EX or absorbing stall bubbles.\n2. **BTB (-19.22%)** and **shared 33x33 multiplier (-3.93%)** failed by widening the Fmax-critical cones.\n3. Current state: Fmax=170 MHz, LUT4=5717/10000 (budget available), FF=2186.\n\nThe largest remaining combinational slab in EX is the **three parallel 32×32→64-bit multipliers** in `alu.sv`. Lesson from r2s0 teaches that *pre-mux* consolidation fails, but *pipelining* (registers AFTER the DSP) is structurally different — it breaks the EX cone at the output, analogous to how DIV extraction broke it. MUL is rare enough in CoreMark (a few hundred per iteration) that 1-cycle stalls are affordable if Fmax climbs.","time":{"start":1777762561101,"end":1777762608116}}}
