{"type":"text","timestamp":1777759428967,"sessionID":"ses_21549578affeFrF5KKs01j8gLE","part":{"id":"prt_deab8143a0014wRdJ4Lzg1eEnd","messageID":"msg_deab801b7001Iqj8TbE1CU9vVB","sessionID":"ses_21549578affeFrF5KKs01j8gLE","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Predictor-category hypothesis proposing a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters looked up in IF. Currently every taken branch/jump costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble (EX-resolve + two-stage flush). With ~15% taken CTIs in CoreMark's inner loops, this represents substantial CPI overhead. The BPU sits on a LUT-RAM lookup path (32 entries × ~60 bits ≈ fits in distributed RAM), reuses the existing EX redirect pipeline for misprediction recovery, and is RVFI-transparent since architectural retirement still flows from MEM/WB. Predicted fitness delta: +12%, confidence medium.","time":{"start":1777759425594,"end":1777759428965}}}
