{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777761321517,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","part":{"id":"prt_dead5022a001S1hXfuUmlnTojT","messageID":"msg_dead4ec2a001tDIkXGvNgRgFyy","sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","snapshot":"2405fc1ad93a9e2d1cba31440e2c1d8f6782c3ae","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777761360272,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01FdjAKqZmMrTTiSN9DuWmDC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777761360262,"end":1777761360271}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the previous predictor design that failed due to excessive area overhead on a resource-constrained part, and I'm identifying the key culprits—the BTB storage, tag comparison logic, and pipeline widening all contributed significantly to the cost. Now I need to find a more area-efficient approach that maintains prediction accuracy without pushing against the LUT limits.\n\nLooking at the current state, we've actually freed up considerable headroom since dropping the divider unit, leaving roughly 4500 LUTs available for new logic. This gives me room to explore alternatives like a return address stack for function returns, a minimal BTB paired with next-line fetching, or a simple static predictor that handles backward branches as taken and forward branches as not taken. Given that taken branches currently incur a 2-cycle penalty in this single-issue pipeline, even modest prediction improvements could yield meaningful gains if I can keep the implementation lean. I'm reconsidering the approach — a 32-entry BTB was too costly, but what if I go much smaller, like 8 entries? Looking at CoreMark's hot loops, they're fairly compact. The real win though might be a Return Address Stack for function calls and returns, which is simpler and needs less storage than a full BTB. I'm leaning toward a 4-entry RAS that pushes return addresses on JAL and pops on JALR, catching the frequent function returns without the complexity of a large branch predictor. I'm working through the timing constraints of a return-address stack predictor. The key issue is that when a JAL (call) instruction leaves the IF stage, I need to push PC+4 onto the stack, but the prediction itself needs to happen earlier in the pipeline. JAL targets are already computed from PC+imm in IF, so predicting JAL as taken there would save two bubbles per call—though I'm concerned about the Fmax impact from doing the redirect that early. Let me think through the cycle-by-cycle behavior to make sure the push/pop logic aligns with when instructions actually commit. I'm weighing a simpler static branch predictor (backward-taken forward-not-taken) against committing to a 4-entry RAS for return prediction. The RAS approach seems stronger because it targets function returns—a major win for CoreMark with its many small function calls—and avoids the complexity that sank the previous BTB attempt. I'm going to go with RAS and write up the hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dead597ae001yupNYBBgriiOJY","sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","messageID":"msg_dead4ec2a001tDIkXGvNgRgFyy"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777761360273,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","part":{"id":"prt_dead5951a001zc6nWTeSz3eJ8I","messageID":"msg_dead4ec2a001tDIkXGvNgRgFyy","sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","type":"text","text":"Looking at the task, I need to propose a predictor hypothesis for cores/bench/. Let me check the relevant lessons first:\n- hyp-003-r1s2 (BTB) failed hard at -19.22% due to LUT-tight Gowin part (9880/10000), 32-entry BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles\n- hyp-001-r1s0 (JAL early redirect) regressed due to widened fetch PC mux\n- hyp-002-r1s1 (div_unit) is the current best, leaving ~4500 LUT headroom\n\nLet me look at one key file to understand fetch-side redirect structure, then form the hypothesis:","time":{"start":1777761359130,"end":1777761360272}}}
