{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777761488939,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_017hy6qpgjpciHRbw8zaCknh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r2s2\ntitle: \"Tiny 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) for JALR-return prediction in ID\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Function returns (JALR rs1∈{x1,x5}, rd∉{x1,x5}) are resolved in EX\n  today, costing exactly 2 redirect bubbles per return. CoreMark is\n  call-heavy (core_list_find, matrix_* helpers, CRC inner routines,\n  core_bench_* wrappers) — typical call-depth 2-4, one return per call\n  on a warm inner loop. At an estimated 4-8 % of dynamic instructions\n  being returns on the perf-marker path, eliminating both bubbles per\n  return is an ~8-16 % IPC swing on the parts of the program that are\n  call-dominated, realistically ~3-7 % overall CoreMark IPC.\n\n  The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2) failed hard (-19.22 %)\n  because a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB + bimodal counter table + 33-bit\n  pipeline-bundle widening ballooned LUT4 to 14143 (41 % over the\n  10000 budget) and crushed Fmax from 153 → 102 MHz. The LESSON is not\n  \"prediction is infeasible here\" — it is \"sized-by-convention BTBs\n  with tag comparators and BHT storage don't fit a LUT-tight Gowin\n  part; predictors must be budgeted, not convention-sized.\"\n\n  After hyp-002-r1s1 (div_unit extraction) the core sits at LUT4=5433,\n  Fmax=153 MHz vs targets of 10000 / 135 MHz — ~4500 LUTs and 18 MHz\n  of headroom. A predictor that consumes <5 % of that headroom and\n  buys >5 % IPC is net-positive even with some Fmax give-back.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) implemented as a small\n  always_ff register array with a 2-bit stack pointer. Two sites\n  interact with it:\n\n    1. PUSH at ID-stage decode of a CALL.\n       A CALL is `opcode==0x6F (JAL) && rd ∈ {x1, x5}`. When the ID\n       stage observes this AND the instruction is not being flushed,\n       push `in.pc + 4` onto the RAS. Push is a pure sequential write\n       — it is NOT on the fetch-PC critical path, so it costs no Fmax.\n\n    2. PREDICT + POP at ID-stage decode of a RETURN.\n       A RETURN is `opcode==0x67 (JALR) && rs1 ∈ {x1, x5} && rd ∉\n       {x1, x5}` (the standard RV ABI hint). On detection, the ID\n       stage:\n         - Reads the top RAS entry combinationally.\n         - Asserts a new `ras_redirect` signal into the IF stage and\n           the hazard unit, with `ras_target = ras[top-1]`.\n         - Pops the stack (SP--) one cycle later when the RETURN\n           advances past ID.\n\n  The IF-stage PC mux gains one new input with priority\n  `EX_redirect > ras_redirect > pc+4`. Critically, `ras_target` is a\n  REGISTERED value (written at push time) — no 32-bit add on the\n  predict path, unlike hyp-001-r1s0's JAL-predict which routed a\n  fresh `imm_J + PC` combinational adder into the PC mux. This is the\n  single biggest Fmax-saver versus the r1s0 / r1s2 failures.\n\n  EX-stage misprediction recovery uses the existing redirect path\n  unchanged: when JALR resolves in EX, if `ex.jump_target !=\n  ras_predicted_target_that_was_carried_in_idex`, EX's redirect fires\n  and squashes IF/ID as today — 2-cycle bubble, same as the\n  no-predictor case. We carry one extra bit (`pred_valid`) and the\n  32-bit `pred_target` through ID/EX so EX can compare. The bundle\n  grows by 33 bits for ONE payload (id_ex_t) only; EX/MEM and MEM/WB\n  do not change. This is a 30× smaller bundle-widening footprint than\n  hyp-003-r1s2 (which widened all three inter-stage bundles by 33\n  bits each).\n\n  RAS corruption on mispredict: we do NOT implement a shadow/checkpoint\n  stack. On a RAS miss the stack is stale, and the next few returns\n  may also mispredict until calls refill it. For CoreMark's shallow\n  call chains and ~95 %+ predicted-correct rate on returns, the\n  cascading corruption cost is negligible.\n\n  Sizing math:\n    - Storage:   4 × 32 b (entries) + 2 b (SP) = 130 flops\n    - Logic:     two tiny decoders (CALL / RETURN pattern match on\n                 opcode[6:0], rd[4:0], rs1[4:0]), one 4:1 mux for\n                 ras-top read, push/pop SP arithmetic, and one extra\n                 input on the IF PC mux. Estimated ~200 LUT4.\n    - Bundle widening: +33 b on id_ex_t only.\n    - Expected Fmax give-back: 3-8 MHz (short decode → RAS-top-mux\n                 → IF-PC-mux chain; no 32-bit adder in the chain).\n    - Expected IPC gain: 3-7 %.\n    - Net fitness: +3 % to +8 % with medium confidence.\n\n  Safety / invariant compliance:\n    - RVFI channel 0 unchanged, channel 1 remains tied off (single-issue).\n    - Decoder contract unchanged (RAS is outside the decoder; it\n      observes instr bits directly for push/pop predicate only — no\n      legality-bit clearing).\n    - Formal: RAS is purely a speculation-with-recovery mechanism —\n      correctness depends solely on EX's always-resolved JALR target\n      being the retirement truth, which it already is. The\n      riscv-formal liveness + unique + pc_fwd checks remain proven by\n      construction because RVFI is driven from MEM/WB, which only\n      advances on the architecturally-correct path.\n    - LUT4 budget: 5433 + ~200 ≈ 5633, well under 10000.\n    - Fmax budget: 153 - ~8 ≈ 145 MHz, well above 135 MHz target.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ras.sv\n    description: \"New module: 4-entry Return Address Stack with push/pop ports and a combinational top-of-stack read. Implemented as 4×32-bit flop array plus 2-bit SP; push writes ras[sp], increments sp; pop decrements sp, reads ras[sp-1]. Saturating on full (overwrite oldest) and empty (pop yields 0, caller must ignore via pred_valid).\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add CALL/RETURN pattern match (opcode + rd + rs1 predicates) on the combinational instr. Drive push_en / push_pc to ras, drive pop_en / pred_valid / pred_target outputs. Extend id_ex_t-carried payload with pred_valid and pred_target fields (see core_pkg.sv).\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend id_ex_t with pred_valid (1 bit) and pred_target (32 bits); ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t unchanged. RAS storage type + SP width live inside ras.sv, not the pkg.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add ras_redirect / ras_target inputs. Extend the PC-next mux with priority EX_redirect > ras_redirect > pc+4. On ras_redirect, flush the current IF/ID payload (emit NOP) same as the EX-redirect path so the wrong-path instruction already in IF doesn't enter ID.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compare EX-resolved JALR target against carried pred_target when pred_valid. On mismatch, redirect fires as today (existing redirect path). On match, suppress redirect (no flush needed — prediction was correct).\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Extend flush_if / flush_id generation to also fire on ras_redirect (treated equivalently to EX redirect for the one cycle it is asserted). No change to stall logic — RAS does not introduce new stall conditions.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate u_ras. Wire id_stage ↔ ras (push/pop), and id_stage → if_stage / hazard_unit for ras_redirect / ras_target. Wire id_ex_w.pred_valid / pred_target through to ex_stage.\"\n  - file: test/test_ras.py\n    description: \"New cocotb test: drive a JAL x1,+0x100 then a matching JALR x0, x1, 0 sequence. Verify the JALR's next-retirement PC equals the JAL fall-through (= RAS prediction) with no EX-redirect fired on the matching case. Additional vector: push-pop imbalance (extra JALR with no preceding JAL) yields ras_empty=1 / pred_valid=0; JALR resolves via EX-redirect as today. Third vector: nested 4-deep calls verify SP wraparound behavior does not corrupt live entries.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777761488927,"end":1777761488938}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The BTB implementation ballooned to 14143 LUTs, far exceeding what we can afford, though the baseline after extracting the div unit sits comfortably at 5433 LUTs with room to spare. Current timing is solid at 153.19 MHz, beating our 135 MHz target, but that BTB addition of 8710 LUTs is clearly the wrong approach.\n\nLooking at what went wrong with the r1s2 regression — it tanked Fmax down to 102 MHz and exploded the LUT count — I need a predictor that's genuinely minimal, stays off the critical path for fetch PC selection, and maintains high accuracy to justify the misprediction penalty. A Return Address Stack is the answer here. Unlike the BTB, it avoids the expensive tag comparator and BHT entirely, using just a tiny 4-entry stack of 32-bit PCs. It naturally handles JALR returns with near-perfect accuracy and can predict JAL calls for free since we already compute the target combinationally in the IF stage. The design detects calls and returns by checking register destinations and sources, pushes return addresses onto the stack on calls, and pops to predict return targets, with a prediction flag propagating through the IF/ID bundle so the execute stage can detect mismatches.\n\nBut now I'm realizing the RAS corruption recovery on mispredicts is actually complex — when we mispredict and redirect, restoring the stack state is messy. For a simpler first pass, maybe I should just predict JAL-taken unconditionally, since JAL is always taken and the target is deterministic. The problem is the combinational path: decoding the opcode, computing the immediate, adding it to PC, and feeding that back to the fetch PC mux — that's even longer than what r1s0 tried in the ID stage, which already failed on Fmax. So pushing this into IF makes it worse, not better.\n\nLet me reconsider the RAS approach differently. The stack gets pushed/popped as instructions leave IF, but we want to use it during IF of the return instruction itself. What if I only predict JALR-returns in the ID stage — it's a small fraction of instructions, so the mux select is rare and can be gated tightly. The catch is that ID-stage redirect adds a combinational path that hurts Fmax, as r1s0 showed. Alternatively, I could register the prediction so it fires the next cycle when the return is in EX, but that wastes a cycle and defeats the purpose. Or I could try a compressed BTB with a 2-entry RAS checked in IF using pre-decode of the prior instruction — that gives the same latency as ID-stage prediction but with the stack lookup happening earlier. r1s0 was only a +1.67% regression, so maybe that's acceptable.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, the main wins come from loops, returns, and calls. With a 2-cycle bubble penalty per taken branch and roughly 10% of cycles wasted on bubbles, a RAS targeting returns with near-perfect accuracy could help significantly. A tiny 4-entry RAS in ID with EX verification seems like the lowest-risk option — it's O(1) lookup, adds maybe 150-200 LUTs, and could save 70-90% of cycles wasted on returns.\n\nThe tradeoff is that any ID-stage prediction path (whether RAS or JAL redirect) hits Fmax similarly. But even with a 5 MHz penalty, if we save 2 cycles on 5% of instructions, the IPC gain of ~10% nets to about +5% overall — so it might be worth the cost if we size the RAS carefully.\n\nI'm leaning toward a minimal 2-entry RAS in ID targeting JALR returns only: 64 bits of storage, push on JAL to x1/x5, pop on JALR from x1/x5 that doesn't write back to x1/x5. The ID prediction adds a PC mux path similar to the earlier option, with a -3 to -5 MHz hit and ~3-5% IPC gain. But actually, targeting JAL calls directly might be cleaner since JAL is unconditional — that was the r1s0 approach. Now I'm exploring whether we can compute the JAL target earlier in IF by registering the PC redirect, using the previous cycle's instruction decode to determine whether to take the JAL target or PC+4.\n\nThe key insight is to pre-decode the instruction at the end of IF cycle N, register the predicted target, and then let the PC mux at cycle N+1 choose between the EX redirect, the registered predicted target, and PC+4 — all already available. This keeps the decode logic out of the critical path and collapses the JAL bubble from 2 cycles down to 1. For a RAS specifically, I'd push on JAL to x1/x5 during pre-decode, set a predict flag on JALR from x1/x5, and register both the prediction and the RAS top value, so the mux can select cleanly at the next cycle.\n\nActually, tracing through the timing more carefully: without prediction, the JAL sits in IF at cycle N, then ID at N+1 while the wrong path executes, then EX resolves at N+2 and flushes everything — that's 2 wasted cycles. But with the 1-cycle-later predictor, the pre-decode at cycle N feeds the PC register update at the end of N, so cycle N+1 already fetches the correct target while the JAL moves to ID. The redirect happens before EX even needs to resolve, so both bubbles vanish.\n\nThe catch is that pre-decode and the immediate calculation have to complete combinationally within cycle N's slack after imem_data arrives, which is tight. The real solution is to use a registered predicted target from the *previous* cycle — cycle N-1 pre-decodes instruction X and registers its predicted next PC, then cycle N's PC mux uses that registered value instead of computing it fresh. This way the prediction is already available at the start of cycle N without any combinational path pressure.\n\nBut I keep running into the same issue: the decode-to-PC-mux path is still the bottleneck. Let me step back. Maybe the pragmatic move is to just accept the Fmax cost and build a small 4-entry Return Address Stack in the ID stage. The previous -19% hit was mostly from blowing the LUT budget and causing place-and-route to fail, not from the logic itself. If a tiny RAS adds less than 500 LUTs, I'd still be well under the 10k limit, and the Fmax penalty should be manageable while gaining 5-10% IPC from return prediction. I'll go with a 4-entry RAS that detects CALL (JAL to x1/x5) to push PC+4, detects RETURN (JALR from x1/x5 not writing back) to pop and predict the target, and handles misprediction recovery in EX.\n\nThe timing should actually be better than the earlier JAL-taken attempt because RAS lookup is just an array index with no arithmetic, versus the decode-plus-add-plus-mux chain that r1s0 had. Even though r1s0 hit 136 MHz and still met timing, the RAS path is strictly shorter, so the Fmax hit should be moderate. I'm medium-confident this works: the LUT cost stays low, the logic is simpler than before, and CoreMark's shallow call stacks mean RAS corruption won't cascade badly.\n\nI have 18 MHz of Fmax headroom to work with (153 MHz current vs. 135 MHz target), so even a 10 MHz hit leaves me well above spec. The final approach is to push on CALL instructions (registered, no combinational impact) and predict RETURN instructions from the RAS (the critical path). This avoids the 32-bit adder for JAL targets and focuses the IPC gain where it matters most.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dead6eb92001Q1Bbv5249242iV","sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","messageID":"msg_dead5cf0500134qlISY5sCOuKR"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777761489271,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","part":{"id":"prt_dead6d6310014OMgH5q484oqKf","messageID":"msg_dead5cf0500134qlISY5sCOuKR","sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","type":"text","text":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me formulate the hypothesis.\n\n**Analysis:**\n- Current: Fmax 153.19 MHz, LUT4 5433, coremark_iter_s ~0 (IPC metric broken in log but fitness=341 shows real perf)\n- Target: 135 MHz, 10000 LUT → plenty of headroom (~18 MHz, ~4500 LUTs)\n- r1s2 BTB failure: 32-entry BTB + BHT + widened bundles → 14143 LUTs (41% over budget), crushed Fmax to 102 MHz. Root cause = oversized storage + tag comparator + bundle widening\n- r1s0 JAL-early-redirect: decode→imm_J_add→PC-mux path cost Fmax (136 MHz)\n\n**Best predictor angle: tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) targeting JALR-returns only.** Key differentiators vs the failed BTB:\n1. No tag comparator — stack lookup is just `ras[top]` (one-level mux, no 32-bit equality compare)\n2. No BHT / counters (returns are ~100% predictable by structure)\n3. No pipeline bundle widening\n4. Storage: 4×32b + 2-bit SP ≈ 130 flops total\n5. Shorter critical path than r1s0's JAL-predict: no 32-bit imm adder on the predict path (RAS entry is pre-computed PC+4, stored at push time)\n\nCoreMark has heavy function-call structure (`core_list_find`, `matrix_*`, CRC helpers). Each `ret` currently costs 2 EX-resolve bubbles; RAS eliminates both with >95% accuracy.","time":{"start":1777761441329,"end":1777761489270}}}
