{"type":"text","timestamp":1777761497931,"sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","part":{"id":"prt_dead79c230015QQ4HGd9FO4vQD","messageID":"msg_dead791da001Dtbkfpjgx1M5T7","sessionID":"ses_2152b14c2ffemQiMBFBNC6v7kk","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary of the proposal:**\n\nA tiny 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) for JALR-return prediction, predicting the target at ID and recovering via the existing EX redirect path on mispredict.\n\n**Key differentiators vs the failed BTB (r1s2, -19.22%):**\n- No tag comparator — RAS is a stack, top-read is a 4:1 mux, not a CAM\n- No BHT / counter array\n- Bundle widening: +33 b on id_ex_t ONLY (r1s2 widened all three bundles = 30× larger footprint)\n- Storage: 130 flops total vs ~32×(tag+target+valid) + 2-bit counters in r1s2\n- Critical path: decode→ras[top]-mux→PC-mux — crucially no 32-bit adder (r1s0's JAL predict lost Fmax on its `imm_J + PC` adder in the same mux)\n\n**Budget math:** current 5433/10000 LUT4 and 153/135 MHz Fmax gives ~4500 LUTs and 18 MHz of headroom; RAS estimated at ~200 LUTs and ~3-8 MHz give-back, so net +3-8% fitness at medium confidence.","time":{"start":1777761492003,"end":1777761497930}}}
