{"type":"text","timestamp":1777762616860,"sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","part":{"id":"prt_deae8bb20001Kr8mLHxZOOEeiu","messageID":"msg_deae6b318001NioNHRx5KZYph2","sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","type":"text","text":"Looking at the context, I need to propose a predictor hypothesis. Key constraints from lessons:\n- The failed 32-entry BTB (hyp-003-r1s2, -19.22%) was too large and widened both PC mux and EX comparator\n- LUT budget is now healthy (5717/10000) after DIV extraction + fetch buffer\n- Predictor must be sized to CoreMark's hot-loop footprint, not conventional sizes\n- PC-mux widening is expensive; target must come from flops not adders","time":{"start":1777762614048,"end":1777762616858}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762616896,"sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01FYyEMUoeo4bzS6rVWZRq1r","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check existing hypothesis files"},"output":"hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml\nhyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml\nhyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777762616889,"end":1777762616894}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what went wrong with the previous BTB predictor attempt—the 32-entry design added too much area overhead in the IF stage, and the wider 32-bit comparator needed for misprediction detection created a bottleneck in the EX stage that expanded the pipeline by 33 bits per stage.\n\nNow I'm considering a much leaner approach: static backwards-taken/forwards-not-taken heuristic paired with a tiny 4-8 entry BTB, a shallow return address stack for JALR returns, and handling JAL targets directly in the ID stage since those are unconditional and known at decode time. The key insight is that predictors need to stay cheap in LUT and Fmax cost, sized specifically to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint rather than trying to be a general-purpose predictor. I can compute the branch target directly from the instruction bits arriving in the IF stage—checking the opcode and immediate sign to predict backwards branches as taken, then feeding that through the adder to override the PC. The critical path would be tight though, similar to why the previous JAL-in-ID approach regressed by 1.67%.\n\nA better angle might be a small 4 or 8-entry BTB sized specifically for CoreMark's hot loops, using just a partial tag and direct mapping to keep it cheap—maybe 40-50 flip-flops total—with a simple 1-bit taken hint instead of a full bimodal predictor.\n\nThe real constraint is that I can't widen the PC mux in IF or add a 32-bit comparator in EX without hurting performance. The key insight is that if the BTB predicts taken and IF fetches from the predicted target, then in EX I just need to check whether the actual branch resolution matches what was predicted—if it does, no redirect; if not, assert redirect using the existing logic. The tricky part is tracking what PC the IF stage actually fetched so I can compare it later.\n\nI keep circling back to computing the branch target in ID stage using the decoder's is_branch signal and imm_gen's immediate, which would let me redirect with just 1 bubble on taken branches instead of 2. But the JAL-in-ID attempt failed because adding a new redirect source from ID widens the PC mux to 3 inputs, which kills the critical path. The PC mux is already 2-way (reset vs sequential), and adding a third input from ID is what caused the regression.\n\nLet me reconsider whether there's a way to add the speculative redirect without actually widening the mux itself—maybe by keeping the mux 2-way but changing how the redirect signal works. Looking at the IF stage logic...\n\nExamining the PC update logic...\n\nThe issue is that redirect is already the second input to the mux, so adding an ID-stage redirect would force a 4-way mux. I could try merging the ID-redirect into the EX-redirect at EX's output, but that creates a combinational path from ID through EX back to IF that's too long.\n\nA different approach: use a Return Address Stack for JALR returns, which are common in function-heavy code like CoreMark. Push on JAL with x1 or x5, pop on JALR with rs1=x1 and rd=x0, and predict the target from the RAS top in ID stage. But this still requires an ID-redirect path, which brings back the same mux widening problem.\n\nWhat if I do the prediction in IF itself by partially decoding the instruction bits for JAL opcodes and RAS pops for JALR?\n\nI can compute pc+imm as soon as imem_data arrives, potentially before the PC mux even settles. The path would be imem_data → opcode check → J-imm generation → pc+imm → PC mux, which is long but might be worth it.\n\nActually, let me just go with a small 4-entry BTB with the right constraints: only 1-bit taken history per entry, update only on taken branches to avoid thrashing, and use just PC[15:2] for tagging since code fits in under 1MB. The IF PC mux widens by one case for BTB hits, but the target comes from a flop so it should be fast. For misprediction detection in EX, I can compare the actual next PC against what was fetched right after the branch—if they don't match, it's a misprediction.\n\nOr even simpler: just use the BTB for JAL instructions only, since JAL is unconditional.\n\nLooking at CoreMark's hot paths, the real wins are backward-taken branches in tight loops like the BNE in core_list_find and the CRC computation loops. So I should focus the BTB on those patterns.\n\nI'm settling on a 4-entry fully-associative BTB for taken branches and JAL, indexed by parallel tag lookups against all 4 entries, with round-robin replacement and no LRU needed. The storage is just 264 bits total—about 33 flip-flops plus a 4-way 32-bit comparator in IF and a 32-bit mux, which is minimal area overhead.\n\nThe tricky part is the critical path: adding the BTB prediction to the PC mux in IF makes it 4-way instead of 3-way (adds one LUT), and I need to detect mispredictions in EX without bloating the pipeline. The key insight is that I only need to redirect when the BTB prediction was wrong—if it predicted correctly, I save the redirect cycle. So I can pass the predicted target and taken bit down the pipeline from IF to EX, then compare against the actual branch outcome to decide whether to redirect.\n\nThe cost is about 64 flip-flops across two pipeline stages plus comparison logic to check if actual_next_pc matches predicted_next_pc, which is roughly equivalent to the failed r1s2 approach but with a 4-entry BTB instead of 32, giving me an 8x storage savings. The real constraint is whether the LUT and timing budget allow this predictor to actually improve IPC.\n\nLet me commit to a 4-entry fully-associative BTB for taken branches and JAL instructions, looked up in IF and verified/updated in EX.\n\nActually, rereading the BTB regression notes, the core problems are structural: the fetch-PC mux widens, the EX-stage comparator adds a new critical path, the pipeline bundles expand, and the storage overhead doesn't justify the Fmax hit. Any BTB design inherits these issues to some degree.\n\nSo instead of fighting the BTB approach, I should try a different angle—maybe ID-stage branch target precomputation combined with a trick to avoid widening the PC mux by merging the IF-stage redirect logic to handle both EX-late-resolve and ID-early-taken-backward-branch in a single 2-way mux prioritized by EX correctness.\n\nBut that still requires both targets in the mux, so it doesn't actually solve the widening problem. Alternatively, I could attach a \"predicted taken, next PC\" flag to instructions in the fetch buffer itself, then flush and redirect on pop—but that still needs a PC mux.\n\nLet me step back and consider a direction predictor without a BTB: a 32×2-bit saturating counter indexed by PC predicts taken/not-taken, while the target always comes from ID's immediate generator. But this still requires an ID-stage redirect, which brings back the same PC mux widening issue.\n\nWhat if I predict entirely in IF using just the instruction bits with no storage—something like static predict-backwards-taken-forwards-not-taken, checking the opcode and sign bit as soon as the instruction arrives from memory?\n\nThe critical path would be instruction decode → B-immediate generation → PC addition → mux, all combinational. Since the PC is already a flop output, the adder might be fast enough, and the opcode check is trivial. Rough LUT count comes to about 50 total, which is cheap. The real question is whether this path is actually faster than the existing redirect path from EX, which already has a 32-bit adder in it. The ID-stage JAL attempt regressed, but that was specific to jump detection and immediate generation—this is different.\n\nActually, static backward-branch prediction in IF might hit the same PC mux widening problem that killed the earlier approach: the mux would need to prioritize IF predictions over EX redirects, adding another tier to the hierarchy. Let me pivot to something simpler: a 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR returns. It's cheap—just 16 flip-flops and a few LUTs to detect the return pattern in IF—and CoreMark has hundreds of function calls per iteration, so each correctly predicted return saves 2 bubbles. The downside is still the PC mux widening, but the IPC gain from handling returns alone might justify it. I'm realizing that any IF-stage predictor computing targets combinationally will hit the Fmax wall. But a registered-target BTB could work—I'd store pre-computed JAL targets in a small 4-entry table indexed by fetch PC, so lookup is just tag comparison and a mux of stored targets with no adder delay. The critical path becomes tag matching and target selection through the PC mux, which should fit in a few LUT levels and stay under timing. I'd make it 8-entry direct-mapped with a 6-bit partial tag, update only on taken branches, and verify predictions in the EX stage.\n\nActually, I could shrink this further to 4-entry with a full 32-bit tag to eliminate aliasing, or even go fully associative with just 2 entries for the most recent taken branches. For now I'll stick with 4-entry direct-mapped, focusing on backward-taken branches and carrying the predicted bits through the pipeline for validation. The validation itself is tricky though—comparing the predicted target against the actual computed target in EX requires a 32-bit equality check, which adds delay to the redirect path. I need to find a cheaper way to validate without that full comparison.\n\nI could pass the predicted next PC through the pipeline and compare it against what IF actually fetched, but that's still a 32-bit compare at EX time. Validating later in the pipeline (MEM or WB) would mean more bubbles on a mispredict, which defeats the purpose. The 32-bit compare in EX seems unavoidable if I want a target-predicting BTB. A direction-only predictor wouldn't help either since I still need the target.\n\nSo I'm settling on a small 4-entry fully-associative BTB with a 1-bit taken hint, focused on the hottest backward branches in CoreMark's tight loops. I'll allocate entries on taken backward branches and JAL instructions in EX, use round-robin replacement, and do parallel tag lookups in IF to fetch the predicted target. The predicted next PC flows through the pipeline, gets compared against the correct PC in EX, and on a mismatch I redirect and flush the earlier stages. This costs about 33 flip-flops for the BTB itself plus 64 for the pipeline registers and a 32-bit comparator, but should save roughly 2 bubbles per correctly predicted taken branch—translating to maybe a 30% IPC gain given CoreMark's branch density.\n\nRealistically though, I'm looking at 10-15% IPC improvement, probably offset by a 5-10% Fmax hit, so net gain of 5-10%.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering a much simpler approach: just a single-entry latch that remembers the last taken branch and its target. If the current fetch PC matches that stored branch PC, I use the stored target. This handles the tightest inner loops perfectly—like CoreMark's CRC loops with a single repeating backward branch—and costs only 8 flip-flops. It's almost trivial to implement and might give enough benefit for the effort.\n\nBut a 1-entry predictor is probably too small for CoreMark's multiple hot loops. A 4-entry fully-associative BTB is more realistic—that matches the actual PC footprint of CoreMark's inner loops better than the 32 entries used before. The tradeoff is whether to detect mispredictions in EX (on the critical path) or delay it to MEM (cheaper but 3-cycle penalty per mispredict). If accuracy is 80%+, the MEM-stage approach might still win overall, but the worst-case penalty is harsh. I'll stick with the 4-entry BTB and keep misprediction detection in EX.\n\nThe verification logic is straightforward: pass the predicted target and a valid bit through the pipeline with the branch instruction, then in EX compare the actual resolved target against what was predicted. If they match, no redirect; if they don't, redirect to the correct target. I can simplify this further by checking whether the next instruction's PC already matches the correct target—if it does, no redirect is needed.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the practical impact on CoreMark: tight loops with backward branches would see the biggest gains since they repeat the same target, potentially cutting the 2-cycle bubble penalty down to 1 cycle per iteration. With a 4-entry BTB, I'd realistically expect maybe 5-10% IPC improvement overall, though the Fmax might drop by around 5% due to the wider datapath needed for the 32-bit comparison in EX.\n\nThe risk-reward doesn't look great, so I'm considering alternatives like pre-decoding instructions in the fetch buffer to save decoder area, or doubling fetch width if dual-port memory is available. But those have their own complications.\n\nI think I should just go with the 4-entry BTB approach—it's the most straightforward predictor that could actually help without major architectural changes. Looking back at the existing redirect logic, I can see the critical path already flows through the branch taken check, so adding a predicted target match verification should integrate cleanly.\n\nThe tricky part is validating predictions: I'd need to compare the computed next PC against what was actually fetched, but the IF/ID stage gets flushed on redirect, so there's no reference point to compare against. I'll just move forward with the BTB design.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deae8c0650014KUHU2CaGHYT2e","sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","messageID":"msg_deae6b318001NioNHRx5KZYph2"}}
