{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762623814,"sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_019cb6kTyBrpiky1YtBBzc9T","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -l \"predictor\\|BTB\\|RAS\\|branch.pred\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -3; grep -i \"predictor\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -10","description":"Search for past predictor attempts"},"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage BTB + bimodal predictor to eliminate taken-branch bubbles\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Today the 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves every control transfer in\\nEX. A taken branch or jump flushes two in-flight instructions (the one\\nin IF->ID this cycle, plus the one captured into ID/EX next cycle), so\\nevery taken CTI costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble. Untaken conditional\\nbranches cost 0 because the static predict-not-taken path matches the\\npc+4 default fetch.\\n\\nCoreMark is branch-dense: the inner loops of matrix_mul_matrix_bitextract,\\ncore_list_mergesort, crc16, and core_bench_state all spin on backward\\nbranches that are taken the overwhelming majority of the time, plus\\nevery function call/return is a JAL + JALR pair that unconditionally\\ncosts the 2-cycle bubble today. Back-of-the-envelope: if taken CTIs\\nare ~15% of retired instructions (typical for integer workloads) and\\nwe pay 2 bubble cycles each, that is ~30% CPI overhead attributable\\nto branches alone. Even a modest-accuracy predictor that covers the\\nhot loops and function returns should claw back a large chunk of that.\\n\\nThere is headroom in the LUT budget (9880/10000) but it is tight, and\\nFmax is already at 135 MHz. The predictor must be cheap and must not\\nsit on the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Today the 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves every control transfer in\\nEX. A taken branch or jump flushes two in-flight instructions (the one\\nin IF->ID this cycle, plus the one captured into ID/EX next cycle), so\\nevery taken CTI costs a fixed 2-cycle bubble. Untaken conditional\\nbranches cost 0 because the static predict-not-taken path matches the\\npc+4 default fetch.\\n\\nCoreMark is branch-dense: the inner loops of matrix_mul_matrix_bitextract,\\ncore_list_mergesort, crc16, and core_bench_state all spin on backward\\nbranches that are taken the overwhelming majority of the time, plus\\nevery function call/return is a JAL + JALR pair that unconditionally\\ncosts the 2-cycle bubble today. Back-of-the-envelope: if taken CTIs\\nare ~15% of retired instructions (typical for integer workloads) and\\nwe pay 2 bubble cycles each, that is ~30% CPI overhead attributable\\nto branches alone. Even a modest-accuracy predictor that covers the\\nhot loops and function returns should claw back a large chunk of that.\\n\\nThere is headroom in the LUT budget (9880/10000) but it is tight, and\\nFmax is already at 135 MHz. The predictor must be cheap and must not\\nsit on the IF critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small branch target buffer with a bimodal direction predictor,\\nlooked up combinationally in IF alongside the imem fetch. Concretely:\\n\\n1. rtl/bpu.sv (new): 32-entry direct-mapped BTB indexed by PC[6:2].\\n   Each entry holds {valid, tag[24:0], target[31:0], ctr[1:0]}. Predict\\n   taken when the entry is valid, tag matches, and ctr[1]=1. JAL/JALR\\n   entries are forced to ctr=2'b11 on allocation (unconditional-taken).\\n   The predicted-PC path is: pc_next = hit_and_taken ? btb_target : pc+4.\\n   Lookup is a single LUT-RAM read plus a 25-bit comparator \\u2014 short\\n   enough to coexist with the existing imem-addr fanout inside one\\n   135 MHz cycle on GW2AR-18.\\n\\n2. rtl/if_stage.sv: consume the BPU's (predict_taken, predict_target,\\n   predict_valid) and forward them down the pipeline inside if_id_t /\\n   id_ex_t / ex_mem_t so EX can detect misprediction.\\n\\n3. rtl/core_pkg.sv: extend the pipeline bundles with three extra\\n   payload bits (predicted_taken, predicted_target[31:0]).\\n\\n4. rtl/ex_stage.sv: compute the \\\"actual\\\" resolution as today, then:\\n     - correct prediction (taken matches and target matches, or both\\n       not-taken) => suppress redirect entirely. Zero-bubble path.\\n     - misprediction => redirect to the architecturally-correct next\\n       PC (unchanged from today's redirect logic). Two-bubble flush,\\n       same as baseline.\\n   Also emit a BPU update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) so the\\n   BPU can train on every resolved CTI. Updates happen a few cycles\\n   after lookup; training-in-flight is fine because the prediction\\n   path is tolerant of stale counters \\u2014 at worst we eat the 2-cycle\\n   bubble we would have eaten anyway.\\n\\n5. rtl/core.sv: wire the BPU instance, the BPU-update bundle from EX,\\n   and the new prediction fields through the stage instantiations.\\n   The existing redirect + flush_if/flush_id plumbing is reused\\n   untouched for misprediction recovery.\\n\\nRVFI contract is unaffected: rvfi_pc_rdata / rvfi_pc_wdata still come\\nfrom the MEM/WB register and still reflect the architecturally-correct\\nPC chain (mispredicts are corrected before retirement, just like\\nload-use stalls are invisible to retirement). Channel 1 stays tied\\noff; this is still single-issue. Invariants 1..10 all hold.\\n\\nTests: extend test/test_pipeline.py with a tight-loop CoreMark-like\\nkernel (BNE backward 1000 times) and assert IPC > 0.9; add a\\nmisprediction-recovery cocotb test that flips a branch direction\\nmid-stream and checks architectural state is identical to the\\nbaseline single-step reference.\\n\\nExpected win: CoreMark/MHz moves from the current baseline (~2.2)\\ntoward 2.6-2.8 if the 32-entry BTB captures the hot loops. Fmax may\\ndrop 1-3% from the extra IF-stage mux; net fitness should still be\\nclearly positive. Worst case (Fmax loss dominates) we abort and keep\\nthe BPU as a #ifdef'd option.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bpu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters. Combinational lookup port (pc -> predict_taken, predict_target, predict_valid) and synchronous update port (pc, taken, target, is_cti, allocate). JAL/JALR allocations force counter to strongly-taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken:1 and predicted_target[31:0] fields so the prediction travels with the instruction and EX can detect misprediction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate-and-wire path to the BPU: drive pc into the lookup port, route predict_taken into the PC-next mux (pc_next = predict_taken ? predict_target : pc+4), and forward the prediction metadata into if_id_t. On redirect from EX, discard prediction (flush semantics unchanged).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bpu.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit bimodal counters. Combinational lookup port (pc -> predict_taken, predict_target, predict_valid) and synchronous update port (pc, taken, target, is_cti, allocate). JAL/JALR allocations force counter to strongly-taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken:1 and predicted_target[31:0] fields so the prediction travels with the instruction and EX can detect misprediction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate-and-wire path to the BPU: drive pc into the lookup port, route predict_taken into the PC-next mux (pc_next = predict_taken ? predict_target : pc+4), and forward the prediction metadata into if_id_t. On redirect from EX, discard prediction (flush semantics unchanged).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 243.18, \"delta_pct\": -19.22, \"vs_baseline\": -19.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 101.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194085, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 14143, \"ff\": 3758, \"seeds\": [101.99, 103.98, 99.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:34:07.431021Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (regression, -19.22%): A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational IF-stage lookup plus a new EX-stage `correct_next_pc != predicted_next_pc` 32-bit comparator widens both the fetch-PC mux and the branch-resolution path simultaneously, and on a LUT-tight (9880/10000) Gowin part the BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles (+33 bits/stage) blow area and Fmax faster than the recovered taken-branch bubbles pay back \\u2014 predictor hypotheses on this target must budget Fmax/LUT cost before IPC gain, and the BTB-index/tag geometry should be sized to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint, not picked by convention.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Share a single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Collapse the three parallel 64-bit multiplications into a single shared\\n33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign-extensions are selected per\\nop. RV32M semantics map cleanly onto one signed 33x33->66 multiplier:\\n\\n  op       sign_a   sign_b    result slice\\n  MUL      (either \\u2014 low half is invariant to signedness)  low[31:0]\\n  MULHU    0        0         high[63:32]  (unsigned * unsigned)\\n  MULH     a[31]    b[31]     high[63:32]  (signed   * signed)\\n  MULHSU   a[31]    0         high[63:32]  (signed   * unsigned)\\n\\nImplementation plan inside `rtl/alu.sv`:\\n  1. Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with a single `logic signed [65:0]\\n     mul_prod` computed from two 33-bit signed operands:\\n       a_ext = {sign_a & a[31], a};   // 33-bit\\n       b_ext = {sign_b & b[31], b};   // 33-bit\\n       mul_prod = $signed(a_ext) * $signed(b_ext);\\n     where sign_a, sign_b are decoded from `op` combinationally:\\n       MUL    -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0  (unsigned*unsigned; low half matches)\\n       MULH   -> sign_a=1, sign_b=1\\n       MULHU  -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0\\n       MULHSU -> sign_a=1, sign_b=0\\n  2. Case statement now reads `mul_prod[31:0]` for MUL and\\n     `mul_prod[63:32]` for the three high-half variants. Unused\\n     top bits [65:64] of mul_prod are dead-code eliminated by\\n     yosys; silence Verilator UNUSEDSIGNAL locally.\\n  3. ALTOPS branch under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is untouched (the\\n     XOR stand-ins already bypass real arithmetic). This keeps\\n     per-iteration formal BMC tractable exactly as today.\\n  4. `ex_stage.sv` and every other RTL file are unmodified. The\\n     alu_result_final mux for div_unit is unaffected.\\n\\nExpected outcome: ~2x fewer DSP blocks used for MUL*, a visibly\\nshorter output-select LUT chain in the EX cone, and therefore\\nmeasurably higher Fmax plus a smaller LUT4 count. Area reduction\\nalso relieves routing pressure in the LUT-tight 5433/10000 region,\\nwhich has shown second-order Fmax benefits on this target.\\n\\nIPC is unchanged (MUL/MULH* remain single-cycle combinational).\\nRisk surface is confined to a single file and a tight set of four\\nbit-exact operations that the cocotb test_alu.py + cosim diff\\ncover exhaustively (30+ vectors per op) \\u2014 regression on arithmetic\\ncorrectness would fail loudly before FPGA eval.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 327.64, \"delta_pct\": -3.93, \"vs_baseline\": 8.84, \"fmax_mhz\": 147.17, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491817, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5429, \"ff\": 2051, \"seeds\": [169.29, 147.17, 145.03], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:43:33.490819Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (regression, -3.93%): Collapsing three parallel 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier moves the operand-signedness mux *before* the multiplier (an op\\u2192sign_a/sign_b case + AND-with-MSB + sign-extension) serializing onto the DSP input path, and widens operands from 32\\u219233 bits which on Gowin GW2AR-18's 18x18 signed DSP primitives bumps the 2x2 DSP tile to a 3x2/3x3 arrangement with deeper partial-product adder tree; synthesis was already sharing/DCEing unused halves of the three parallel products, so the \\\"3x DSP savings\\\" was largely illusory while the pre-mux on the critical EX cone cost real Fmax \\u2014 shared-operator consolidation only wins when the pre-selection mux is cheaper than the post-selection mux it replaces.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decoupled instruction-fetch FIFO (2-entry) to absorb iStall and ID-side bubbles\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Fitness is measured under the orchestrator's cosim mode with ~22% random\\niStall + dStall (VexRiscv-parity methodology). In the current 5-stage\\npipeline, fetch is directly coupled to ID consumption: when imem_ready=0\\nthe PC register freezes AND the IF/ID combinational payload becomes a NOP,\\nso every iStall cycle is a straight-through pipeline bubble. Symmetrically,\\nany cycle where ID cannot consume (load-use stall, EX redirect target\\nunknown, dmem/div stall propagating upstream) is a cycle where a successful\\nimem fetch \\u2014 if one were possible \\u2014 is discarded. Under 22% random iStall\\nthis pattern of \\\"fetch bubble = retire bubble\\\" costs roughly 22% of peak\\nIPC directly; even a small fetch decoupling buffer should recover a large\\nfraction of that.\\n\\nPrior LESSONS.md entries on the PC path show that widening the fetch-PC\\nmux or adding predictor logic on the critical path has regressed twice\\n(hyp-001 early-redirect, hyp-003 BTB). That argues for a purely *queue-\\nside* decoupling change that leaves the IF\\u2192imem request path unchanged\\nand only adds state downstream of the imem response. There is ~4.5k LUT\\nslack and the core is not LUT-starved after DIV was extracted, so spending\\n~100\\u2013150 LUTs on a small FIFO is affordable if it pays back in IPC.\\n\\nThis is a well-understood structural pattern (Rocket's fetch buffer,\\nVexRiscv's decoupled IBUS plugin, BOOM's fetch queue) and does not touch\\ndecode, EX, or RVFI semantics at all \\u2014 retirement still happens from\\nMEM/WB exactly as before, rvfi_order is still strictly monotonic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Fitness is measured under the orchestrator's cosim mode with ~22% random\\niStall + dStall (VexRiscv-parity methodology). In the current 5-stage\\npipeline, fetch is directly coupled to ID consumption: when imem_ready=0\\nthe PC register freezes AND the IF/ID combinational payload becomes a NOP,\\nso every iStall cycle is a straight-through pipeline bubble. Symmetrically,\\nany cycle where ID cannot consume (load-use stall, EX redirect target\\nunknown, dmem/div stall propagating upstream) is a cycle where a successful\\nimem fetch \\u2014 if one were possible \\u2014 is discarded. Under 22% random iStall\\nthis pattern of \\\"fetch bubble = retire bubble\\\" costs roughly 22% of peak\\nIPC directly; even a small fetch decoupling buffer should recover a large\\nfraction of that.\\n\\nPrior LESSONS.md entries on the PC path show that widening the fetch-PC\\nmux or adding predictor logic on the critical path has regressed twice\\n(hyp-001 early-redirect, hyp-003 BTB). That argues for a purely *queue-\\nside* decoupling change that leaves the IF\\u2192imem request path unchanged\\nand only adds state downstream of the imem response. There is ~4.5k LUT\\nslack and the core is not LUT-starved after DIV was extracted, so spending\\n~100\\u2013150 LUTs on a small FIFO is affordable if it pays back in IPC.\\n\\nThis is a well-understood structural pattern (Rocket's fetch buffer,\\nVexRiscv's decoupled IBUS plugin, BOOM's fetch queue) and does not touch\\ndecode, EX, or RVFI semantics at all \\u2014 retirement still happens from\\nMEM/WB exactly as before, rvfi_order is still strictly monotonic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 2-entry instruction FIFO between the imem response and the\\nIF/ID combinational bundle, decoupling fetch from ID-side backpressure.\\n\\nMechanism:\\n  - New module `fetch_buffer.sv`: 2-entry SRL/flop FIFO holding\\n    {pc[31:0], instr[31:0], valid}. Head feeds IF/ID; tail captures\\n    imem_data when a fetch completes and FIFO has room.\\n  - `if_stage.sv` becomes a thin driver: PC advances (pc+4) whenever\\n    the FIFO has space to accept a new response (i.e. a fetch request\\n    may complete this cycle). The imem_addr output is still just the\\n    current PC \\u2014 request is in-flight when imem_ready=1 AND space\\n    available; the response word is written into the FIFO tail at the\\n    end of the same cycle (zero-wait semantics preserved).\\n  - Hazard interface is unchanged externally: stall_if continues to\\n    freeze the PC register on load-use / dmem stall / div stall, but\\n    now it does NOT have to stall the FIFO drain \\u2014 ID can keep pulling\\n    buffered instructions while PC is held and imem is idle. The\\n    `stall_if` wire is retargeted at the PC register only; a new\\n    `ibuf_pop` (ID consumes head) governs FIFO advance.\\n  - Redirect: on EX redirect, both the PC register and the FIFO are\\n    flushed atomically; imem_addr becomes redirect_target next cycle.\\n    This is identical in latency to the current redirect path \\u2014 no\\n    extra PC-mux tier is introduced.\\n  - flush_if on IF/ID combinational output becomes: \\\"FIFO empty OR\\n    redirect this cycle\\\" \\u2014 emits NOP/invalid into ID. Load-use bubble\\n    injection still lives in hazard_unit via flush_id; the fetch\\n    buffer plays no role in ID/EX register control.\\n\\nWhy it should help (under 22% iStall methodology):\\n  - When imem_ready=0 but FIFO has \\u22651 buffered instruction, ID still\\n    consumes a valid instruction that cycle \\u2014 an iStall bubble\\n    converts to zero bubbles.\\n  - When ID stalls (load-use, dmem stall) and imem_ready=1, the FIFO\\n    continues filling up to its 2-entry capacity; those buffered\\n    instructions pre-pay for subsequent iStall cycles.\\n  - Mathematical back-of-envelope: with 22% random iStall and ID\\n    backpressure roughly uncorrelated, a 2-entry buffer's steady-state\\n    occupancy recovers ~50\\u201370% of the iStall bubbles; expected IPC\\n    lift 4\\u20138% on CoreMark.\\n\\nWhy it should not hurt Fmax:\\n  - The imem request path is unchanged (PC \\u2192 imem_addr). The imem\\n    response no longer fans out to the IF/ID combinational payload\\n    directly; instead it feeds FIFO tail flops and the FIFO head\\n    feeds IF/ID. This is a *shortening* of the post-imem combinational\\n    cone on cycles where the FIFO head is already valid (IF/ID\\n    becomes flop-to-flop rather than mem-port-to-flop through the\\n    flush mux).\\n  - No new path traverses the EX-stage PC resolution. No new 32-bit\\n    comparators added. FIFO pointer logic is 2-entry (single-bit\\n    head/tail), negligible.\\n\\nArea: ~96 bits of state (2 \\u00d7 (32 instr + 32 pc + 1 valid)) plus a\\ntiny control FSM. Budget ~120 LUT4 / 96 FF. Current 5433/10000 LUT\\nleaves plenty of room.\\n\\nRVFI/invariant impact: none. Retirement still happens at MEM/WB.\\nrvfi_order still +1 per retirement. All channel-1 ports stay tied\\noff (single-issue). The 2-channel NRET=2 contract is untouched.\\nmisaligned-branch and misaligned-mem traps still originate in EX/MEM.\\nThe FIFO purely buffers imem responses on their way into ID.\\n\\nRollout guard: unit test `test/test_fetch_buffer.py` exercises\\n(a) zero-wait continuous fetch, (b) periodic iStall with ID\\nconsuming, (c) ID stall with imem ready, (d) redirect flushing\\nboth PC and buffer mid-flight, (e) back-to-back redirects.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/fetch_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 2-entry instruction FIFO holding {pc, instr, valid}. Single-cycle push (on imem response capture when space available) and single-cycle pop (on ID consume). Flush input clears both entries atomically for EX redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Retarget stall_if to gate only the PC register update; drive imem_addr from PC as before; instantiate fetch_buffer and route imem_data into its push port; drive IF/ID combinational bundle (pc, instr, valid) from the FIFO head instead of directly from imem_data. On redirect, assert fetch_buffer.flush and override PC \\u2192 redirect_target in the same cycle (preserving existing priority).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Split stall_if into two conceptually distinct signals: pc_hold (freezes PC reg on load-use / dmem stall / div stall \\u2014 same condition as today's stall_if) and flush_if (IF/ID becomes NOP on redirect OR FIFO-head-not-valid). Add ibuf_pop output = !stall_id && !flush_if && fifo_head_valid to govern FIFO advance. Semantics for downstream stages are identical \\u2014 only the fetch side decouples.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new hazard-unit signals (pc_hold, ibuf_pop) through to if_stage; no change to RVFI port set, no change to channel-1 tie-off, no change to imem/dmem port signatures.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_fetch_buffer.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb suite: zero-wait streaming, periodic iStall with active ID, ID-stall with imem-ready, redirect-during-fill flushes both entries, back-to-back redirect, load-use + iStall coincidence. Uses channel-0 RVFI probes only (single-issue contract).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Extend existing pipeline suite with an iStall-burst scenario (e.g. 50 cycles with pseudo-random 22% iStall driving a known instruction stream) asserting rvfi_order strict-monotonicity, no X/Z on channel-1 ports, and bounded retirement latency (liveness sanity).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/fetch_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 2-entry instruction FIFO holding {pc, instr, valid}. Single-cycle push (on imem response capture when space available) and single-cycle pop (on ID consume). Flush input clears both entries atomically for EX redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Retarget stall_if to gate only the PC register update; drive imem_addr from PC as before; instantiate fetch_buffer and route imem_data into its push port; drive IF/ID combinational bundle (pc, instr, valid) from the FIFO head instead of directly from imem_data. On redirect, assert fetch_buffer.flush and override PC \\u2192 redirect_target in the same cycle (preserving existing priority).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Split stall_if into two conceptually distinct signals: pc_hold (freezes PC reg on load-use / dmem stall / div stall \\u2014 same condition as today's stall_if) and flush_if (IF/ID becomes NOP on redirect OR FIFO-head-not-valid). Add ibuf_pop output = !stall_id && !flush_if && fifo_head_valid to govern FIFO advance. Semantics for downstream stages are identical \\u2014 only the fetch side decouples.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new hazard-unit signals (pc_hold, ibuf_pop) through to if_stage; no change to RVFI port set, no change to channel-1 tie-off, no change to imem/dmem port signatures.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_fetch_buffer.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb suite: zero-wait streaming, periodic iStall with active ID, ID-stall with imem-ready, redirect-during-fill flushes both entries, back-to-back redirect, load-use + iStall coincidence. Uses channel-0 RVFI probes only (single-issue contract).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Extend existing pipeline suite with an iStall-burst scenario (e.g. 50 cycles with pseudo-random 22% iStall driving a known instruction stream) asserting rvfi_order strict-monotonicity, no X/Z on channel-1 ports, and bounded retirement latency (liveness sanity).\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 391.86, \"delta_pct\": 14.9, \"vs_baseline\": 30.17, \"fmax_mhz\": 170.13, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4341607, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5717, \"ff\": 2186, \"seeds\": [170.13, 168.98, 172.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:53:43.000186Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r2s1 (improvement, +14.90%): A 2-entry fetch FIFO between imem response and IF/ID decouples the ~22% random iStall/ID-backpressure pattern that otherwise turns every un-ready fetch cycle into a retire bubble, and since retirement still fires from MEM/WB the change is RVFI/contract-neutral \\u2014 the key structural trick was repacking `if_id_w` from three flat wires (pc/instr/valid) at the top level so Verilator tracks the bypass dependency at bit granularity and the hazard unit's `load_use_hazard`/`ibuf_pop` path doesn't form a UNOPTFLAT loop through `can_accept`; fetch-side area (~96 FF) was affordable only because DIV extraction had already freed LUT budget, so queue-side decoupling is the cheap IPC lever once the PC mux is off-limits.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_alu.py']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Function returns (JALR rs1\\u2208{x1,x5}, rd\\u2209{x1,x5}) are resolved in EX\\ntoday, costing exactly 2 redirect bubbles per return. CoreMark is\\ncall-heavy (core_list_find, matrix_* helpers, CRC inner routines,\\ncore_bench_* wrappers) \\u2014 typical call-depth 2-4, one return per call\\non a warm inner loop. At an estimated 4-8 % of dynamic instructions\\nbeing returns on the perf-marker path, eliminating both bubbles per\\nreturn is an ~8-16 % IPC swing on the parts of the program that are\\ncall-dominated, realistically ~3-7 % overall CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nThe prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2) failed hard (-19.22 %)\\nbecause a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB + bimodal counter table + 33-bit\\npipeline-bundle widening ballooned LUT4 to 14143 (41 % over the\\n10000 budget) and crushed Fmax from 153 \\u2192 102 MHz. The LESSON is not\\n\\\"prediction is infeasible here\\\" \\u2014 it is \\\"sized-by-convention BTBs\\nwith tag comparators and BHT storage don't fit a LUT-tight Gowin\\npart; predictors must be budgeted, not convention-sized.\\\"\\n\\nAfter hyp-002-r1s1 (div_unit extraction) the core sits at LUT4=5433,\\nFmax=153 MHz vs targets of 10000 / 135 MHz \\u2014 ~4500 LUTs and 18 MHz\\nof headroom. A predictor that consumes <5 % of that headroom and\\nbuys >5 % IPC is net-positive even with some Fmax give-back.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) implemented as a small\\nalways_ff register array with a 2-bit stack pointer. Two sites\\ninteract with it:\\n\\n  1. PUSH at ID-stage decode of a CALL.\\n     A CALL is `opcode==0x6F (JAL) && rd \\u2208 {x1, x5}`. When the ID\\n     stage observes this AND the instruction is not being flushed,\\n     push `in.pc + 4` onto the RAS. Push is a pure sequential write\\n     \\u2014 it is NOT on the fetch-PC critical path, so it costs no Fmax.\\n\\n  2. PREDICT + POP at ID-stage decode of a RETURN.\\n     A RETURN is `opcode==0x67 (JALR) && rs1 \\u2208 {x1, x5} && rd \\u2209\\n     {x1, x5}` (the standard RV ABI hint). On detection, the ID\\n     stage:\\n       - Reads the top RAS entry combinationally.\\n       - Asserts a new `ras_redirect` signal into the IF stage and\\n         the hazard unit, with `ras_target = ras[top-1]`.\\n       - Pops the stack (SP--) one cycle later when the RETURN\\n         advances past ID.\\n\\nThe IF-stage PC mux gains one new input with priority\\n`EX_redirect > ras_redirect > pc+4`. Critically, `ras_target` is a\\nREGISTERED value (written at push time) \\u2014 no 32-bit add on the\\npredict path, unlike hyp-001-r1s0's JAL-predict which routed a\\nfresh `imm_J + PC` combinational adder into the PC mux. This is the\\nsingle biggest Fmax-saver versus the r1s0 / r1s2 failures.\\n\\nEX-stage misprediction recovery uses the existing redirect path\\nunchanged: when JALR resolves in EX, if `ex.jump_target !=\\nras_predicted_target_that_was_carried_in_idex`, EX's redirect fires\\nand squashes IF/ID as today \\u2014 2-cycle bubble, same as the\\nno-predictor case. We carry one extra bit (`pred_valid`) and the\\n32-bit `pred_target` through ID/EX so EX can compare. The bundle\\ngrows by 33 bits for ONE payload (id_ex_t) only; EX/MEM and MEM/WB\\ndo not change. This is a 30\\u00d7 smaller bundle-widening footprint than\\nhyp-003-r1s2 (which widened all three inter-stage bundles by 33\\nbits each).\\n\\nRAS corruption on mispredict: we do NOT implement a shadow/checkpoint\\nstack. On a RAS miss the stack is stale, and the next few returns\\nmay also mispredict until calls refill it. For CoreMark's shallow\\ncall chains and ~95 %+ predicted-correct rate on returns, the\\ncascading corruption cost is negligible.\\n\\nSizing math:\\n  - Storage:   4 \\u00d7 32 b (entries) + 2 b (SP) = 130 flops\\n  - Logic:     two tiny decoders (CALL / RETURN pattern match on\\n               opcode[6:0], rd[4:0], rs1[4:0]), one 4:1 mux for\\n               ras-top read, push/pop SP arithmetic, and one extra\\n               input on the IF PC mux. Estimated ~200 LUT4.\\n  - Bundle widening: +33 b on id_ex_t only.\\n  - Expected Fmax give-back: 3-8 MHz (short decode \\u2192 RAS-top-mux\\n               \\u2192 IF-PC-mux chain; no 32-bit adder in the chain).\\n  - Expected IPC gain: 3-7 %.\\n  - Net fitness: +3 % to +8 % with medium confidence.\\n\\nSafety / invariant compliance:\\n  - RVFI channel 0 unchanged, channel 1 remains tied off (single-issue).\\n  - Decoder contract unchanged (RAS is outside the decoder; it\\n    observes instr bits directly for push/pop predicate only \\u2014 no\\n    legality-bit clearing).\\n  - Formal: RAS is purely a speculation-with-recovery mechanism \\u2014\\n    correctness depends solely on EX's always-resolved JALR target\\n    being the retirement truth, which it already is. The\\n    riscv-formal liveness + unique + pc_fwd checks remain proven by\\n    construction because RVFI is driven from MEM/WB, which only\\n    advances on the architecturally-correct path.\\n  - LUT4 budget: 5433 + ~200 \\u2248 5633, well under 10000.\\n  - Fmax budget: 153 - ~8 \\u2248 145 MHz, well above 135 MHz target.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New module: 4-entry Return Address Stack with push/pop ports and a combinational top-of-stack read. Implemented as 4\\u00d732-bit flop array plus 2-bit SP; push writes ras[sp], increments sp; pop decrements sp, reads ras[sp-1]. Saturating on full (overwrite oldest) and empty (pop yields 0, caller must ignore via pred_valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add CALL/RETURN pattern match (opcode + rd + rs1 predicates) on the combinational instr. Drive push_en / push_pc to ras, drive pop_en / pred_valid / pred_target outputs. Extend id_ex_t-carried payload with pred_valid and pred_target fields (see core_pkg.sv).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend id_ex_t with pred_valid (1 bit) and pred_target (32 bits); ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t unchanged. RAS storage type + SP width live inside ras.sv, not the pkg.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ras_redirect / ras_target inputs. Extend the PC-next mux with priority EX_redirect > ras_redirect > pc+4. On ras_redirect, flush the current IF/ID payload (emit NOP) same as the EX-redirect path so the wrong-path instruction already in IF doesn't enter ID.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compare EX-resolved JALR target against carried pred_target when pred_valid. On mismatch, redirect fires as today (existing redirect path). On match, suppress redirect (no flush needed \\u2014 prediction was correct).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend flush_if / flush_id generation to also fire on ras_redirect (treated equivalently to EX redirect for the one cycle it is asserted). No change to stall logic \\u2014 RAS does not introduce new stall conditions.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate u_ras. Wire id_stage \\u2194 ras (push/pop), and id_stage \\u2192 if_stage / hazard_unit for ras_redirect / ras_target. Wire id_ex_w.pred_valid / pred_target through to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_ras.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb test: drive a JAL x1,+0x100 then a matching JALR x0, x1, 0 sequence. Verify the JALR's next-retirement PC equals the JAL fall-through (= RAS prediction) with no EX-redirect fired on the matching case. Additional vector: push-pop imbalance (extra JALR with no preceding JAL) yields ras_empty=1 / pred_valid=0; JALR resolves via EX-redirect as today. Third vector: nested 4-deep calls verify SP wraparound behavior does not corrupt live entries.\"}]}}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\nsv\", \"description\": \"Compute misprediction = (predicted_taken XOR actual_taken) OR (predicted_taken AND actual_taken AND predicted_target != actual_target). Suppress redirect on correct prediction; drive redirect to correct PC on misprediction. Emit BPU-update bundle (pc, taken, target, is_cti) for training.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate bpu; wire lookup port to if_stage, update port from ex_stage. No change to top-level IO or RVFI ports \\u2014 channel 1 stays tied off.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add test_branch_predictor_tight_loop (BNE backward 1000x should complete in ~1000 cycles once warmed) and test_misprediction_recovery (flip branch mid-stream, verify regfile state matches reference ISS).\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 243.18, \"delta_pct\": -19.22, \"vs_baseline\": -19.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 101.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194085, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 14143, \"ff\": 3758, \"seeds\": [101.99, 103.98, 99.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:34:07.431021Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (regression, -19.22%): A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational IF-stage lookup plus a new EX-stage `correct_next_pc != predicted_next_pc` 32-bit comparator widens both the fetch-PC mux and the branch-resolution path simultaneously, and on a LUT-tight (9880/10000) Gowin part the BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles (+33 bits/stage) blow area and Fmax faster than the recovered taken-branch bubbles pay back \\u2014 predictor hypotheses on this target must budget Fmax/LUT cost before IPC gain, and the BTB-index/tag geometry should be sized to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint, not picked by convention.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Share a single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU instantiates THREE separate 64-bit multiplications in\\nparallel every cycle: `mul_ss = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) * $signed({{32{b[31]}},b})`,\\n`mul_uu = {32'b0,a} * {32'b0,b}`, and `mul_su = $signed({{32{a[31]}},a}) *\\n$signed({32'b0,b})`. The case-statement picks one per M-ext op.\\n\\nOn the Tang Nano 20K (Gowin GW2AR-18) a 32x32->64 multiplier maps onto a\\nsmall cluster of 18x18 DSP primitives plus fabric LUTs for the partial-\\nproduct adder tree. Three parallel 64-bit multipliers therefore cost\\nroughly 3x the DSP blocks and triple the fabric add tree, AND all three\\noutputs feed the same output mux inside the ALU's combinational cone \\u2014\\nso the mux/selector LUT depth grows linearly with the number of variants.\\n\\nThis is the Fmax-critical EX-stage cone (the ALU result drives the\\nEX/MEM register capture path in the same cycle). The prior DIV/REM\\nextraction (hyp-20260502-002-r1s1, +13.29%) confirmed that shrinking\\nthis exact cone translates directly to fitness. The three-parallel-\\nmultiplier structure is the largest remaining avoidable slab of logic\\nin that cone, and CoreMark's matrix_mul kernels hit the multiplier\\non the hot path, so keeping MUL/MULH* fully combinational (single-\\ncycle) matters \\u2014 we want area reduction, not pipelining.\\n\\nLUT budget is also tight (prior predictor regression blamed 9880/10000\\nLUT4 pressure), so freeing multiplier area is independently valuable\\nfor Fmax via reduced routing congestion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Collapse the three parallel 64-bit multiplications into a single shared\\n33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign-extensions are selected per\\nop. RV32M semantics map cleanly onto one signed 33x33->66 multiplier:\\n\\n  op       sign_a   sign_b    result slice\\n  MUL      (either \\u2014 low half is invariant to signedness)  low[31:0]\\n  MULHU    0        0         high[63:32]  (unsigned * unsigned)\\n  MULH     a[31]    b[31]     high[63:32]  (signed   * signed)\\n  MULHSU   a[31]    0         high[63:32]  (signed   * unsigned)\\n\\nImplementation plan inside `rtl/alu.sv`:\\n  1. Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with a single `logic signed [65:0]\\n     mul_prod` computed from two 33-bit signed operands:\\n       a_ext = {sign_a & a[31], a};   // 33-bit\\n       b_ext = {sign_b & b[31], b};   // 33-bit\\n       mul_prod = $signed(a_ext) * $signed(b_ext);\\n     where sign_a, sign_b are decoded from `op` combinationally:\\n       MUL    -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0  (unsigned*unsigned; low half matches)\\n       MULH   -> sign_a=1, sign_b=1\\n       MULHU  -> sign_a=0, sign_b=0\\n       MULHSU -> sign_a=1, sign_b=0\\n  2. Case statement now reads `mul_prod[31:0]` for MUL and\\n     `mul_prod[63:32]` for the three high-half variants. Unused\\n     top bits [65:64] of mul_prod are dead-code eliminated by\\n     yosys; silence Verilator UNUSEDSIGNAL locally.\\n  3. ALTOPS branch under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is untouched (the\\n     XOR stand-ins already bypass real arithmetic). This keeps\\n     per-iteration formal BMC tractable exactly as today.\\n  4. `ex_stage.sv` and every other RTL file are unmodified. The\\n     alu_result_final mux for div_unit is unaffected.\\n\\nExpected outcome: ~2x fewer DSP blocks used for MUL*, a visibly\\nshorter output-select LUT chain in the EX cone, and therefore\\nmeasurably higher Fmax plus a smaller LUT4 count. Area reduction\\nalso relieves routing pressure in the LUT-tight 5433/10000 region,\\nwhich has shown second-order Fmax benefits on this target.\\n\\nIPC is unchanged (MUL/MULH* remain single-cycle combinational).\\nRisk surface is confined to a single file and a tight set of four\\nbit-exact operations that the cocotb test_alu.py + cosim diff\\ncover exhaustively (30+ vectors per op) \\u2014 regression on arithmetic\\ncorrectness would fail loudly before FPGA eval.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su with one shared 33x33 signed multiplier; drive operand sign-extensions from op decode; select low/high slice per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Confirm existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vectors still pass; add a handful of signed/unsigned boundary vectors (INT_MIN * -1, -1 * -1, INT_MAX * INT_MAX, mixed-sign MULHSU edge cases) to catch any regression in the sign-extension path.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 327.64, \"delta_pct\": -3.93, \"vs_baseline\": 8.84, \"fmax_mhz\": 147.17, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491817, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5429, \"ff\": 2051, \"seeds\": [169.29, 147.17, 145.03], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:43:33.490819Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (regression, -3.93%): Collapsing three parallel 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier moves the operand-signedness mux *before* the multiplier (an op\\u2192sign_a/sign_b case + AND-with-MSB + sign-extension) serializing onto the DSP input path, and widens operands from 32\\u219233 bits which on Gowin GW2AR-18's 18x18 signed DSP primitives bumps the 2x2 DSP tile to a 3x2/3x3 arrangement with deeper partial-product adder tree; synthesis was already sharing/DCEing unused halves of the three parallel products, so the \\\"3x DSP savings\\\" was largely illusory while the pre-mux on the critical EX cone cost real Fmax \\u2014 shared-operator consolidation only wins when the pre-selection mux is cheaper than the post-selection mux it replaces.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decoupled instruction-fetch FIFO (2-entry) to absorb iStall and ID-side bubbles\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Fitness is measured under the orchestrator's cosim mode with ~22% random\\niStall + dStall (VexRiscv-parity methodology). In the current 5-stage\\npipeline, fetch is directly coupled to ID consumption: when imem_ready=0\\nthe PC register freezes AND the IF/ID combinational payload becomes a NOP,\\nso every iStall cycle is a straight-through pipeline bubble. Symmetrically,\\nany cycle where ID cannot consume (load-use stall, EX redirect target\\nunknown, dmem/div stall propagating upstream) is a cycle where a successful\\nimem fetch \\u2014 if one were possible \\u2014 is discarded. Under 22% random iStall\\nthis pattern of \\\"fetch bubble = retire bubble\\\" costs roughly 22% of peak\\nIPC directly; even a small fetch decoupling buffer should recover a large\\nfraction of that.\\n\\nPrior LESSONS.md entries on the PC path show that widening the fetch-PC\\nmux or adding predictor logic on the critical path has regressed twice\\n(hyp-001 early-redirect, hyp-003 BTB). That argues for a purely *queue-\\nside* decoupling change that leaves the IF\\u2192imem request path unchanged\\nand only adds state downstream of the imem response. There is ~4.5k LUT\\nslack and the core is not LUT-starved after DIV was extracted, so spending\\n~100\\u2013150 LUTs on a small FIFO is affordable if it pays back in IPC.\\n\\nThis is a well-understood structural pattern (Rocket's fetch buffer,\\nVexRiscv's decoupled IBUS plugin, BOOM's fetch queue) and does not touch\\ndecode, EX, or RVFI semantics at all \\u2014 retirement still happens from\\nMEM/WB exactly as before, rvfi_order is still strictly monotonic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Fitness is measured under the orchestrator's cosim mode with ~22% random\\niStall + dStall (VexRiscv-parity methodology). In the current 5-stage\\npipeline, fetch is directly coupled to ID consumption: when imem_ready=0\\nthe PC register freezes AND the IF/ID combinational payload becomes a NOP,\\nso every iStall cycle is a straight-through pipeline bubble. Symmetrically,\\nany cycle where ID cannot consume (load-use stall, EX redirect target\\nunknown, dmem/div stall propagating upstream) is a cycle where a successful\\nimem fetch \\u2014 if one were possible \\u2014 is discarded. Under 22% random iStall\\nthis pattern of \\\"fetch bubble = retire bubble\\\" costs roughly 22% of peak\\nIPC directly; even a small fetch decoupling buffer should recover a large\\nfraction of that.\\n\\nPrior LESSONS.md entries on the PC path show that widening the fetch-PC\\nmux or adding predictor logic on the critical path has regressed twice\\n(hyp-001 early-redirect, hyp-003 BTB). That argues for a purely *queue-\\nside* decoupling change that leaves the IF\\u2192imem request path unchanged\\nand only adds state downstream of the imem response. There is ~4.5k LUT\\nslack and the core is not LUT-starved after DIV was extracted, so spending\\n~100\\u2013150 LUTs on a small FIFO is affordable if it pays back in IPC.\\n\\nThis is a well-understood structural pattern (Rocket's fetch buffer,\\nVexRiscv's decoupled IBUS plugin, BOOM's fetch queue) and does not touch\\ndecode, EX, or RVFI semantics at all \\u2014 retirement still happens from\\nMEM/WB exactly as before, rvfi_order is still strictly monotonic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 2-entry instruction FIFO between the imem response and the\\nIF/ID combinational bundle, decoupling fetch from ID-side backpressure.\\n\\nMechanism:\\n  - New module `fetch_buffer.sv`: 2-entry SRL/flop FIFO holding\\n    {pc[31:0], instr[31:0], valid}. Head feeds IF/ID; tail captures\\n    imem_data when a fetch completes and FIFO has room.\\n  - `if_stage.sv` becomes a thin driver: PC advances (pc+4) whenever\\n    the FIFO has space to accept a new response (i.e. a fetch request\\n    may complete this cycle). The imem_addr output is still just the\\n    current PC \\u2014 request is in-flight when imem_ready=1 AND space\\n    available; the response word is written into the FIFO tail at the\\n    end of the same cycle (zero-wait semantics preserved).\\n  - Hazard interface is unchanged externally: stall_if continues to\\n    freeze the PC register on load-use / dmem stall / div stall, but\\n    now it does NOT have to stall the FIFO drain \\u2014 ID can keep pulling\\n    buffered instructions while PC is held and imem is idle. The\\n    `stall_if` wire is retargeted at the PC register only; a new\\n    `ibuf_pop` (ID consumes head) governs FIFO advance.\\n  - Redirect: on EX redirect, both the PC register and the FIFO are\\n    flushed atomically; imem_addr becomes redirect_target next cycle.\\n    This is identical in latency to the current redirect path \\u2014 no\\n    extra PC-mux tier is introduced.\\n  - flush_if on IF/ID combinational output becomes: \\\"FIFO empty OR\\n    redirect this cycle\\\" \\u2014 emits NOP/invalid into ID. Load-use bubble\\n    injection still lives in hazard_unit via flush_id; the fetch\\n    buffer plays no role in ID/EX register control.\\n\\nWhy it should help (under 22% iStall methodology):\\n  - When imem_ready=0 but FIFO has \\u22651 buffered instruction, ID still\\n    consumes a valid instruction that cycle \\u2014 an iStall bubble\\n    converts to zero bubbles.\\n  - When ID stalls (load-use, dmem stall) and imem_ready=1, the FIFO\\n    continues filling up to its 2-entry capacity; those buffered\\n    instructions pre-pay for subsequent iStall cycles.\\n  - Mathematical back-of-envelope: with 22% random iStall and ID\\n    backpressure roughly uncorrelated, a 2-entry buffer's steady-state\\n    occupancy recovers ~50\\u201370% of the iStall bubbles; expected IPC\\n    lift 4\\u20138% on CoreMark.\\n\\nWhy it should not hurt Fmax:\\n  - The imem request path is unchanged (PC \\u2192 imem_addr). The imem\\n    response no longer fans out to the IF/ID combinational payload\\n    directly; instead it feeds FIFO tail flops and the FIFO head\\n    feeds IF/ID. This is a *shortening* of the post-imem combinational\\n    cone on cycles where the FIFO head is already valid (IF/ID\\n    becomes flop-to-flop rather than mem-port-to-flop through the\\n    flush mux).\\n  - No new path traverses the EX-stage PC resolution. No new 32-bit\\n    comparators added. FIFO pointer logic is 2-entry (single-bit\\n    head/tail), negligible.\\n\\nArea: ~96 bits of state (2 \\u00d7 (32 instr + 32 pc + 1 valid)) plus a\\ntiny control FSM. Budget ~120 LUT4 / 96 FF. Current 5433/10000 LUT\\nleaves plenty of room.\\n\\nRVFI/invariant impact: none. Retirement still happens at MEM/WB.\\nrvfi_order still +1 per retirement. All channel-1 ports stay tied\\noff (single-issue). The 2-channel NRET=2 contract is untouched.\\nmisaligned-branch and misaligned-mem traps still originate in EX/MEM.\\nThe FIFO purely buffers imem responses on their way into ID.\\n\\nRollout guard: unit test `test/test_fetch_buffer.py` exercises\\n(a) zero-wait continuous fetch, (b) periodic iStall with ID\\nconsuming, (c) ID stall with imem ready, (d) redirect flushing\\nboth PC and buffer mid-flight, (e) back-to-back redirects.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/fetch_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 2-entry instruction FIFO holding {pc, instr, valid}. Single-cycle push (on imem response capture when space available) and single-cycle pop (on ID consume). Flush input clears both entries atomically for EX redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Retarget stall_if to gate only the PC register update; drive imem_addr from PC as before; instantiate fetch_buffer and route imem_data into its push port; drive IF/ID combinational bundle (pc, instr, valid) from the FIFO head instead of directly from imem_data. On redirect, assert fetch_buffer.flush and override PC \\u2192 redirect_target in the same cycle (preserving existing priority).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Split stall_if into two conceptually distinct signals: pc_hold (freezes PC reg on load-use / dmem stall / div stall \\u2014 same condition as today's stall_if) and flush_if (IF/ID becomes NOP on redirect OR FIFO-head-not-valid). Add ibuf_pop output = !stall_id && !flush_if && fifo_head_valid to govern FIFO advance. Semantics for downstream stages are identical \\u2014 only the fetch side decouples.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new hazard-unit signals (pc_hold, ibuf_pop) through to if_stage; no change to RVFI port set, no change to channel-1 tie-off, no change to imem/dmem port signatures.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_fetch_buffer.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb suite: zero-wait streaming, periodic iStall with active ID, ID-stall with imem-ready, redirect-during-fill flushes both entries, back-to-back redirect, load-use + iStall coincidence. Uses channel-0 RVFI probes only (single-issue contract).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Extend existing pipeline suite with an iStall-burst scenario (e.g. 50 cycles with pseudo-random 22% iStall driving a known instruction stream) asserting rvfi_order strict-monotonicity, no X/Z on channel-1 ports, and bounded retirement latency (liveness sanity).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/fetch_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 2-entry instruction FIFO holding {pc, instr, valid}. Single-cycle push (on imem response capture when space available) and single-cycle pop (on ID consume). Flush input clears both entries atomically for EX redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Retarget stall_if to gate only the PC register update; drive imem_addr from PC as before; instantiate fetch_buffer and route imem_data into its push port; drive IF/ID combinational bundle (pc, instr, valid) from the FIFO head instead of directly from imem_data. On redirect, assert fetch_buffer.flush and override PC \\u2192 redirect_target in the same cycle (preserving existing priority).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Split stall_if into two conceptually distinct signals: pc_hold (freezes PC reg on load-use / dmem stall / div stall \\u2014 same condition as today's stall_if) and flush_if (IF/ID becomes NOP on redirect OR FIFO-head-not-valid). Add ibuf_pop output = !stall_id && !flush_if && fifo_head_valid to govern FIFO advance. Semantics for downstream stages are identical \\u2014 only the fetch side decouples.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new hazard-unit signals (pc_hold, ibuf_pop) through to if_stage; no change to RVFI port set, no change to channel-1 tie-off, no change to imem/dmem port signatures.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_fetch_buffer.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb suite: zero-wait streaming, periodic iStall with active ID, ID-stall with imem-ready, redirect-during-fill flushes both entries, back-to-back redirect, load-use + iStall coincidence. Uses channel-0 RVFI probes only (single-issue contract).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Extend existing pipeline suite with an iStall-burst scenario (e.g. 50 cycles with pseudo-random 22% iStall driving a known instruction stream) asserting rvfi_order strict-monotonicity, no X/Z on channel-1 ports, and bounded retirement latency (liveness sanity).\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 391.86, \"delta_pct\": 14.9, \"vs_baseline\": 30.17, \"fmax_mhz\": 170.13, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4341607, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5717, \"ff\": 2186, \"seeds\": [170.13, 168.98, 172.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T22:53:43.000186Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r2s1 (improvement, +14.90%): A 2-entry fetch FIFO between imem response and IF/ID decouples the ~22% random iStall/ID-backpressure pattern that otherwise turns every un-ready fetch cycle into a retire bubble, and since retirement still fires from MEM/WB the change is RVFI/contract-neutral \\u2014 the key structural trick was repacking `if_id_w` from three flat wires (pc/instr/valid) at the top level so Verilator tracks the bypass dependency at bit granularity and the hazard unit's `load_use_hazard`/`ibuf_pop` path doesn't form a UNOPTFLAT loop through `can_accept`; fetch-side area (~96 FF) was affordable only because DIV extraction had already freed LUT budget, so queue-side decoupling is the cheap IPC lever once the PC mux is off-limits.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_alu.py']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Function returns (JALR rs1\\u2208{x1,x5}, rd\\u2209{x1,x5}) are resolved in EX\\ntoday, costing exactly 2 redirect bubbles per return. CoreMark is\\ncall-heavy (core_list_find, matrix_* helpers, CRC inner routines,\\ncore_bench_* wrappers) \\u2014 typical call-depth 2-4, one return per call\\non a warm inner loop. At an estimated 4-8 % of dynamic instructions\\nbeing returns on the perf-marker path, eliminating both bubbles per\\nreturn is an ~8-16 % IPC swing on the parts of the program that are\\ncall-dominated, realistically ~3-7 % overall CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nThe prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2) failed hard (-19.22 %)\\nbecause a 32-entry direct-mapped BTB + bimodal counter table + 33-bit\\npipeline-bundle widening ballooned LUT4 to 14143 (41 % over the\\n10000 budget) and crushed Fmax from 153 \\u2192 102 MHz. The LESSON is not\\n\\\"prediction is infeasible here\\\" \\u2014 it is \\\"sized-by-convention BTBs\\nwith tag comparators and BHT storage don't fit a LUT-tight Gowin\\npart; predictors must be budgeted, not convention-sized.\\\"\\n\\nAfter hyp-002-r1s1 (div_unit extraction) the core sits at LUT4=5433,\\nFmax=153 MHz vs targets of 10000 / 135 MHz \\u2014 ~4500 LUTs and 18 MHz\\nof headroom. A predictor that consumes <5 % of that headroom and\\nbuys >5 % IPC is net-positive even with some Fmax give-back.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) implemented as a small\\nalways_ff register array with a 2-bit stack pointer. Two sites\\ninteract with it:\\n\\n  1. PUSH at ID-stage decode of a CALL.\\n     A CALL is `opcode==0x6F (JAL) && rd \\u2208 {x1, x5}`. When the ID\\n     stage observes this AND the instruction is not being flushed,\\n     push `in.pc + 4` onto the RAS. Push is a pure sequential write\\n     \\u2014 it is NOT on the fetch-PC critical path, so it costs no Fmax.\\n\\n  2. PREDICT + POP at ID-stage decode of a RETURN.\\n     A RETURN is `opcode==0x67 (JALR) && rs1 \\u2208 {x1, x5} && rd \\u2209\\n     {x1, x5}` (the standard RV ABI hint). On detection, the ID\\n     stage:\\n       - Reads the top RAS entry combinationally.\\n       - Asserts a new `ras_redirect` signal into the IF stage and\\n         the hazard unit, with `ras_target = ras[top-1]`.\\n       - Pops the stack (SP--) one cycle later when the RETURN\\n         advances past ID.\\n\\nThe IF-stage PC mux gains one new input with priority\\n`EX_redirect > ras_redirect > pc+4`. Critically, `ras_target` is a\\nREGISTERED value (written at push time) \\u2014 no 32-bit add on the\\npredict path, unlike hyp-001-r1s0's JAL-predict which routed a\\nfresh `imm_J + PC` combinational adder into the PC mux. This is the\\nsingle biggest Fmax-saver versus the r1s0 / r1s2 failures.\\n\\nEX-stage misprediction recovery uses the existing redirect path\\nunchanged: when JALR resolves in EX, if `ex.jump_target !=\\nras_predicted_target_that_was_carried_in_idex`, EX's redirect fires\\nand squashes IF/ID as today \\u2014 2-cycle bubble, same as the\\nno-predictor case. We carry one extra bit (`pred_valid`) and the\\n32-bit `pred_target` through ID/EX so EX can compare. The bundle\\ngrows by 33 bits for ONE payload (id_ex_t) only; EX/MEM and MEM/WB\\ndo not change. This is a 30\\u00d7 smaller bundle-widening footprint than\\nhyp-003-r1s2 (which widened all three inter-stage bundles by 33\\nbits each).\\n\\nRAS corruption on mispredict: we do NOT implement a shadow/checkpoint\\nstack. On a RAS miss the stack is stale, and the next few returns\\nmay also mispredict until calls refill it. For CoreMark's shallow\\ncall chains and ~95 %+ predicted-correct rate on returns, the\\ncascading corruption cost is negligible.\\n\\nSizing math:\\n  - Storage:   4 \\u00d7 32 b (entries) + 2 b (SP) = 130 flops\\n  - Logic:     two tiny decoders (CALL / RETURN pattern match on\\n               opcode[6:0], rd[4:0], rs1[4:0]), one 4:1 mux for\\n               ras-top read, push/pop SP arithmetic, and one extra\\n               input on the IF PC mux. Estimated ~200 LUT4.\\n  - Bundle widening: +33 b on id_ex_t only.\\n  - Expected Fmax give-back: 3-8 MHz (short decode \\u2192 RAS-top-mux\\n               \\u2192 IF-PC-mux chain; no 32-bit adder in the chain).\\n  - Expected IPC gain: 3-7 %.\\n  - Net fitness: +3 % to +8 % with medium confidence.\\n\\nSafety / invariant compliance:\\n  - RVFI channel 0 unchanged, channel 1 remains tied off (single-issue).\\n  - Decoder contract unchanged (RAS is outside the decoder; it\\n    observes instr bits directly for push/pop predicate only \\u2014 no\\n    legality-bit clearing).\\n  - Formal: RAS is purely a speculation-with-recovery mechanism \\u2014\\n    correctness depends solely on EX's always-resolved JALR target\\n    being the retirement truth, which it already is. The\\n    riscv-formal liveness + unique + pc_fwd checks remain proven by\\n    construction because RVFI is driven from MEM/WB, which only\\n    advances on the architecturally-correct path.\\n  - LUT4 budget: 5433 + ~200 \\u2248 5633, well under 10000.\\n  - Fmax budget: 153 - ~8 \\u2248 145 MHz, well above 135 MHz target.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New module: 4-entry Return Address Stack with push/pop ports and a combinational top-of-stack read. Implemented as 4\\u00d732-bit flop array plus 2-bit SP; push writes ras[sp], increments sp; pop decrements sp, reads ras[sp-1]. Saturating on full (overwrite oldest) and empty (pop yields 0, caller must ignore via pred_valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add CALL/RETURN pattern match (opcode + rd + rs1 predicates) on the combinational instr. Drive push_en / push_pc to ras, drive pop_en / pred_valid / pred_target outputs. Extend id_ex_t-carried payload with pred_valid and pred_target fields (see core_pkg.sv).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend id_ex_t with pred_valid (1 bit) and pred_target (32 bits); ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t unchanged. RAS storage type + SP width live inside ras.sv, not the pkg.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ras_redirect / ras_target inputs. Extend the PC-next mux with priority EX_redirect > ras_redirect > pc+4. On ras_redirect, flush the current IF/ID payload (emit NOP) same as the EX-redirect path so the wrong-path instruction already in IF doesn't enter ID.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compare EX-resolved JALR target against carried pred_target when pred_valid. On mismatch, redirect fires as today (existing redirect path). On match, suppress redirect (no flush needed \\u2014 prediction was correct).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend flush_if / flush_id generation to also fire on ras_redirect (treated equivalently to EX redirect for the one cycle it is asserted). No change to stall logic \\u2014 RAS does not introduce new stall conditions.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate u_ras. Wire id_stage \\u2194 ras (push/pop), and id_stage \\u2192 if_stage / hazard_unit for ras_redirect / ras_target. Wire id_ex_w.pred_valid / pred_target through to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_ras.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb test: drive a JAL x1,+0x100 then a matching JALR x0, x1, 0 sequence. Verify the JALR's next-retirement PC equals the JAL fall-through (= RAS prediction) with no EX-redirect fired on the matching case. Additional vector: push-pop imbalance (extra JALR with no preceding JAL) yields ras_empty=1 / pred_valid=0; JALR resolves via EX-redirect as today. Third vector: nested 4-deep calls verify SP wraparound behavior does not corrupt live entries.\"}]}}\n","exit":0,"description":"Search for past predictor attempts","truncated":false},"title":"Search for past predictor attempts","time":{"start":1777762623810,"end":1777762623812}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deae8dd62001aB92egwUxKJUXz","sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","messageID":"msg_deae8c6b9001V3jqoGIPlFk6Fe"}}
