{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762732778,"sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BYG76e3Cj4rBrZhb1MGsM9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r3s2\ntitle: \"4-entry Return Address Stack to eliminate JALR-return bubbles\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Function returns (JALR with rs1 ∈ {x1,x5}, rd ∉ {x1,x5} — the standard\n  RV ABI RET pattern) are resolved in EX today, costing exactly 2 redirect\n  bubbles per return. CoreMark is call-heavy: core_list_find, the matrix_*\n  helpers, CRC inner routines, core_bench_* wrappers all make calls on the\n  perf-marker hot path. Typical call-depth is 2-4; with ~4-8% of dynamic\n  instructions being returns on the perf-marker path, eliminating both\n  bubbles per return is ~3-7% overall CoreMark IPC uplift.\n\n  The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2) lost -19.22% because a\n  32-entry direct-mapped BTB + bimodal counters + 33-bit widening of\n  ALL three pipeline bundles + a new 32-bit EX-stage target comparator\n  balloonned LUT4 to 14143 (41% over budget) and crushed Fmax from 153\n  → 102 MHz. The lesson was NOT \"prediction is infeasible\" — it was\n  \"sized-by-convention BTBs with pre-decode tag comparators on the IF\n  critical path don't fit a LUT-tight Gowin part.\"\n\n  The prior r2s2 slot tried essentially this RAS approach but was\n  rolled back because the agent modified off-limits test/test_alu.py.\n  The hypothesis itself was never evaluated. This round revives the\n  approach with stricter file-scope guardrails.\n\n  Current state after hyp-002-r2s1 (fetch buffer) gave +14.90%: LUT4\n  5717/10000, Fmax 170.13 MHz. About 4283 LUTs and 35 MHz of headroom\n  — plenty of room for a small, targeted predictor that consumes\n  <5% of that budget.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) that predicts JALR-return\n  targets in the ID stage using a registered (not combinationally\n  computed) value, avoiding the adder-on-PC-mux path that killed the\n  prior JAL-in-ID attempt (hyp-001-r1s0, -1.67%).\n\n  Key structural differences from the r1s2 BTB failure that justify\n  medium confidence:\n\n    1. Target comes from a flop, not a 32-bit adder.\n       The RAS entries are pc+4 values written at push (call) time,\n       read combinationally at pop (return) time. The ID→IF redirect\n       path is: id_is_return_decode → 4:1-mux-over-RAS-entries → IF\n       PC mux. No 32-bit add in the chain — in contrast to r1s0's\n       JAL-in-ID which put pc+J_imm combinationally on the PC mux.\n\n    2. Only id_ex_t widens; ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t are unchanged.\n       We carry (pred_valid, pred_target) = 33 bits through ID/EX only\n       so EX can validate on JALR resolve. That's 1 bundle × 33 bits\n       vs the r1s2 BTB's 3 bundles × 33 bits each — 3× smaller bundle\n       footprint.\n\n    3. No BTB-style tag comparator on the fetch PC.\n       The RAS predicate is a 5-bit opcode match + rs1/rd register-\n       number compares on the ID-stage instr bits. Those bits are\n       already available combinationally in ID (imm_gen reads them).\n       No new LUT tier on the fetch PC fanout.\n\n    4. 100% architectural predictability.\n       Returns to their matching call have probability 1 of being\n       correct — the only misprediction source is RAS underflow\n       (tail call chain exceeding 4 entries) or RAS corruption after\n       a mispredict. CoreMark call depth is typically 2-4, well\n       within a 4-entry RAS. Expected correct-prediction rate ≥95%.\n\n    5. Small: 4 × 32 b entries + 2 b SP = 130 FFs; push/pop decode\n       + top-of-stack mux ≈ 200 LUT4. Under <5% of the 4283-LUT\n       and 35-MHz-Fmax headroom.\n\n  Implementation outline (all inside cores/bench/rtl/ and a new\n  cocotb file test/test_ras.py — no modifications to any off-limits\n  paths, including test/test_alu.py which the prior r2s2 attempt\n  incorrectly touched):\n\n    rtl/ras.sv (new module):\n      Ports: clock, reset, push_en, push_pc (pc+4 at push site),\n             pop_en, top_valid, top_pc.\n      Storage: ras[0..3][31:0] regs + sp[1:0] pointer + depth[2:0]\n               saturating counter (0..4).\n      Behavior:\n        - push_en: ras[sp] ← push_pc; sp ← sp + 1 (mod 4);\n                   depth ← min(depth+1, 4).\n        - pop_en:  sp ← sp - 1 (mod 4); depth ← max(depth-1, 0).\n        - top_pc ← ras[sp-1] (combinational read at pop site).\n        - top_valid ← (depth != 0).\n      Both push and pop in the same cycle cancel (net sp unchanged)\n      and top_pc holds its prior value. This is the pure-ISS model —\n      no shadow/checkpoint stack; mispredicts corrupt the stack\n      until enough subsequent calls refill it.\n\n    rtl/core_pkg.sv:\n      Extend ctrl_t with is_call (1 b) and is_return (1 b) — set\n      in the decoder based on JAL/JALR opcode + rd/rs1 predicates.\n      These two bits ride the ctrl_t bundle for zero additional\n      struct-member plumbing.\n      Extend id_ex_t only with pred_valid (1 b) and pred_target\n      (32 b). ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t unchanged — pred metadata is\n      consumed in EX and need not survive to MEM.\n\n    rtl/decoder.sv:\n      Inside the existing JAL arm (7'b1101111): is_call ← (rd==5'd1\n      || rd==5'd5); is_return ← 0.\n      Inside the existing JALR arm (7'b1100111, funct3==3'd0):\n        is_call   ← (rd  == 5'd1 || rd  == 5'd5);\n        is_return ← (rs1 == 5'd1 || rs1 == 5'd5)\n                 && (rd  != 5'd1 && rd  != 5'd5);\n      (The RV ABI hint: JALR consumes {x1,x5} source implies a\n      return, unless destination is also {x1,x5} in which case it's\n      a register-indirect call, preferably also pushing. The\n      predicate above matches the RAS hint from RISC-V Unprivileged\n      Spec §2.5.) is_illegal handling is UNTOUCHED — the default\n      = 1 and the clearing-only-on-validated-match discipline\n      (CLAUDE.md invariant 10) stays intact.\n\n    rtl/id_stage.sv:\n      Drive ras.push_en = in.valid && !flush && !stall && is_call\n                         && (rd_of_instr in {x1, x5}).\n      Drive ras.pop_en  = in.valid && !flush && !stall && is_return.\n      Capture pred_valid = is_return && ras.top_valid, pred_target\n      = ras.top_pc into the id_ex_t outgoing payload.\n      Assert ras_redirect into if_stage on pred_valid, with\n      ras_target = ras.top_pc. This is combinational from decoder\n      + ras-top-mux.\n\n    rtl/if_stage.sv:\n      Add ras_redirect / ras_target inputs. PC-next mux priority\n      becomes: reset > ex_redirect > ras_redirect > push_valid ? pc+4 :\n      pc_q. Fetch buffer's flush is extended to fire on ras_redirect\n      as well (same as ex_redirect — both squash the wrong-path\n      in-flight fetch).\n\n    rtl/ex_stage.sv:\n      On JALR resolve (in.ctrl.is_jalr): if in.pred_valid and\n      in.pred_target == jump_target (the architecturally resolved\n      JALR target), the existing redirect fires NOT — suppressed\n      because the IF path is already on the predicted target.\n      If in.pred_valid and mismatch, redirect fires as today\n      (2-cycle bubble, recovery identical to baseline).\n      If !in.pred_valid, behavior is unchanged (existing redirect\n      path). The comparator is a 32-bit eq; it sits next to the\n      existing jump_target computation — no new 32-bit adder, just\n      a compare-and-suppress on the existing redirect wire.\n\n    rtl/hazard_unit.sv:\n      flush_id extended to fire on ras_redirect as well as ex_redirect\n      (same semantics — IF/ID becomes a bubble). ibuf_pop is not\n      affected (pop already happens when ID captures a valid inst,\n      which a return does, so the return consumes the FIFO head as\n      today). No new stall conditions.\n\n    rtl/core.sv:\n      Instantiate u_ras. Wire id_stage ↔ ras (push/pop), and\n      id_stage → if_stage / hazard_unit for ras_redirect / ras_target.\n      Route id_ex_w.pred_valid / id_ex_w.pred_target down to ex_stage.\n\n  Tests (NEW cocotb file only — no modification of existing tests):\n    test/test_ras.py (new):\n      - test_ras_basic_call_return: JAL x1, +0x100; ADDI (pad);\n        JALR x0, x1, 0 — assert the JALR does NOT trigger an\n        EX redirect (ras_redirect handled it) and the next retiring\n        inst's PC equals the JAL fall-through.\n      - test_ras_nested_depth_4: 4-deep nested call/return chain\n        — all four returns prediction-correct.\n      - test_ras_overflow_depth_5: 5-deep nesting — innermost four\n        returns predicted, outermost one mispredicts via EX redirect\n        (stack underflow detected via depth==0 on pop).\n      - test_ras_mispredict_recovery: corrupt stack by JALR with a\n        non-matching rs1 — architectural state matches the reference\n        ISS (the EX redirect takes us to the correct target).\n      - test_ras_rvfi_unchanged: run 100 random instructions, assert\n        rvfi_order strict-monotonic +1, rvfi_valid_1 always 0, no\n        X/Z on any channel-1 port (single-issue contract preserved).\n\n  Invariant compliance:\n    - Inv 1 (2-channel RVFI): unchanged. Single-issue; channel 1 tied.\n    - Inv 2 (trap = illegal): decoder still defaults is_illegal=1;\n      is_call / is_return are SEPARATE bits from is_illegal and do\n      not alter the clearing discipline.\n    - Inv 3 (EBREAK only legal SYSTEM): untouched.\n    - Inv 4 (rvfi_order strict +1): retirement still from MEM/WB,\n      unchanged; ras_redirect just squashes wrong-path fetches\n      before they retire.\n    - Inv 5 (liveness): on mispredict we fall back to the existing\n      EX redirect path — same as baseline. No new stall conditions\n      that could deadlock.\n    - Inv 5b (M-ext correctness): alu.sv untouched.\n    - Inv 6 (mem bounds): untouched.\n    - Inv 7/8/9 (CoreMark): retirement unchanged → CRCs unchanged.\n    - Inv 10 (decoder default illegal): untouched.\n\n  Risk surface and mitigations:\n    - Fmax risk: ID→RAS-top-mux→IF-PC-mux adds a priority tier to\n      the fetch-PC mux. The tier is registered-value-to-mux (no\n      combinational add) so depth is ~1 LUT4. If Fmax regresses\n      more than ~5% we'd see it in the 3-seed nextpnr result.\n    - RAS corruption: tail-call chains >4 corrupt the stack.\n      CoreMark's maximum observed call depth from disassembly is 3\n      — well within capacity.\n    - JALR that's not a return (register-indirect call): if is_call\n      and is_return both false for JALR (e.g. rd=x0, rs1=x7), the\n      RAS is neither pushed nor popped; existing EX redirect handles\n      it. No regression.\n\n  Expected outcome:\n    - IPC lift: +3-7% on CoreMark from eliminating 2-bubble return\n      penalty on ~4-8% of retired insts at ≥95% RAS hit rate.\n    - Fmax: -1 to -4% from the extra PC-mux tier.\n    - LUT4: +~200 (5717 → ~5900).\n    - Net fitness: +2-5%, medium confidence.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ras.sv\n    description: \"New module: 4-entry Return Address Stack with 2-bit sp + saturating depth counter. Ports: clock, reset, push_en, push_pc, pop_en, top_valid, top_pc. Push writes ras[sp] and increments sp; pop decrements sp and exposes ras[sp-1] combinationally. Simultaneous push+pop cancel. No shadow/checkpoint — mispredict corrupts stack until refilled.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend ctrl_t with is_call (1 bit) and is_return (1 bit) to carry JAL/JALR-return hints through the pipeline. Extend id_ex_t only with pred_valid (1 bit) and pred_target (32 bits). ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t are UNCHANGED.\"\n  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n    description: \"Inside the existing JAL arm set is_call=(rd==x1||rd==x5), is_return=0. Inside the existing JALR arm set is_call=(rd in {x1,x5}) and is_return=(rs1 in {x1,x5} && rd not in {x1,x5}) per RISC-V RAS hint spec. is_illegal clearing discipline untouched (default still 1; only cleared inside validated opcode/funct arms).\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Drive ras.push_en on valid decoded CALLs and ras.pop_en on valid decoded RETURNs (both gated by !stall && !flush). Assert ras_redirect to if_stage when is_return && ras.top_valid, with ras_target = ras.top_pc. Capture pred_valid and pred_target into the outgoing id_ex_t payload so EX can validate on JALR resolve.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add ras_redirect / ras_target inputs. PC-next mux priority becomes reset > ex_redirect > ras_redirect > push_valid ? pc+4. Extend fetch_buffer.flush to also fire on ras_redirect so wrong-path fetches are squashed identically to the ex_redirect path.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"On JALR resolve with in.pred_valid, compare in.pred_target == jump_target. On match, suppress redirect (prediction was correct, IF is already on the right path). On mismatch, fire redirect as today. No new 32-bit adder — only a 32-bit eq-compare next to the existing jump_target path.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Extend flush_id to fire on ras_redirect equivalently to ex_redirect (IF/ID captures a bubble). No new stall conditions; ibuf_pop logic unchanged — a return inst still pops the FIFO head as today.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate u_ras. Wire id_stage ↔ ras (push_en, push_pc, pop_en, top_valid, top_pc) and id_stage → if_stage / hazard_unit for ras_redirect / ras_target. Route id_ex_w.pred_valid / pred_target to ex_stage. No change to top-level IO, RVFI port set (channel 1 stays tied off), imem/dmem port signatures, or the retirement path from MEM/WB.\"\n  - file: test/test_ras.py\n    description: \"NEW cocotb suite (do not touch any existing test file, especially test_alu.py which caused r2s2 rollback). Vectors: (1) basic JAL/JALR pair, assert no EX-redirect and correct retirement PC; (2) 4-deep nested call/return, all returns predicted; (3) 5-deep overflow, outermost mispredicts via EX redirect path, arch state matches reference; (4) non-matching JALR (indirect call pattern), behavior unchanged from baseline; (5) 100 random insts, assert rvfi_order strict +1, rvfi_valid_1=0, no X/Z on any channel-1 port.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777762732768,"end":1777762732776}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I see the RAS approach from the previous attempt was actually viable—it uses ID-stage decode to avoid critical path issues and pulls targets from registered entries—but it failed because the hypothesis agent modified files it shouldn't have, so the approach itself never got properly evaluated.\n\nThe real concern is that any ID→IF redirect path risks the same regression that killed the JAL-in-ID attempt, though that was only -1.67% which might be recoverable. But with the fetch buffer now in place, there's an opportunity: I could precompute JAL targets when instructions arrive at the fetch buffer and store them alongside the instruction data, so when ID pops an entry, the redirect is based on already-stored values rather than combinational decode logic. Or even simpler—integrate a lightweight BTB at the fetch buffer level that stores precomputed targets for each of the two buffered entries.\n\nThe key insight is moving the JAL adder from the IF→ID critical path (which killed Fmax before) to the push path where it sits before a flop register, breaking the combinational chain. But I need to trace through the pipeline timing carefully: when ID pops a JAL in cycle N and needs to redirect IF to the target, IF is already fetching for cycle N+1, so the redirect has to propagate back and flush the fetch buffer while replacing the PC.\n\nActually, storing the precomputed target in each FIFO entry means ID can drive the PC directly on a JAL pop—the target comes from a flop, not combinational logic. This is essentially using the FIFO as a trace cache, trading a wider PC mux for breaking the critical path. It's conceptually similar to the r1s0 approach but with the adder moved earlier, which might actually be viable.\n\nLooking at the ROI across all options, RAS seems like the most targeted win: it only widens id_ex_t, keeps the target registered, and avoids the large validation cost of a BTB. The r2s2 attempt failed due to modifying off-limits files, not the hypothesis itself. I should revive it with a cleaner approach—stick to cocotb tests and leave the ALU tests alone. Since predictors can only improve bubbles (never hurt them), the real risk is Fmax drop or LUT overflow, but RAS should stay under budget at ~200 LUT and ~130 FF with an expected net gain of 3-5%. The RAS approach is much leaner than the prior BTB widening—it only adds 33 bits to one pipeline stage instead of three, and the LUT budget is comfortably within limits at around 200 LUTs. Time to formalize this as the hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deae976d3001SIXkTfat5pbr75","sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","messageID":"msg_deae8e1b60016EI8IWtZZ0XsCu"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777762732792,"sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","part":{"id":"prt_deae967e7001O4XfRKelAZvLdh","messageID":"msg_deae8e1b60016EI8IWtZZ0XsCu","sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","type":"text","text":"Looking at the history carefully, I can see:\n- hyp-003-r1s2 (32-entry BTB): -19.22% — too large, widened PC mux + EX 32-bit comparator + 3 pipeline bundles\n- hyp-001-r1s0 (JAL-in-ID): -1.67% — combinational adder on ID→IF redirect path\n- hyp-003-r2s2 (RAS): broken because the agent modified off-limits `test/test_alu.py` — hypothesis itself never evaluated\n\nThe RAS approach from r2s2 is architecturally sound and was blocked by agent misbehavior, not by hypothesis merit. Key advantages vs the failed BTB:\n- Target comes from a **registered** RAS entry (no 32-bit adder on predict path)\n- Only id_ex_t widens (not all 3 bundles → 3× smaller bundle cost)\n- 4 entries × 32 bits = ~130 flops (vs 32-entry BTB's ~2000+ bits)\n- 100% predictable workload (returns always match calls, modulo RAS depth)\n- CoreMark is call-heavy (core_list_find, matrix helpers, CRC routines)\n\nLUT budget is healthy now (5717/10000 = 4283 free) after fetch-buffer+DIV extraction.\n\nLet me write this hypothesis with clear constraints to avoid r2s2's agent-failure mode.","time":{"start":1777762658279,"end":1777762732791}}}
