{"type":"text","timestamp":1777762742367,"sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","part":{"id":"prt_deaea9933001IBC18is41XyXSx","messageID":"msg_deaea8b92001lN2w2xVDob3Vy4","sessionID":"ses_215194d4affeiJxGaKE3bxWylb","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: A 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) to predict JALR-return targets from a **registered** value (not a combinational adder), avoiding the PC-mux adder path that killed hyp-001-r1s0, and the 3-bundle + 32-bit tag comparator weight that killed the r1s2 BTB.\n\nKey differences from prior failed predictor attempts:\n1. Target from flop, not adder (vs r1s0's pc+J_imm combinational)\n2. Only `id_ex_t` widens by 33 bits — 3× smaller bundle footprint than the r1s2 BTB\n3. No IF-stage BTB tag comparator; predicate is simple decoder-side opcode+rd/rs1 match\n4. ~200 LUT4 + ~130 FF (vs the r1s2 BTB's ~8400 LUT4 over-budget)\n5. 100%-predictable workload: returns-to-matching-calls, ≥95% accuracy at CoreMark's shallow call depth\n\nPrior r2s2 slot attempted this same concept but was rolled back because the agent modified off-limits `test/test_alu.py` — this proposal explicitly scopes tests to a new `test/test_ras.py` file.","time":{"start":1777762736435,"end":1777762742366}}}
