{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762592775,"sessionID":"ses_215180ec9ffe1VAkuriDx3NWc9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_011x3RyvDBnwWQ1v552Fcm7W","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0/cores/bench/rtl/reg_file.sv","content":"// rtl/reg_file.sv\n//\n// 32 x 32 RV32I integer register file.\n//   - x0 hardwired to zero (writes silently dropped via the in-storage\n//     write-guard, reads always 0 via the combinational read-port mux).\n//   - Two combinational read ports.\n//   - Single synchronous write port.\n//   - Write-first bypass: a same-cycle write to the read address returns\n//     the new value via an explicit combinational mux on the read path.\n//\n// Storage-shape note (micro_opt hypothesis): the regs[] array has NO\n// synchronous reset. Gowin Yosys + synth will only infer distributed\n// LUTRAM (SPX9 / SDPB-pair) for a 32x32 2R1W memory when the storage\n// has no reset net. The prior `if (reset) for (int i; i<32; i++) regs[i]\n// <= 0;` forced 32x32=1024 discrete flops plus two LUT-mux trees for the\n// read ports. By dropping the storage-level reset we let synth map the\n// array to distributed RAM; architectural correctness does not depend\n// on post-reset contents because:\n//   (a) x0 is hardwired to 0 via the read-port mux (below), independent\n//       of regs[0]'s stored value — and the always_ff write-guard\n//       (`w_en && w_addr != 0`) ensures regs[0] is never written after\n//       any program-originated regfile write, which in any case is\n//       functionally moot because the read-port mux short-circuits\n//       addr==0 to 32'b0 before regs[0] is ever consulted.\n//   (b) non-x0 pre-write reads are a program-level UB; crt0 and\n//       CoreMark both write every live register before reading it.\n//\n// Write-first bypass stays EXTERNAL to the storage block because\n// Gowin's 2R1W distributed RAM does not natively emit write-first on\n// same-cycle-read — encoding it as an explicit mux on the read path\n// (`(w_en && w_addr == rs_addr) ? w_data : ram_read`) keeps the RAM\n// block a clean read-first / write-after-read shape and the bypass\n// becomes a couple of LUT4s on each read port.\n//\n// Latency:        write = 1 cycle (synchronous), read = combinational.\n// RVFI fields:    feeds rs1_rdata, rs2_rdata, rd_wdata.\nmodule reg_file (\n  input  logic        clock,\n  // reset is retained on the port for top-level wiring compatibility,\n  // but is deliberately unused inside — see storage-shape note above.\n  /* verilator lint_off UNUSEDSIGNAL */\n  input  logic        reset,\n  /* verilator lint_on UNUSEDSIGNAL */\n\n  input  logic [4:0]  rs1_addr,\n  input  logic [4:0]  rs2_addr,\n  output logic [31:0] rs1_data,\n  output logic [31:0] rs2_data,\n\n  input  logic        w_en,\n  input  logic [4:0]  w_addr,\n  input  logic [31:0] w_data\n);\n\n  logic [31:0] regs [0:31];\n\n  // Storage array: single synchronous write, no reset. The x0 write-guard\n  // is kept INSIDE the always_ff (not merely gated externally on w_en)\n  // so regs[0] is never captured; Gowin synth still recognises this as\n  // a conditional write — the LUTRAM inference pattern tolerates a\n  // write-enable that depends on the write address.\n  always_ff @(posedge clock) begin\n    if (w_en && w_addr != 5'b0) begin\n      regs[w_addr] <= w_data;\n    end\n  end\n\n  // Combinational read ports with the x0 short-circuit outermost (so the\n  // RAM cell output is not on the critical path for reads of x0) and the\n  // write-first bypass as an explicit mux between the x0 mux and the\n  // RAM output.\n  always_comb begin\n    if (rs1_addr == 5'b0)\n      rs1_data = 32'b0;\n    else if (w_en && w_addr == rs1_addr)\n      rs1_data = w_data;\n    else\n      rs1_data = regs[rs1_addr];\n\n    if (rs2_addr == 5'b0)\n      rs2_data = 32'b0;\n    else if (w_en && w_addr == rs2_addr)\n      rs2_data = w_data;\n    else\n      rs2_data = regs[rs2_addr];\n  end\n\nendmodule\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0/cores/bench/rtl/reg_file.sv","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/rtl/reg_file.sv","time":{"start":1777762592765,"end":1777762592775}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I need to update the `reset_clears_all` test since we're removing the reset functionality from the register file. The plan is to remove reset from the storage array while keeping x0 hardwired through the read-port mux, maintaining write-first bypass, and keeping the write-guard logic inside the storage always_ff block. For the tests, I'm adjusting the reset case to verify that x0 still returns 0 without relying on reset.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deae822c3001hrL5aLOlpqxklh","sessionID":"ses_215180ec9ffe1VAkuriDx3NWc9","messageID":"msg_deae80f62001BA11WpqYXLiCb2"}}
