{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777762750207,"sessionID":"ses_215154959ffe4lYe6Fozu7Hu6G","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01UAKVrvvipg7AFTFax2GXiC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"cat cores/bench/LESSONS.md 2>/dev/null | head -100","description":"Check lessons learned"},"output":"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r1s0 (regression, +1.67%): ID-stage JAL early-redirect adds a decode→J-imm-add→IF-PC-mux combinational path plus a new priority tier (EX>ID>pc+4) on the Fmax-critical fetch PC selection; the per-JAL bubble savings on CoreMark's call-heavy inner loops don't offset the Fmax/area cost, so \"IPC-only\" optimizations on the PC path are rarely free.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r1s1 (improvement, +13.29%): Combinational `/` and `%` synthesize to a ~32-level restoring-divider tree that dominates both EX critical path and LUT4 area on DSP-less Gowin parts, and since CoreMark hits DIV/REM a handful of times (mostly outside timing markers), pulling them into an iterative 32-cycle `div_unit` with hazard-unit stall is a near-pure Fmax/area win — always keep the ALTOPS branch identical in `alu.sv` so formal BMC stays tractable.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (regression, -19.22%): A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational IF-stage lookup plus a new EX-stage `correct_next_pc != predicted_next_pc` 32-bit comparator widens both the fetch-PC mux and the branch-resolution path simultaneously, and on a LUT-tight (9880/10000) Gowin part the BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles (+33 bits/stage) blow area and Fmax faster than the recovered taken-branch bubbles pay back — predictor hypotheses on this target must budget Fmax/LUT cost before IPC gain, and the BTB-index/tag geometry should be sized to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint, not picked by convention.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (regression, -3.93%): Collapsing three parallel 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier moves the operand-signedness mux *before* the multiplier (an op→sign_a/sign_b case + AND-with-MSB + sign-extension) serializing onto the DSP input path, and widens operands from 32→33 bits which on Gowin GW2AR-18's 18x18 signed DSP primitives bumps the 2x2 DSP tile to a 3x2/3x3 arrangement with deeper partial-product adder tree; synthesis was already sharing/DCEing unused halves of the three parallel products, so the \"3x DSP savings\" was largely illusory while the pre-mux on the critical EX cone cost real Fmax — shared-operator consolidation only wins when the pre-selection mux is cheaper than the post-selection mux it replaces.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r2s1 (improvement, +14.90%): A 2-entry fetch FIFO between imem response and IF/ID decouples the ~22% random iStall/ID-backpressure pattern that otherwise turns every un-ready fetch cycle into a retire bubble, and since retirement still fires from MEM/WB the change is RVFI/contract-neutral — the key structural trick was repacking `if_id_w` from three flat wires (pc/instr/valid) at the top level so Verilator tracks the bypass dependency at bit granularity and the hazard unit's `load_use_hazard`/`ibuf_pop` path doesn't form a UNOPTFLAT loop through `can_accept`; fetch-side area (~96 FF) was affordable only because DIV extraction had already freed LUT budget, so queue-side decoupling is the cheap IPC lever once the PC mux is off-limits.\n","metadata":{"output":"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r1s0 (regression, +1.67%): ID-stage JAL early-redirect adds a decode→J-imm-add→IF-PC-mux combinational path plus a new priority tier (EX>ID>pc+4) on the Fmax-critical fetch PC selection; the per-JAL bubble savings on CoreMark's call-heavy inner loops don't offset the Fmax/area cost, so \"IPC-only\" optimizations on the PC path are rarely free.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r1s1 (improvement, +13.29%): Combinational `/` and `%` synthesize to a ~32-level restoring-divider tree that dominates both EX critical path and LUT4 area on DSP-less Gowin parts, and since CoreMark hits DIV/REM a handful of times (mostly outside timing markers), pulling them into an iterative 32-cycle `div_unit` with hazard-unit stall is a near-pure Fmax/area win — always keep the ALTOPS branch identical in `alu.sv` so formal BMC stays tractable.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (regression, -19.22%): A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational IF-stage lookup plus a new EX-stage `correct_next_pc != predicted_next_pc` 32-bit comparator widens both the fetch-PC mux and the branch-resolution path simultaneously, and on a LUT-tight (9880/10000) Gowin part the BTB storage + tag comparator + widened pipeline bundles (+33 bits/stage) blow area and Fmax faster than the recovered taken-branch bubbles pay back — predictor hypotheses on this target must budget Fmax/LUT cost before IPC gain, and the BTB-index/tag geometry should be sized to the CoreMark hot-loop PC footprint, not picked by convention.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (regression, -3.93%): Collapsing three parallel 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier moves the operand-signedness mux *before* the multiplier (an op→sign_a/sign_b case + AND-with-MSB + sign-extension) serializing onto the DSP input path, and widens operands from 32→33 bits which on Gowin GW2AR-18's 18x18 signed DSP primitives bumps the 2x2 DSP tile to a 3x2/3x3 arrangement with deeper partial-product adder tree; synthesis was already sharing/DCEing unused halves of the three parallel products, so the \"3x DSP savings\" was largely illusory while the pre-mux on the critical EX cone cost real Fmax — shared-operator consolidation only wins when the pre-selection mux is cheaper than the post-selection mux it replaces.\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r2s1 (improvement, +14.90%): A 2-entry fetch FIFO between imem response and IF/ID decouples the ~22% random iStall/ID-backpressure pattern that otherwise turns every un-ready fetch cycle into a retire bubble, and since retirement still fires from MEM/WB the change is RVFI/contract-neutral — the key structural trick was repacking `if_id_w` from three flat wires (pc/instr/valid) at the top level so Verilator tracks the bypass dependency at bit granularity and the hazard unit's `load_use_hazard`/`ibuf_pop` path doesn't form a UNOPTFLAT loop through `can_accept`; fetch-side area (~96 FF) was affordable only because DIV extraction had already freed LUT budget, so queue-side decoupling is the cheap IPC lever once the PC mux is off-limits.\n","exit":0,"description":"Check lessons learned","truncated":false},"title":"Check lessons learned","time":{"start":1777762750206,"end":1777762750207}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deaeace4e001BY8POkLKBFc9vS","sessionID":"ses_215154959ffe4lYe6Fozu7Hu6G","messageID":"msg_deaeac6d9001cFukgKyw6fNW6F"}}
